euai:ARTICLE_3_50_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 3(50)"@en ;
    skos:definition "**ARTICLE 3(50)** serves as the formal definition and regulatory reference point for the term \"Personal Data.\" It establishes the foundational legal meaning of what constitutes personal data within the relevant framework, ensuring that the term is clearly defined and consistently applicable. By acting as the definitive source for this terminology, Article 3(50) provides the necessary guidance and clarity for interpreting how personal information is categorized and handled under the applicable re"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_3_51_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 3(51)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Definition of non-personal data"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_3_52_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 3(52)"@en ;
    skos:definition "**ARTICLE 3(52)** serves as the authoritative definition and legal reference for the term \"profiling.\" Within the context of the relevant regulatory framework, this provision formally establishes what constitutes profiling, ensuring a standardized understanding for its application in legal and compliance matters. By defining this concept, ARTICLE 3(52) provides the necessary foundation for organizations and entities to identify and regulate activities that involve the automated processing of per"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_40_AND_41 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 40 AND 41"@en ;
    skos:definition "References to harmonised standards or common specifications conferring a presumption of conformity"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_41 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 41"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ARTICLE 41**

Article 41 serves as a critical regulatory provision concerning the use and implementation of common specifications within the relevant legal framework. Primarily, this article outlines the formal process and specific conditions under which the Commission is authorized to adopt implementing acts for these common specifications.

Beyond establishing this procedural framework, Article 41 functions as a key reference point for manufacturers. It defines how these common specification"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_10_OF_REGULATION__EU__NO_1025_2012 .

euai:ARTICLE_45 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 45"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specifies the information obligations of notified bodies, requiring them to inform notifying and other notified bodies about certification decisions."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_46 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 46"@en ;
    skos:definition "Defines the derogation from conformity assessment procedures for high-risk AI systems under exceptional circumstances of public security or life/health protection."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_48 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 48"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article defining the requirements for affixing the CE marking."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_49_1_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 49(1)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 49(1) delineates the registration obligations specifically applicable to providers of high-risk AI systems. This article establishes the regulatory requirements that these providers must adhere to concerning the registration of their high-risk AI systems."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_49_3_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 49(3)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Provision detailing the specific information deployers must submit to the EU database regarding high-risk AI systems"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_4_1_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 4(1)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Reference for Personal Data definition in GDPR"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_4_1__OF_DIRECTIVE__EU__2016_680 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 4(1) OF DIRECTIVE (EU) 2016/680"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article setting principles for data processing including lawfulness, fairness, transparency, and purpose limitation (Recital 94)"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_4_3__OF_DIRECTIVE__EU__2019_790 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 4(3) OF DIRECTIVE (EU) 2019/790"@en ;
    skos:definition """Article 4(3) of Directive (EU) 2019/790 serves as a critical legal provision concerning copyright protection, specifically addressing the reservation of rights by rightsholders. Under this article, service providers are required to adhere to specific rules regarding the use of protected content, particularly within the context of training artificial intelligence models or data mining.

The provision establishes a clear mechanism through which rightsholders can opt out of or restrict the use of t"""@en .

euai:ARTICLE_4_4_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 4(4)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Reference for Profiling definition in GDPR"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_52 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 52"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article detailing the procedure for notifying, designating, and reassessing GPAI models with systemic risk"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_53_1__A_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 53(1)(A)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 53(1)(a) is a provision within the EU AI Act that establishes a specific regulatory obligation for providers of general-purpose AI models. Under this article, these providers are mandated to create, draw up, and maintain comprehensive technical documentation concerning their models. This requirement ensures that there is a documented record of the model's development, capabilities, and underlying technical framework, which is essential for compliance and oversight within the scope of the"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_56_6_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 56(6)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article referencing the procedure for the Commission to approve codes of practice"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_5_1__H__III_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 5(1)(H)(III)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Provision within the AI Act referencing criminal offences, which triggers specific legal considerations for AI usage in law enforcement contexts."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_5_PROHIBITIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 5 PROHIBITIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "The section of the AI Act outlining prohibited AI practices due to unacceptable risk"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_5_TEU a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 5 TEU"@en ;
    skos:definition "Reference to the Treaty on European Union regarding the principle of subsidiarity and proportionality (Recital 176)"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_62 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 62"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article concerning measures for support of SMEs and start-ups"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_63 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 63"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 63 functions as a regulatory provision that governs derogations for specific operators, specifically targeting microenterprises. This article outlines the specific exemptions or special conditions applicable to these smaller business entities, particularly in the context of their quality management systems."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_64 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 64"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article establishing and defining the AI Office"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_65 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 65"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article establishing and defining the structure of the European Artificial Intelligence Board"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_66 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 66"@en ;
    skos:definition "The article defining the specific tasks and functions of the European Artificial Intelligence Board."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_68 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 68"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 68 establishes the scientific panel composed of independent experts. This article details the panel's structure, including its specific composition, the tasks it is mandated to perform, and the operating requirements it must adhere to. Furthermore, the article clarifies that the members serving on this panel function in the capacity of independent experts."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:SCIENTIFIC_PANEL .

euai:ARTICLE_6_1_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 6(1)"@en ;
    skos:definition "**ARTICLE 6(1)** serves as a critical regulatory provision within the legal framework governing artificial intelligence. This article is primarily responsible for defining the criteria used to classify AI systems as \"high-risk.\" In addition to establishing these classification standards, **ARTICLE 6(1)** sets forth specific obligations that must be met by these high-risk AI systems. Notably, the application of these requirements is subject to a deferred timeline, with the provisions set to becom"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_113 .

euai:ARTICLE_6_TEU a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 6 TEU"@en ;
    skos:definition "Reference to the Charter of Fundamental Rights as a standard for AI development"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_7 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 7"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 7 is the section of the regulation that governs the amendment of Annex III, specifically outlining the procedures and criteria that the Commission must follow when modifying the list of high-risk AI systems contained therein."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_70 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 70"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 70 serves as the regulatory provision governing the designation and operational framework of national competent authorities and single points of contact. This article establishes the legal requirements for appointing these entities, defining their roles and outlining the specific operational mandates they must fulfill to ensure effective compliance and coordination."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_74 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 74"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article governing market surveillance and control of AI systems in the Union market"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_74_11_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 74(11)"@en ;
    skos:definition "ARTICLE 74(11) serves as a regulatory reference concerning cross-border market surveillance activities. Specifically, this article provides the framework regarding joint activities undertaken by market surveillance authorities, which are supported and facilitated by the Board."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_74_9_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 74(9)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article specifying the market surveillance authorities designated to access technical documentation"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_75_3_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 75(3)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article regarding the powers of the AI Office and national competent authorities, referenced in Article 88(2)"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_76 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 76"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article establishing supervision of testing in real-world conditions by market surveillance authorities"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_77 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 77"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article defining the powers of authorities protecting fundamental rights regarding high-risk AI systems."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_77_1_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 77(1)"@en ;
    skos:definition "**ARTICLE 77(1)** serves as a regulatory reference that outlines the requirements for information sharing concerning serious incidents. Specifically, it mandates that market surveillance authorities must notify certain national public authorities or bodies when such incidents occur. Furthermore, this article encompasses provisions related to the involvement of specific national public authorities or bodies that are tasked with the protection of fundamental rights. In essence, ARTICLE 77(1) estab"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_78 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 78"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ARTICLE 78** is a provision within the relevant Regulation that establishes comprehensive confidentiality obligations. It serves to define the requirements for maintaining the secrecy and protection of information or documentation obtained during the course of official duties.

Specifically, **ARTICLE 78** applies to various entities, including national competent authorities, authorities, and other persons involved in the execution of the Regulation. It governs the handling of information obta"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_113 .

euai:ARTICLE_7_1_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 7(1)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article providing conditions for adding or modifying use-cases in Annex III"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_7_2_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 7(2)"@en ;
    skos:definition "**Article 7(2)** serves as a regulatory provision that establishes the essential criteria for evaluating risks associated with AI systems, specifically within the context of amending Annex III. This article outlines a framework for assessing potential risks to ensure that any adjustments to the classification or regulation of these systems are grounded in objective factors. Key elements considered in this evaluation include the intensity of the potential harm, the degree of dependency that indiv"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_7_3_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 7(3)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 7(3) is a provision that empowers the European Commission to adopt delegated acts for the purpose of removing specific high-risk AI systems from the scope of Annex III, provided that certain conditions are met. This mechanism allows for the flexibility to adjust the classification of high-risk AI systems as the regulatory landscape and technology evolve."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_80 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 80"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article detailing the procedure for dealing with AI systems misclassified by the provider as non-high-risk"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_79 .

euai:ARTICLE_82 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 82"@en ;
    skos:definition "**ARTICLE 82** concerns high-risk AI systems that, despite being formally compliant with the Regulation, still present significant risks. This article serves as a mechanism to address these exceptional cases, ensuring that compliance with standard regulatory requirements does not preclude the identification and mitigation of actual or potential dangers posed by these advanced technologies."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_84 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 84"@en ;
    skos:definition "**ARTICLE 84** pertains to the framework for Union AI testing support activities, specifically addressing the designation and responsibilities of the relevant support structures. It outlines the mandate for these entities to facilitate the testing of artificial intelligence systems, ensuring that there is a formal and organized approach to evaluating AI technologies within the Union. By defining both the status and the specific tasks of these Union AI testing support structures, Article 84 estab"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_85 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 85"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 85 establishes the fundamental right for any person to lodge a formal complaint with a market surveillance authority concerning potential infringements. By providing this legal mechanism, the article ensures that individuals have a recognized pathway to report violations, thereby facilitating oversight and enforcement within the market surveillance framework."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_86 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 86"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 86 is a specific provision within the relevant regulatory framework that establishes the right for individuals to receive an explanation regarding decision-making processes. Specifically, it guarantees that persons affected by high-risk AI systems are entitled to a clear and understandable explanation of the decisions made by those systems, ensuring transparency and accountability in automated individual decision-making."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_8_15 rdfs:label "ARTICLE 8 15"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_90 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 90"@en ;
    skos:definition "**ARTICLE 90** serves as the regulatory provision that governs and establishes the formal procedure for the scientific panel to issue alerts regarding potential systemic risks associated with artificial intelligence. This article outlines the specific mechanisms through which the scientific panel communicates such concerns, ensuring that the AI Office is properly notified of any identified systemic risks. By codifying this reporting process, Article 90 provides a structured framework for oversig"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_90_1__A_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 90(1)(A)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article referenced for qualified alerts from the scientific panel regarding systemic risks"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_93 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 93"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ARTICLE 93**

Article 93 is a regulatory provision that outlines the specific measures requested by the European Commission and the associated commitments made by providers. It functions as a critical component of the enforcement framework, establishing accountability for providers, specifically including providers of General Purpose AI (GPAI) models. 

Failure to comply with the measures requested under Article 93 carries significant consequences, as non-compliance can lead to the imposition """@en .

euai:ARTICLE_95 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 95"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article governing the creation and voluntary application of codes of conduct for AI systems"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_98 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 98"@en ;
    skos:definition "**Article 98** serves as the regulatory provision that establishes and governs the committee procedure designed to assist the European Commission in its functions. By outlining the framework for this committee procedure, Article 98 ensures a structured approach for the Commission to receive necessary support and oversight during its decision-making and implementation processes."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_99_1_ rdfs:label "ARTICLE 99 1"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_9_2_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 9(2)"@en ;
    skos:definition "**ARTICLE 9(2)** serves as a critical legal reference point within regulatory frameworks, addressing two primary domains: the governance of personal data usage and the management of risks associated with Artificial Intelligence (AI) systems. In its capacity regarding data protection, Article 9(2) outlines the specific legal bases and conditions under which the processing of personal data is permissible. Simultaneously, in the context of AI governance, Article 9(2) functions as a crucial referenc"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_9_OF_REGULATION__EU__2016_679 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 9 OF REGULATION (EU) 2016/679"@en ;
    skos:definition "Regulation referenced regarding the processing of biometric data for purposes other than law enforcement"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_9_TO_15_AND_72_TO_73 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 9 TO 15 AND 72 TO 73"@en ;
    skos:definition "A cluster of articles representing key obligations (e.g., risk management, data governance, human oversight) that microenterprises must still fulfill despite simplified quality management systems."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_R23_OF_ANNEX_I_TO_DECISION_768_2008_EC a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE R23 OF ANNEX I TO DECISION 768/2008/EC"@en ;
    skos:definition "Reference to the legal basis for the electronic notification tool used by national competent authorities"@en .

euai:ASSESSMENT_DOCUMENTATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "ASSESSMENT DOCUMENTATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty for a provider to draw up documentation demonstrating why an AI system is considered non-high-risk before the system is placed on the market or put into service."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:NATIONAL_COMPETENT_AUTHORITY .

euai:AUTHORISATION_DECISION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "AUTHORISATION DECISION"@en ;
    skos:definition "A formal decision by the Commission regarding the justification of a conformity assessment body's authorisation when objections have been raised, addressed to the Member State and the body."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:EUROPEAN_COMMISSION .

euai:AUTOMATICALLY_GENERATED_LOGS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "AUTOMATICALLY GENERATED LOGS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Logs generated by high-risk AI systems that providers must keep for at least six months, governed by Article 19."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_19 .

euai:AWARENESS_COMMUNICATION_CAMPAIGNS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "AWARENESS COMMUNICATION CAMPAIGNS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty of the AI Office to organize communication campaigns to raise awareness about obligations arising from the Regulation."@en .

euai:BENCHMARKS_AND_MEASUREMENT_METHODOLOGIES rdfs:label "BENCHMARKS AND MEASUREMENT METHODOLOGIES"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:METROLOGY_AND_BENCHMARKING_AUTHORITIES .

euai:BEST_PRACTICE_EVALUATION_IN_PROCUREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "BEST PRACTICE EVALUATION IN PROCUREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty of the AI Office to evaluate and promote the convergence of best practices in public procurement regarding AI systems."@en .

euai:BIOMETRIC_CATEGORISATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ClassificationRule ;
    rdfs:label "BIOMETRIC CATEGORISATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The process of assigning natural persons to specific categories (sex, age, hair colour, eye colour, tattoos, behavioural or personality traits, language, religion, membership of a national minority, sexual or political orientation) based on biometric data."@en .

euai:BIOMETRIC_CATEGORISATION_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "BIOMETRIC CATEGORISATION EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The prohibition on biometric categorisation does not cover labelling or filtering of lawfully acquired biometric datasets or categorising biometric data in the area of law enforcement."@en .

euai:BIOMETRIC_CATEGORISATION_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "BIOMETRIC CATEGORISATION SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition """A **Biometric Categorisation System** is defined as an AI system designed to assign natural persons to specific categories (such as sex, age, race, religion, political opinions, or sexual orientation) based on their biometric data. The core function of these systems is to identify or categorize individuals using biometric inputs.

The regulatory framework surrounding these systems is nuanced, distinguishing between acceptable use, high-risk status, and outright prohibition based on the nature of"""@en ;
    euai:alwaysClassifiedAs euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM ;
    euai:belongsToCategory euai:AISYSTEM ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_3_40_,
        euai:RECITAL_16 ;
    euai:hasException euai:BIOMETRIC_CATEGORISATION_EXCLUSION ;
    euai:regulatedBy euai:PROHIBITION_OF_BIOMETRIC_CATEGORISATION_SYSTEMS ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:ANCILLARY_FEATURE_EXCLUSION,
        euai:BIOMETRICS,
        euai:BIOMETRIC_CATEGORISATION,
        euai:PROHIBITED_AI_PRACTICE ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ARTICLE_5,
        euai:INFORMATION_OBLIGATION .

euai:BIOMETRIC_CATEGORISATION_SYSTEMS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "BIOMETRIC CATEGORISATION SYSTEMS"@en ;
    skos:definition """Biometric categorisation systems are AI-powered technologies that process the biometric data of natural persons to classify them based on specific characteristics. Due to the potential risks these systems pose to fundamental rights and privacy, they are subject to strict regulatory oversight.

Broadly, these systems are defined by their capacity to categorize individuals based on biometric data, and they face specific restrictions, particularly within the context of police and judicial cooperati"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:PROHIBITED_AI_PRACTICE,
        euai:RECITAL_30 ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:PROHIBITION_OF_AI_PRACTICES .

euai:BIOMETRIC_DATA_PROCESSING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "BIOMETRIC DATA PROCESSING"@en ;
    skos:definition "Obligation for law enforcement to comply with Article 10 of Directive (EU) 2016/680 when using AI systems for biometric identification (Recital 94)"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_4_1__OF_DIRECTIVE__EU__2016_680,
        euai:ARTICLE_9_OF_REGULATION__EU__2016_679 ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ARTICLE_10_OF_DIRECTIVE__EU__2016_680 .

euai:BIOMETRIC_IDENTIFICATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "BIOMETRIC IDENTIFICATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "**BIOMETRIC IDENTIFICATION** is defined as the automated recognition of specific human physical, physiological, or behavioral features—such as facial characteristics, gait patterns, or heart rate—for the purpose of establishing an individual's identity. This process functions by comparing collected biometric data against a reference database. Crucially, BIOMETRIC IDENTIFICATION encompasses these recognition activities in all instances, regardless of whether the individual has provided consent, a"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_15 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:BIOMETRIC_DATA .

euai:BIOMETRIC_IDENTIFICATION_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "BIOMETRIC IDENTIFICATION SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "A **Biometric Identification System** is a specific category of high-risk artificial intelligence system designed to establish an individual's identity. This process is accomplished by comparing biometric data—such as facial recognition, voice patterns, or gait analysis—against a reference database, regardless of whether the individual has provided consent. Notably, this definition excludes biometric verification or authentication systems that are strictly used for access control, such as unlock"@en ;
    euai:belongsToCategory euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM ;
    euai:isExemptFromHighRisk euai:BIOMETRIC_VERIFICATION_EXCLUSION ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:BIOMETRIC_DATA,
        euai:REFERENCE_DATABASE ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ENHANCED_HUMAN_OVERSIGHT_REQUIREMENT .

euai:BIOMETRIC_VERIFICATION_PURPOSE rdfs:label "BIOMETRIC VERIFICATION PURPOSE"@en .

euai:CAPABILITY_BENCHMARK a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "CAPABILITY BENCHMARK"@en ;
    skos:definition "Evaluations of model capabilities including task execution without additional training, adaptability to new tasks, level of autonomy, scalability, and access to external tools."@en .

euai:CAPITAL_REQUIREMENT_CALCULATION_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "CAPITAL REQUIREMENT CALCULATION EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Condition under which capital requirement calculation systems are not classified as high-risk under this Regulation"@en .

euai:CERTIFICATE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CERTIFICATE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A document issued by a notified body confirming conformity of an AI system; subject to validity periods and revocation/suspension clauses"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_44 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_I,
        euai:ANNEX_III,
        euai:ANNEX_VII .

euai:CESSATION_OF_ACTIVITIES_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CESSATION OF ACTIVITIES OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "If a notified body ceases activities, it must inform the notifying authority and providers at least one year in advance for planned cessations"@en .

euai:CHAPTER_2_OF_TITLE_V_TEU a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "CHAPTER 2 OF TITLE V TEU"@en ;
    skos:definition """Chapter 2 of Title V of the Treaty on European Union (TEU) functions as the foundational legal framework governing the Union's Common Security and Defence Policy (CSDP). This section of the treaty establishes the operational and policy parameters for how the European Union approaches matters of collective security and defense. 

Beyond its general role in outlining the Union’s defence policy, Chapter 2 of Title V TEU is frequently cited as a significant legal instrument in contemporary policy de"""@en .

euai:CHAPTER_4_OR_CHAPTER_5_OF_TITLE_V_OF_PART_THREE_OF_THE_TFEU a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "CHAPTER 4 OR CHAPTER 5 OF TITLE V OF PART THREE OF THE TFEU"@en ;
    skos:definition "Legal framework defining areas of police cooperation and judicial cooperation in criminal matters where Ireland has specific positionings regarding the AI Act"@en .

euai:CHAPTER_III a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "CHAPTER III"@en ;
    skos:definition "Refers to the section of the Act setting out requirements for high-risk AI systems, conformity with which is a condition for source code access"@en .

euai:CHAPTER_III_SECTION_2_REQUIREMENTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "CHAPTER III SECTION 2 REQUIREMENTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Technical and organisational requirements for AI systems, the voluntary application of which is encouraged by codes of conduct"@en .

euai:CHAPTER_VI a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "CHAPTER VI"@en ;
    skos:definition "Refers to the specific chapter in Regulation (EU) 2019/1020 regarding market surveillance procedures that applies mutatis mutandis"@en .

euai:CIVIL_SOCIETY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "CIVIL SOCIETY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Groups and stakeholders engaged by the AI Office to inform the development of systemic risk assessment frameworks."@en .

euai:CIVIL_SOCIETY_ORGANISATIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "CIVIL SOCIETY ORGANISATIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Civil society organisations are formally recognised as key stakeholders within the regulatory framework governing the development of codes of practice and conduct. They are integrated into the legislative process to ensure diverse perspectives are represented during the drafting phases. Specifically, as outlined in Article 56(3), civil society organisations are invited to support and contribute to the process of drawing up codes of practice. Furthermore, in accordance with Article 95(3), they ar"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CODE_OF_CONDUCT,
        euai:CODE_OF_PRACTICE .

euai:CLASSIFICATION_RULE rdfs:label "CLASSIFICATION RULE"@en .

euai:CLOSED_DATA_SET a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "CLOSED DATA SET"@en ;
    skos:definition "Constraint requiring post-remote biometric identification to be based on legally acquired video footage rather than indiscriminate surveillance (Recital 95)"@en .

euai:COMMISSION_DECISION_C_2024__390 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "COMMISSION DECISION C(2024) 390"@en ;
    skos:definition "Commission Decision C(2024) 390 is an official act enacted by the European Commission on January 24, 2024. Its primary purpose is to establish the European Artificial Intelligence Office. This decision is also referenced in Recital 45 of related regulatory documentation."@en .

euai:COMMISSION_DELEGATED_ACT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:DelegatedAct ;
    rdfs:label "COMMISSION DELEGATED ACT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Acts adopted by the Commission to modify or align existing Union harmonisation legislation with the technical requirements of the AI Act."@en ;
    euai:modifies euai:UNION_HARMONISATION_LEGISLATION .

euai:COMMISSION_EVALUATION_AND_REVIEW a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "COMMISSION EVALUATION AND REVIEW"@en ;
    skos:definition "The duty of the Commission to evaluate and review the Regulation by 2 August 2029 and every four years thereafter, as well as annual assessments of high-risk lists, as per Recital 174"@en .

euai:COMMITTEE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "COMMITTEE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A Committee is an entity established under the framework of Article 98, operating within the meaning of Regulation (EU) No 182/2011. Its primary purpose is to assist the European Commission in the process of implementing acts."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_98 .

euai:COMMON_RULES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "COMMON RULES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Implementing acts established by the Commission to mandate obligations from Articles 53 and 55 if a code of practice is not finalized or is deemed inadequate by 2 August 2025"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_53,
        euai:ARTICLE_55 .

euai:COMMON_RULES_FOR_AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOXES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "COMMON RULES FOR AI REGULATORY SANDBOXES"@en ;
    skos:definition "A unified framework for the implementation and operation of sandboxes across the Union"@en .

euai:COMMON_SPECIFICATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "COMMON SPECIFICATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "A set of technical specifications as defined in Article 2, point (4) of Regulation (EU) No 1025/2012 that provides means to comply with certain requirements established under this Regulation."@en .

euai:COMPARISON_OF_BIOMETRIC_DATA a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "COMPARISON OF BIOMETRIC DATA"@en ;
    skos:definition "A core functional requirement for the Eurodac system to identify persons."@en .

euai:COMPETENCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "COMPETENCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific requirement for notified bodies to possess the necessary expertise and technical capability"@en .

euai:COMPETENCE_AND_RESOURCE_REQUIREMENTS rdfs:label "COMPETENCE AND RESOURCE REQUIREMENTS"@en .

euai:COMPETENCE_EVIDENCE rdfs:label "COMPETENCE EVIDENCE"@en .

euai:COMPETENT_MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "COMPETENT MARKET SURVEILLANCE AUTHORITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific authority to whom real-world testing plans must be submitted"@en .

euai:COMPETENT_PERSONNEL_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "COMPETENT PERSONNEL REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for notifying authorities to maintain an adequate number of competent personnel with expertise in information technologies, AI, law, and fundamental rights, as per Article 29(7)"@en .

euai:COMPETENT_PERSONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "COMPETENT PERSONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Persons within a notifying authority who make notification decisions, distinct from those who assessed the conformity assessment bodies"@en .

euai:COMPETITION_AUTHORITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "COMPETITION AUTHORITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "National authorities that receive annual reports regarding market surveillance information of potential interest for competition rules"@en .

euai:COMPETITIVE_ADVANTAGE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:RiskCategory ;
    rdfs:label "COMPETITIVE ADVANTAGE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The scenario where a provider gains an unfair market position by applying lower copyright standards than those required in the Union; this is a regulatory concern addressed by the Act"@en .

euai:COMPLIANCE_QUESTIONNAIRE_TEMPLATE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "COMPLIANCE QUESTIONNAIRE TEMPLATE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A tool developed by the AI Office to assist deployers in meeting their obligations and reduce administrative burden"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DEPLOYER .

euai:COMPLIANCE_WITH_SECTION_2_REQUIREMENTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "COMPLIANCE WITH SECTION 2 REQUIREMENTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Providers must ensure their high-risk AI systems comply with the requirements set out in Section 2 of the AI Act (Article 16(a))."@en .

euai:COMPUTE_METRIC a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "COMPUTE METRIC"@en ;
    skos:definition "The amount of computation used for training the model, measured in floating point operations or via proxies like cost, time, and energy consumption."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:REGULATION_2024_1689 .

euai:COMPUTE_THRESHOLD a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ClassificationRule ;
    rdfs:label "COMPUTE THRESHOLD"@en ;
    skos:definition "A technical criterion (10^25 FLOPs) used to identify general-purpose AI models that are presumed to have systemic risks."@en .

euai:CONCRETE_AND_IDENTIFIABLE_RISK a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:SystemicRisk ;
    rdfs:label "CONCRETE AND IDENTIFIABLE RISK"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific risk classification for general-purpose AI models that triggers the Scientific Panel to provide qualified alerts to the AI Office"@en .

euai:CONFIDENTIALITY_OBLIGATIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CONFIDENTIALITY OBLIGATIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Legal duties to protect information and documentation obtained under the Act, particularly trade secrets, in accordance with Article 78"@en .

euai:CONFIDENTIALITY_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "CONFIDENTIALITY REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Obligation for notifying authorities to safeguard the confidentiality of information obtained, in accordance with Article 78, as per Article 29(6)"@en .

euai:CONFIDENTIAL_INFORMATION_EXCHANGE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION EXCHANGE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty to protect confidential information, with specific disclosure prohibitions for information exchanged between competent authorities"@en .

euai:CONFLICT_OF_INTEREST_PREVENTION rdfs:label "CONFLICT OF INTEREST PREVENTION"@en .

euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT_FEES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CONFORMITY ASSESSMENT FEES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Fees charged by notified bodies for conformity assessments, which must account for the specific interests of SME providers"@en .

euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT_PROCEDURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CONFORMITY ASSESSMENT PROCEDURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Procedures that the Commission may amend via delegated acts, as per Recital 173"@en .

euai:CONFORMITY_REQUIREMENTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "CONFORMITY REQUIREMENTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "The specific technical and organizational requirements set out in Section 2 that high-risk AI systems must meet"@en .

euai:CONSULTATION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CONSULTATION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for national competent authorities to consult relevant authorities under other Union law when providing guidance on AI systems in areas covered by that other law."@en .

euai:COORDINATION_ACTIVITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "COORDINATION ACTIVITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Notified bodies are required to participate in coordination activities as defined in Article 38"@en .

euai:CORRECTIVE_ACTIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CORRECTIVE ACTIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Providers must take necessary measures to bring a non-conforming AI system into conformity, withdraw it, disable it, or recall it as per Article 20(1)"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_20 .

euai:CORRECTIVE_MEASURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CORRECTIVE MEASURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Actions required by the notifying Member State (including suspension or withdrawal of notification) when a notified body fails to meet requirements, per Article 37(4)"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_37_4_ .

euai:COUNCIL_REGULATION__EU__NO_1024_2013 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "COUNCIL REGULATION (EU) NO 1024/2013"@en ;
    skos:definition "Council Regulation (EU) No 1024/2013 is a foundational legislative act that establishes the legal framework for the Single Supervisory Mechanism (SSM). This regulation is instrumental in European financial oversight, as it confers specific, critical tasks upon the European Central Bank (ECB) regarding the prudential supervision of credit institutions within the European Union. By centralizing these supervisory powers, the regulation aims to ensure the safety and soundness of the banking system a"@en .

euai:COURT_OF_JUSTICE_OF_THE_EUROPEAN_UNION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "COURT OF JUSTICE OF THE EUROPEAN UNION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU) serves as the highest judicial body within the European Union. Its role encompasses the authority to review decisions made by the European Commission, particularly those established under the AI Act and other relevant regulations.

In exercising its judicial oversight, the Court possesses unlimited jurisdiction regarding penalties and fines. This authority empowers the Court to not only review Commission decisions but also to cancel, reduce, or i"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_261_TFEU,
        euai:EUROPEAN_COMMISSION,
        euai:EUROPEAN_DATA_PROTECTION_SUPERVISOR,
        euai:FINE_IMPOSITION .

euai:CRIMINAL_OFFENCE_THRESHOLD a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ClassificationRule ;
    rdfs:label "CRIMINAL OFFENCE THRESHOLD"@en ;
    skos:definition "The criterion requiring that criminal offences for which biometric identification is used must be punishable by a custodial sentence or detention order of a maximum period of at least four years."@en .

euai:CRIMINAL_RISK_ASSESSMENT_EXCLUSION rdfs:label "CRIMINAL RISK ASSESSMENT EXCLUSION"@en .

euai:CROSS_BORDER_COOPERATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "CROSS-BORDER COOPERATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The design and implementation of AI regulatory sandboxes must facilitate cross-border cooperation between national competent authorities."@en .

euai:CYBERSECURITY_MEASURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "CYBERSECURITY MEASURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Security protocols and measures implemented to protect the AI system, mandated as part of the technical documentation"@en .

euai:CYBERSECURITY_MEASURES_FOR_DATA_PROTECTION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "CYBERSECURITY MEASURES FOR DATA PROTECTION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Mandatory technical and organizational measures to ensure the security and confidentiality of information obtained by authorities"@en .

euai:Complaint a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Complaint"@en ;
    skos:definition "A formal instrument for downstream providers to report upstream infringements."@en .

euai:ConformityAssessment a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Conformity Assessment"@en ;
    rdfs:subClassOf euai:Obligation ;
    skos:definition "The process to demonstrate a high-risk AI system meets the requirements. (Article 43)"@en .

euai:DATABASE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DATABASE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Refers to the system where law enforcement authorities must register the AI system as required by the Regulation."@en .

euai:DATA_BIAS_MITIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DATA BIAS MITIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific measures to detect, prevent, and mitigate biases that could affect health, safety, or fundamental rights, as mandated by Article 10(2)(g)"@en .

euai:DATA_DELETION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DATA DELETION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "If an authorisation for the use of a real-time remote biometric identification system is rejected, all data, results, and outputs must be immediately discarded and deleted."@en .

euai:DATA_GOVERNANCE_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DATA GOVERNANCE REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Measure for which high-risk AI systems trained on specific data reflecting their intended operational context are presumed to comply"@en .

euai:DATA_MANAGEMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DATA MANAGEMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Procedures for data acquisition, collection, analysis, labelling, storage, filtration, mining, aggregation, and retention for high-risk AI systems."@en .

euai:DATA_MANAGEMENT_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DATA MANAGEMENT SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "Procedures including data acquisition, collection, labelling, storage, and mining, performed before placing on the market (Article 17(2)(f))."@en .

euai:DATA_MINIMISATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DATA MINIMISATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "A principle of data protection requiring that only necessary personal data is processed, applicable throughout the AI system lifecycle."@en .

euai:DATA_PROTECTION_AND_PRIVACY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DATA PROTECTION AND PRIVACY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Mandatory requirement to protect the rights of persons monitored by AI systems in work-related contexts"@en .

euai:DATA_PROTECTION_AUTHORITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "DATA PROTECTION AUTHORITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "A Data Protection Authority is a national or member state body responsible for overseeing and ensuring compliance with data protection regulations. In the specific context of AI innovation, this authority plays a critical role in the operation of AI regulatory sandboxes; whenever the development or testing of AI within these sandboxes involves the processing of personal data, the relevant Data Protection Authority must be actively involved to ensure that privacy standards and legal safeguards ar"@en .

euai:DATA_PROTECTION_LAW a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DATA PROTECTION LAW"@en ;
    skos:definition "The requirement that data governance and management practices must comply with relevant Union law, such as Regulation (EU) 2016/679"@en .

euai:DATA_SETS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DATA SETS"@en ;
    skos:definition "The training, validation, and testing data for high-risk AI systems which must be relevant, representative, complete, and free of errors"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DATA_GOVERNANCE,
        euai:DATA_PROTECTION_LAW,
        euai:PRIVACY_PRESERVING_TECHNIQUES .

euai:DATA_SHEETS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DATA SHEETS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Documented practice for information sharing along the AI value chain, encouraged for open-source developers"@en .

euai:DATA_TRANSFER_SAFEGUARDS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DATA TRANSFER SAFEGUARDS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Mandatory protocols for transferring data collected for real-world testing to third countries, ensuring compliance with Union law on data protection and Regulations (EU) 2022/868 and (EU) 2023/2854"@en .

euai:DECISION_NO_768_2008_EC a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "DECISION NO 768/2008/EC"@en ;
    skos:definition "Decision No 768/2008/EC is a significant legislative instrument that serves as a core component of the European Union's New Legislative Framework. It functions as a foundational decision establishing a common framework for the marketing of products, acting as a crucial legal basis for ensuring overall product compliance within the EU. Furthermore, it provides the essential rules and consistency required for the placing of products on the market, including those categorized as high-risk AI system"@en .

euai:DECLARATION_OF_INTERESTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DECLARATION OF INTERESTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "A document each expert on the scientific panel must draw up, which shall be made publicly available"@en .

euai:DEEPFAKE_DISCLOSURE_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DEEPFAKE DISCLOSURE OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for deployers to clearly disclose that image, audio, or video content (deepfakes) has been artificially created or manipulated."@en .

euai:DELEGATION_OF_POWER_PERIOD a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DELEGATION OF POWER PERIOD"@en ;
    skos:definition "The power to adopt delegated acts is conferred for a period of five years from 1 August 2024, subject to tacit extension unless opposed by the Parliament or Council per Article 97(2)"@en .

euai:DEROGATION_AUTHORISATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DEROGATION AUTHORISATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "An authorization by a market surveillance authority allowing the placing on the market of a high-risk AI system without completing standard conformity assessment procedures for exceptional reasons."@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_46 .

euai:DESIGN_CONTROL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DESIGN CONTROL"@en ;
    skos:definition "Techniques and procedures for design, verification, and control of the high-risk AI system (Article 17(2)(b))."@en .

euai:DEVELOPMENT_AND_QUALITY_CONTROL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DEVELOPMENT AND QUALITY CONTROL"@en ;
    skos:definition "Techniques and procedures for development, quality control, and assurance of the high-risk AI system (Article 17(2)(c))."@en .

euai:DEVELOPMENT_OF_INFORMATION_PLATFORM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DEVELOPMENT OF INFORMATION PLATFORM"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty of the AI Office to develop and maintain a single information platform for all operators across the Union."@en .

euai:DIGITAL_CE_MARKING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DIGITAL CE MARKING"@en ;
    skos:definition "A digital representation of the CE marking used for high-risk AI systems provided digitally or as a supplement to physical marking"@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:DIGITAL_EUROPE_PROGRAMME a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "DIGITAL EUROPE PROGRAMME"@en ;
    skos:definition "The DIGITAL EUROPE PROGRAMME is a European Union funding and support initiative designed to advance digital transformation across the region. As a comprehensive funding program and project, it is structured to actively contribute to the overarching objectives of the relevant Regulation. Central to its mission is the establishment and management of specialized infrastructure, specifically AI testing and experimentation facilities, which foster innovation and the practical application of artificia"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:COMPLIANCE_WITH_THIS_REGULATION .

euai:DIRECTIVE_2000_31_EC rdfs:label "DIRECTIVE 2000 31 EC"@en .

euai:DIRECTIVE_2002_14_EC a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "DIRECTIVE 2002/14/EC"@en ;
    skos:definition """**DIRECTIVE 2002/14/EC** is a piece of European legislation that establishes a general framework for the information and consultation of employees within the European Community. This directive is designed to ensure that workers are properly informed and consulted by their employers regarding relevant workplace matters.

In the context of contemporary legal frameworks—specifically concerning the regulation of artificial intelligence—DIRECTIVE 2002/14/EC plays a significant role. It is explicitly """@en .

euai:DIRECTIVE_2002_58_EC a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "DIRECTIVE 2002/58/EC"@en ;
    skos:definition """Directive 2002/58/EC is the European Union’s directive focused on privacy and electronic communications. Its primary purpose is to protect the private life of individuals and ensure the confidentiality of their communications across electronic networks. 

This directive remains highly relevant to the evolving technological landscape, particularly regarding artificial intelligence (AI) systems. It serves as a critical regulatory framework for AI systems that operate within the electronic communic"""@en .

euai:DIRECTIVE_2004_42_EC rdfs:label "DIRECTIVE 2004 42 EC"@en .

euai:DIRECTIVE_2013_32_EU a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "DIRECTIVE 2013/32/EU"@en ;
    skos:definition """Directive 2013/32/EU, commonly known as the Asylum Procedures Directive, establishes a framework of common procedures for the granting and withdrawing of international protection within the European Union. This legislative instrument is designed to harmonize the processes Member States use to assess asylum claims, ensuring a consistent approach to the protection of individuals seeking refuge. 

Furthermore, Directive 2013/32/EU holds significant relevance within the context of emerging technolog"""@en .

euai:DIRECTIVE_2014_17_EU a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "DIRECTIVE 2014/17/EU"@en ;
    skos:definition """**DIRECTIVE 2014/17/EU**, also known as the Mortgage Credit Directive, serves as a crucial regulatory framework concerning credit agreements for consumers relating to residential immovable property. Specifically referenced within Recital 50, this directive plays an essential role in establishing guidelines for the mortgage and credit sector.

While DIRECTIVE 2014/17/EU primarily focuses on consumer protection and standardizing the internal market for residential property credit, recent discussio"""@en .

euai:DIRECTIVE_2020_1828 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "DIRECTIVE 2020/1828"@en ;
    skos:definition "Directive (EU) 2020/1828 is a legislative act of the European Union that has been amended by Article 110 of the Artificial Intelligence (AI) Act. This directive serves as an important component of the EU regulatory framework, and its modification through the AI Act ensures its alignment with updated legal standards regarding the governance and regulation of artificial intelligence technologies."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_110 .

euai:DIRECTIVE__EU__2016_797 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "DIRECTIVE (EU) 2016/797"@en ;
    skos:definition """Directive (EU) 2016/797 is a legislative act focused on the interoperability of the rail system within the European Union. Its primary objective is to harmonize and streamline technical and operational standards across member states to ensure that rail systems can function seamlessly together.

In addition to its foundational purpose regarding railway interoperability, Directive (EU) 2016/797 has been subject to updates to reflect modern technological advancements. Specifically, the directive wa"""@en .

euai:DIRECTIVE__EU__2016_97 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "DIRECTIVE (EU) 2016/97"@en ;
    skos:definition """Directive (EU) 2016/97, commonly known as the Directive on Insurance Distribution, establishes a regulatory framework governing the distribution of insurance products within the European Union. Central to this directive is Recital 51, which plays a critical role in shaping the compliance landscape for the insurance sector.

Recital 51 is significant because it highlights the necessity of addressing the implications of technological advancements, specifically identifying its relevance to the requ"""@en .

euai:DISTRIBUTOR_OBLIGATION__STORAGE_AND_TRANSPORT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DISTRIBUTOR OBLIGATION: STORAGE AND TRANSPORT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Distributors must ensure that, while the high-risk AI system is under their responsibility, storage or transport conditions do not jeopardize the compliance of the system with the requirements set out in Section 2"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:SECTION_2 .

euai:DISTRIBUTOR_OBLIGATION__VERIFICATION_AND_CORRECTIVE_ACTION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DISTRIBUTOR OBLIGATION: VERIFICATION AND CORRECTIVE ACTION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Before making a system available, distributor must verify CE marking, EU declaration of conformity, instructions, and provider/importer compliance. Must take corrective action or withdraw/recall non-conforming systems"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_47 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_16,
        euai:ARTICLE_23_3_,
        euai:SECTION_2 .

euai:DOCUMENTATION rdfs:label "DOCUMENTATION"@en .

euai:DOCUMENTATION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DOCUMENTATION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for each use of a high-risk AI system to be documented in a police file and made available to relevant authorities upon request"@en .

euai:DOCUMENTATION_PRESERVATION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DOCUMENTATION PRESERVATION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The notifying authority's duty to take steps to ensure that the files of a notified body are kept and made available in the event of a suspension, restriction, or withdrawal of designation"@en .

euai:DOCUMENTATION_PROVISION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DOCUMENTATION PROVISION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Notified bodies must make available and submit all relevant documentation to the notifying authority upon request"@en .

euai:DOCUMENTATION_SUBMISSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DOCUMENTATION SUBMISSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Notified bodies are required to make available and submit upon request all relevant documentation, including provider documentation"@en .

euai:DOWNSTREAM_PROVIDER a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "DOWNSTREAM PROVIDER"@en ;
    skos:definition """A "Downstream Provider" refers to an entity that integrates or utilizes an AI system—including general-purpose AI (GPAI) systems—that has been built upon or incorporates an upstream AI model. These providers sit further down the AI supply chain, taking foundational models and integrating them into their own distinct AI products or services.

Because Downstream Providers rely on the underlying technology provided by upstream model developers, they depend on receiving specific information from tho"""@en ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:LABELING_OBLIGATION ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:COMPLAINT,
        euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL,
        euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:TECHNICAL_SOLUTIONS_FOR_MARKING .

euai:DOWNSTREAM_PROVIDERS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "DOWNSTREAM PROVIDERS"@en ;
    skos:definition "**DOWNSTREAM PROVIDERS** are defined as stakeholders—specifically entities that utilize General Purpose AI (GPAI) models—who are invited to play an active role in the regulatory process. Under Article 56(3), these providers are encouraged to contribute to and support the collaborative development of codes of practice. By leveraging their practical experience in utilizing GPAI models, they help ensure that the resulting codes are comprehensive, informed, and effective."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CODE_OF_PRACTICE .

euai:Deployer a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Deployer"@en ;
    rdfs:subClassOf euai:Actor ;
    skos:definition "A natural or legal person that uses an AI system under their authority. (Article 3(4))"@en .

euai:EARLY_APPLICATION_DATE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "EARLY APPLICATION DATE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The date of 2 February 2025, when prohibitions and general provisions apply (Recital 179)."@en .

euai:EDUCATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AnnexIIICategory ;
    rdfs:label "EDUCATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "In the context of the AI regulatory framework, \"EDUCATION\" is designated as one of the eight specific high-risk use case domains. As defined in Annex III of the relevant regulations, this domain encompasses a broad range of AI systems deployed within educational and training settings. Specifically, these systems include those designed for evaluating students, such as grading or assessment tools, as well as AI technologies that influence educational pathways, such as admissions screening or curri"@en .

euai:EDUCATION_AND_TRAINING_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "EDUCATION AND TRAINING AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition """**EDUCATION AND TRAINING AI SYSTEM**

An Education and Training AI System encompasses various technological tools designed to evaluate learning outcomes, assess educational levels, and monitor student behavior during testing environments. Due to their significant potential to influence an individual's academic progress and overall life trajectory, these systems are classified as high-risk. This classification reflects the critical nature of the decisions they facilitate, such as grading, admissi"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:EDUCATION,
        euai:HIGH_RISK,
        euai:NON_DISCRIMINATION,
        euai:NON_DISCRIMINATION_REQUIREMENT .

euai:EDUCATION_CATEGORY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AnnexIIICategory ;
    rdfs:label "EDUCATION CATEGORY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Use case domain involving the access and assignment to educational and vocational training institutions (Recital 44)"@en .

euai:EFFECTIVE_OVERSIGHT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "EFFECTIVE OVERSIGHT"@en ;
    skos:definition "A mandatory requirement for competent personnel to be involved in real-world testing to ensure proper supervision"@en .

euai:ELECTRONIC_INSTRUCTIONS_FOR_USE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "ELECTRONIC INSTRUCTIONS FOR USE"@en ;
    skos:definition "**ELECTRONIC INSTRUCTIONS FOR USE** serve as a mandatory documentation requirement for high-risk AI systems, ensuring that users are provided with necessary information regarding the system's operation and usage. However, this requirement is not universal; specific exemptions exist for AI systems deployed within the sectors of law enforcement, migration, asylum, and border control. In particular, these systems, often categorized under Annex III of relevant AI regulations, are relieved from the o"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_III .

euai:ELECTRONIC_NOTIFICATION_TOOL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "ELECTRONIC NOTIFICATION TOOL"@en ;
    skos:definition "The digital system referenced in Article 30(2) used by the notifying authority to notify the Commission and Member States of changes to a notified body's status"@en .

euai:EMERGENCY_SERVICE_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "EMERGENCY SERVICE AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "AI systems used to evaluate and classify emergency calls, dispatch, or establish priority for emergency services like police, fire, and medical aid"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:HIGH_RISK .

euai:EMOTION_INFERENCE_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "EMOTION INFERENCE EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The prohibition on emotion inference systems in workplace/education does not apply where the system is intended for medical or safety reasons."@en .

euai:EMPLOYMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AnnexIIICategory ;
    rdfs:label "EMPLOYMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "**EMPLOYMENT** is classified as one of the eight high-risk use case domains under the regulatory framework, specifically as defined in Annex III. This category encompasses a range of artificial intelligence systems designed to facilitate various professional processes. Specifically, these systems are utilized for recruitment procedures, the monitoring of employee performance, broader worker management, and the management of access to self-employment opportunities. As a high-risk domain, AI appli"@en .

euai:ENERGY_EFFICIENT_DEVELOPMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "ENERGY EFFICIENT DEVELOPMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Technical standardisation deliverable specifically concerning general-purpose AI models (Recital 174)"@en .

euai:ENFORCEMENT_ASSESSMENT_REPORT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "ENFORCEMENT ASSESSMENT REPORT"@en ;
    skos:definition "A duty of the European Commission to assess the enforcement of the Regulation by 2 August 2031 and report findings."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:COUNCIL,
        euai:EUROPEAN_ECONOMIC_AND_SOCIAL_COMMITTEE,
        euai:EUROPEAN_PARLIAMENT .

euai:ENTRY_EXIT_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "ENTRY/EXIT SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Entry/Exit System (EES) is an automated IT system established by Regulation (EU) 2017/2226. Its primary purpose is to register the entry and exit data, as well as the refusal of entry data, of third-country nationals crossing the external borders of the European Union. In addition to serving as a record-keeping mechanism for border crossings, the system also incorporates specific conditions and frameworks allowing for access to this data for law enforcement purposes."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:REGISTRATION_OF_ENTRY_AND_EXIT_DATA,
        euai:REGULATION__EU__2017_2226 .

euai:ENVIRONMENTAL_SUSTAINABILITY_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "ENVIRONMENTAL SUSTAINABILITY REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "A specific requirement for codes of conduct involving the assessment and minimization of impact on environmental sustainability, as per Article 95(2)(b)"@en .

euai:ETHICAL_REVIEW a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "ETHICAL REVIEW"@en ;
    skos:definition "Mandatory ethical assessment required by Union or national law that must be respected during real-world testing"@en .

euai:ETHICS_GUIDELINES_FOR_TRUSTWORTHY_AI a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "ETHICS GUIDELINES FOR TRUSTWORTHY AI"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **ETHICS GUIDELINES FOR TRUSTWORTHY AI** comprise a set of non-binding ethical principles developed by the High-Level Expert Group on Artificial Intelligence (AI HLEG). Although these guidelines are voluntary in nature, they serve as an influential framework intended to ensure that the development and deployment of artificial intelligence systems are trustworthy, ethically sound, and aligned with human values.

The guidelines are specifically designed to support the development of high-risk """@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:EUROHPC_JOINT_UNDERTAKING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "EUROHPC JOINT UNDERTAKING"@en ;
    skos:definition "A Union-level structure providing high-performance computing resources, utilized to build AI expertise and capabilities"@en .

euai:EUROPEAN_COMMON_DATA_SPACES rdfs:label "EUROPEAN COMMON DATA SPACES"@en .

euai:EUROPEAN_DATA_PROTECTION_BOARD a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "EUROPEAN DATA PROTECTION BOARD"@en ;
    skos:definition "The European Data Protection Board (EDPB) is an independent European body with a mandate to ensure the consistent application of data protection rules throughout the European Union. In its advisory and regulatory capacity, the European Data Protection Board is consulted during the process of adopting new regulations. Furthermore, it serves as a critical regulatory body that must be consulted regarding the establishment of specific rules governing the processing of personal data in relation to ar"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:REGULATION__EU__2018_1725 .

euai:EUROPEAN_DIGITAL_INNOVATION_HUB a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "EUROPEAN DIGITAL INNOVATION HUB"@en ;
    skos:definition """European Digital Innovation Hubs (EDIHs) are EU-supported entities specifically designated to foster digital innovation and facilitate the implementation of relevant European regulations. Functioning as integral pillars within the European technological landscape, these hubs serve multiple strategic purposes.

Primarily, European Digital Innovation Hubs are tasked with supporting the broader digital transformation efforts across the region. They play a critical role in the regulatory sandbox eco"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOX .

euai:EUROPEAN_DIGITAL_INNOVATION_HUBS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "EUROPEAN DIGITAL INNOVATION HUBS"@en ;
    skos:definition "European Digital Innovation Hubs (EDIHs) are organizations specifically designated to facilitate and support digital transformation efforts. Beyond this core mission, they are tasked with contributing to the practical implementation of the Regulation and providing essential technical and scientific support. Furthermore, European Digital Innovation Hubs are recognized as relevant entities that may be granted access to data for the specific purposes of developing and assessing high-risk artificial"@en .

euai:EUROPEAN_ECONOMIC_AND_SOCIAL_COMMITTEE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "EUROPEAN ECONOMIC AND SOCIAL COMMITTEE"@en ;
    skos:definition "An advisory body that receives the enforcement assessment report from the Commission."@en .

euai:EUROPEAN_HARMONISED_STANDARD a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "EUROPEAN HARMONISED STANDARD"@en ;
    skos:definition "Technical standards whose compliance grants presumption of conformity for GPAI model obligations"@en ;
    euai:grants euai:PRESUMPTION_OF_CONFORMITY .

euai:EUROPEAN_STANDARDISATION_ORGANISATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "EUROPEAN STANDARDISATION ORGANISATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "European Standardisation Organisations (ESOs) are recognized as the key bodies responsible for the development and drafting of harmonised standards. Their function is formally triggered upon receiving a specific request from the European Commission, a role that is crucial within the context of European standardisation procedures. Furthermore, these organisations may be actively involved within the broader AI ecosystem, where they play a significant part in supporting the effective implementation"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_24_OF_REGULATION__EU__NO_1025_2012 .

euai:EUROPEAN_STANDARDISATION_ORGANISATIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "EUROPEAN STANDARDISATION ORGANISATIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "European Standardisation Organisations (ESOs) are crucial entities operating within the framework of Regulation (EU) No 1025/2012. These organisations have been tasked by the European Commission with the critical responsibility of drafting harmonised standards specifically for high-risk AI systems and general-purpose AI models. Furthermore, European Standardisation Organisations serve as essential forums for engagement, as notified bodies are required to participate in or be represented within t"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:HARMONISED_STANDARDS,
        euai:STANDARDISATION_REQUEST .

euai:EUROPEAN_UNION_AVIATION_SAFETY_AGENCY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "EUROPEAN UNION AVIATION SAFETY AGENCY"@en ;
    skos:definition "The European Union Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) is a regulatory body established by Regulation (EU) 2018/1139. It serves as the primary authority responsible for developing and implementing common rules and standards in the field of civil aviation across the European Union."@en .

euai:EU_AI_ACT rdfs:label "EU AI ACT"@en .

euai:EU_DATABASE_REGISTRATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "EU DATABASE REGISTRATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The EU Database Registration process is a critical regulatory obligation for providers of AI systems. According to the governing regulations, providers are required to register their AI systems in the designated EU database before the systems are deployed for use.

While Article 49 mandates this registration prior to use, there is a specific exception for urgent situations. In such cases, an AI system may be utilized before the registration process is finalized, provided that the registration is"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_49,
        euai:ARTICLE_83 .

euai:EVALUATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "EVALUATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The process conducted by the AI Office, potentially involving independent experts, to assess compliance of general-purpose AI models"@en .

euai:EXAMINATION_AND_VALIDATION_PROCEDURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "EXAMINATION AND VALIDATION PROCEDURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Procedures for testing and validation carried out at different stages of the AI system lifecycle (Article 17(2)(d))."@en .

euai:EXCEPTIONAL_PUBLIC_SECURITY_AUTHORISATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "EXCEPTIONAL PUBLIC SECURITY AUTHORISATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Market surveillance authorities may authorise the placing on the market or putting into service of AI systems that have not undergone conformity assessment for reasons of public security, protection of life/health, environmental protection, or protection of key assets"@en .

euai:EXCLUSION_CONDITIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "EXCLUSION CONDITIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Conditions under which an AI system is considered not to pose significant risk of harm, currently subject to potential amendment by delegated acts per Article 49(6) and (7)"@en .

euai:EXCLUSION_FOR_ASSISTIVE_FUNCTIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "EXCLUSION FOR ASSISTIVE FUNCTIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Exemption from labeling obligations for AI systems performing primarily assistive functions for standard editing or not substantially altering input/semantics"@en .

euai:EXCLUSION_FOR_MERE_EXPRESSION_DETECTION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "EXCLUSION FOR MERE EXPRESSION DETECTION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Condition under Recital 18 where systems detecting gestures, movements, or expressions are not considered emotion recognition systems unless those expressions are used to identify or infer emotions."@en .

euai:EXCLUSION_FOR_PHYSICAL_STATE_DETECTION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "EXCLUSION FOR PHYSICAL STATE DETECTION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Condition under Recital 18 where systems detecting physical states like pain or fatigue are not considered emotion recognition systems, provided they are not used to infer emotions."@en .

euai:EXCLUSION_FOR_POLITICAL_CAMPAIGN_TOOLS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "EXCLUSION FOR POLITICAL CAMPAIGN TOOLS"@en ;
    skos:definition """The "EXCLUSION FOR POLITICAL CAMPAIGN TOOLS" acts as a specific regulatory provision that exempts certain AI systems from the high-risk classification typically applied to tools used for influencing elections. As outlined in the regulations—specifically within Annex III(8)(b) and clarified by Recital 62—this exception applies to AI tools utilized for the administrative and logistical optimization of political campaigns. 

The core criterion for this exclusion is the lack of direct exposure to na"""@en .

euai:EXCLUSION_FOR_RISK_ANALYTICS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "EXCLUSION FOR RISK ANALYTICS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Exemption for AI systems assessing likelihood of financial fraud or narcotics trafficking, provided they are not based on personal profiling."@en .

euai:EXCLUSION_FOR_TRAVEL_DOCUMENT_VERIFICATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "EXCLUSION FOR TRAVEL DOCUMENT VERIFICATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Exception to the migration identification AI systems category (Annex III(7)(d)) regarding the verification of travel documents"@en .

euai:EXEMPTION_FOR_ARTISTIC_CREATIVE_WORK rdfs:label "EXEMPTION FOR ARTISTIC CREATIVE WORK"@en .

euai:EXEMPTION_FROM_ADMINISTRATIVE_FINES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "EXEMPTION FROM ADMINISTRATIVE FINES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Prospective providers are exempt from administrative fines for Regulation infringements if they follow the sandbox participation plan and guidance provided by the national competent authority."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:NATIONAL_COMPETENT_AUTHORITY .

euai:EXEMPTION_FROM_AUTHORISATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "EXEMPTION FROM AUTHORISATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The authorisation requirement does not apply when the system is used for the initial identification of a potential suspect based on objective and verifiable facts directly linked to the offence"@en .

euai:EXEMPTION_FROM_POST_MARKET_MONITORING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "EXEMPTION FROM POST-MARKET MONITORING"@en ;
    skos:definition "An exemption applied to post-market monitoring activities, stating that monitoring should not cover sensitive operational data of deployers that are law enforcement authorities."@en .

euai:EXPLANATION_OF_DECISION rdfs:label "EXPLANATION OF DECISION"@en .

euai:FEEDBACK_LOOPS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "FEEDBACK LOOPS"@en ;
    skos:definition "**FEEDBACK LOOPS** represent a critical risk mechanism within learning systems where the data outputs generated by a model subsequently influence the inputs for future operations. This cyclical process creates a vulnerability where biased outputs can be fed back into the system, potentially leading to bias amplification. Because of this inherent risk, providers of learning systems are required to actively mitigate these loops to ensure that biased information does not compromise future system op"@en .

euai:FEES_FOR_CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "FEES FOR CONFORMITY ASSESSMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Financial costs for conformity assessments which must be reduced for SME providers under Article 62(2)"@en .

euai:FEE_PAYMENT_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "FEE PAYMENT OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Potential duty for Member States to pay fees for advice and support provided by the scientific panel experts."@en .

euai:FINANCIAL_AND_HUMAN_RESOURCES_ASSESSMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "FINANCIAL AND HUMAN RESOURCES ASSESSMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "The duty of Member States to report to the Commission on the status and adequacy of the financial and human resources of national competent authorities every two years."@en .

euai:FINANCIAL_SERVICES_FRAUD_DETECTION_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "FINANCIAL SERVICES FRAUD DETECTION EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Condition under which fraud detection AI systems are not classified as high-risk under this Regulation"@en .

euai:FINANCIAL_SUPERVISOR a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "FINANCIAL SUPERVISOR"@en ;
    skos:definition "National authority responsible for financial supervision of institutions; acts as the market surveillance authority for AI systems used in financial services"@en .

euai:FINES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "FINES"@en ;
    skos:definition """Fines are financial penalties imposed on providers to ensure accountability and compliance within the regulatory framework. These penalties are enforced under two primary provisions:

*   **Article 99:** Fines are levied against providers for failure to comply with established regulatory requirements. Furthermore, these penalties specifically target providers that engage in the deliberate misclassification of systems or attempt to circumvent high-risk classification protocols.
*   **Article 101:"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_101 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_99 .

euai:FLOATING_POINT_OPERATIONS_THRESHOLD a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ClassificationRule ;
    rdfs:label "FLOATING POINT OPERATIONS THRESHOLD"@en ;
    skos:definition "The \"FLOATING POINT OPERATIONS THRESHOLD\" serves as a technical metric defined by the cumulative compute utilized during the training phase of an artificial intelligence model. This metric is employed as an initial approximation to evaluate and presume whether a General Purpose AI (GPAI) model possesses systemic risks, as explicitly referenced in Recital 111 of the relevant regulatory framework. By quantifying the computational power invested in training, this threshold acts as a foundational be"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL_WITH_SYSTEMIC_RISKS .

euai:FORMAL_NON_COMPLIANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "FORMAL NON-COMPLIANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Situations such as incorrect CE marking, missing declaration of conformity, or missing technical documentation that providers must rectify"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_83 .

euai:FREE_AND_OPEN_SOURCE_AI_COMPONENTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "FREE AND OPEN-SOURCE AI COMPONENTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Software and data, including models and general-purpose AI models, tools, services, or processes of an AI system released under a free and open-source licence, as described in Recital 102 and 103"@en ;
    euai:isExemptFromHighRisk euai:TRANSPARENCY_RELATED_REQUIREMENTS ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:MONETISATION_EXCLUSION ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:TRANSPARENCY_MEASURES .

euai:FULL_ASSESSMENT_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "FULL ASSESSMENT OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for a successor notified body to complete a full assessment of affected high-risk AI systems within nine months following the cessation of the previous notified body's activities"@en .

euai:FUNDAMENTAL_RIGHTS_PROTECTION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "FUNDAMENTAL RIGHTS PROTECTION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The underlying objective of the AI Act requiring deployers to actively protect fundamental rights when using high-risk AI systems (Recital 92, 93)"@en .

euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODELS_WITH_SYSTEMIC_RISK a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:SystemicRisk ;
    rdfs:label "GENERAL-PURPOSE AI MODELS WITH SYSTEMIC RISK"@en ;
    skos:definition "GPAI models with systemic risk, criteria for which the Commission can amend via delegated acts"@en .

euai:GOVERNANCE_AND_ENFORCEMENT_STRUCTURE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "GOVERNANCE AND ENFORCEMENT STRUCTURE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for the operational establishment of infrastructure related to governance and conformity assessment, applicable from 2 August 2025 (Recital 179)"@en .

euai:GPAI_MODEL_PROVIDER a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "GPAI MODEL PROVIDER"@en ;
    skos:definition """A "GPAI Model Provider" is defined as any natural or legal person who develops a general-purpose AI model and places that model on the Union market. As established in Article 3(64) of the AI Act, this role carries specific responsibilities and regulatory obligations.

The GPAI Model Provider is ultimately responsible for ensuring the model’s compliance with all applicable transparency and copyright obligations. Furthermore, these providers are subject to oversight, including supervision and enfo"""@en ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:COPYRIGHT_COMPLIANCE_POLICY,
        euai:TRAINING_DATA_SUMMARY_OBLIGATION,
        euai:TRANSPARENCY_DOCUMENTATION ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL,
        euai:PRESUMPTION_OF_CONFORMITY,
        euai:RESERVATION_OF_RIGHTS,
        euai:UNION_MARKET ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:SYSTEMIC_RISK_CRITERIA .

euai:GUIDANCE_AND_ADVICE_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "GUIDANCE AND ADVICE OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The potential duty/power of national competent authorities to provide guidance on the implementation of the Regulation, particularly to SMEs and start-ups."@en .

euai:GUIDANCE_ON_REPORTING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "GUIDANCE ON REPORTING"@en ;
    skos:definition "Technical/organizational guidance developed by the Commission to facilitate compliance with reporting obligations, to be issued by 2 August 2025."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:REPORTING_OBLIGATION .

euai:GUIDELINES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "GUIDELINES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Documents developed by the Commission to assist with the practical implementation of the Regulation, including requirements, prohibited practices, and transparency obligations, as per Article 96"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_96 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_5,
        euai:ARTICLE_50,
        euai:ARTICLE_8_15,
        euai:COMMON_SPECIFICATIONS,
        euai:HARMONISED_STANDARDS .

euai:GUIDELINES_FOR_QUALITY_MANAGEMENT_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "GUIDELINES FOR QUALITY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "The obligation for the Commission to develop specific guidelines detailing how microenterprises can fulfill quality management system requirements in a simplified manner"@en .

euai:GUIDELINES_ON_PRACTICAL_IMPLEMENTATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "GUIDELINES ON PRACTICAL IMPLEMENTATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Commission must provide guidelines specifying the practical implementation of Article 49 by 2 February 2026, including a list of examples of high-risk and non-high-risk AI systems"@en .

euai:GeneralPurposeAIModel a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "General-Purpose AI Model"@en ;
    rdfs:subClassOf euai:AISystem ;
    skos:definition "An AI model trained on large data that can perform a wide range of tasks. (Article 3(63))"@en .

euai:HIGH_QUALITY_DATA a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "HIGH-QUALITY DATA"@en ;
    skos:definition "A technical requirement for training AI systems to avoid discriminatory or incorrect outcomes"@en .

euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEMS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:RiskCategory ;
    rdfs:label "HIGH-RISK AI SYSTEMS"@en ;
    skos:definition "High-risk AI systems are classified as AI systems for which relevant regulations establish specific requirements and obligations for their operators. These systems are subject to strict regulatory oversight, necessitating that operators adhere to defined standards and responsibilities to ensure the systems are developed and deployed safely, transparently, and in compliance with the law."@en .

euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEMS_LIST a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ClassificationRule ;
    rdfs:label "HIGH-RISK AI SYSTEMS LIST"@en ;
    skos:definition "The list of high-risk AI systems which the Commission is empowered to amend via delegated acts, as per Recital 173"@en .

euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEMS_LIST_AMENDMENT_ASSESSMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "HIGH-RISK AI SYSTEMS LIST AMENDMENT ASSESSMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Commission must assess the need to amend the list of high-risk AI systems and prohibited practices once a year (Recital 174)."@en .

euai:HIGH_RISK_AREAS_HEADINGS_AMENDMENT_EVALUATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "HIGH-RISK AREAS HEADINGS AMENDMENT EVALUATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Commission must evaluate and report on the need to amend the list of high-risk areas headings in the annex by 2 August 2028 and every four years thereafter (Recital 174)."@en .

euai:HOSTING_SERVICES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "HOSTING SERVICES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Service providers subject to obligations under Article 16 of Regulation (EU) 2022/2065 regarding illegal content notices, which remains independent of transparency labeling obligations (Recital 136)"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_16_6_ ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_16_1_ .

euai:HUMAN_ASSESSMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "HUMAN ASSESSMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Essential requirement for risk assessments involving natural persons to ensure they are not judged solely on AI-predicted behavior."@en .

euai:HUMAN_CENTRIC_TECHNOLOGY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "HUMAN-CENTRIC TECHNOLOGY"@en ;
    skos:definition "A core principle that AI should be developed as a tool for people with the aim of increasing human well-being"@en .

euai:HUMAN_OVERSIGHT_MEASURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "HUMAN OVERSIGHT MEASURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Measures needed to ensure appropriate oversight of the AI system, which must be assessed in the technical documentation per Article 14."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_14 .

euai:HUMAN_REVIEW_OR_EDITORIAL_CONTROL_EXCEPTION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "HUMAN REVIEW OR EDITORIAL CONTROL EXCEPTION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Transparency obligations for AI-generated text published in the public interest do not apply if the content has undergone human review or editorial control and a natural or legal person holds editorial responsibility, per Article 50(4)"@en .

euai:IMPACT_ASSESSMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "IMPACT ASSESSMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty for deployers of high-risk AI systems to assess risks, potentially involving stakeholders such as civil society and independent experts"@en .

euai:IMPARTIALITY_AND_OBJECTIVITY_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "IMPARTIALITY AND OBJECTIVITY OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Scientific panel experts must perform tasks with impartiality, objectivity, and confidentiality, and are prohibited from seeking instructions from external parties"@en .

euai:IMPARTIALITY_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "IMPARTIALITY REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "The duty of notified bodies to document and implement structures and procedures to safeguard objective and impartial assessments throughout their organization and personnel, per Article 31(6)."@en .

euai:IMPLEMENTING_ACTS_ON_SANDBOXES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:DelegatedAct ;
    rdfs:label "IMPLEMENTING ACTS ON SANDBOXES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Acts adopted by the Commission to specify detailed arrangements for the establishment, operation, and supervision of AI regulatory sandboxes, ensuring consistency across the Union (Article 58(1))."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_58 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_98_2_ .

euai:IMPORTER_OBLIGATION__DOCUMENTATION_AND_RECORDS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "IMPORTER OBLIGATION: DOCUMENTATION AND RECORDS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Importer must keep copies of certificates, instructions for use, and declaration of conformity for 10 years; provide documentation to competent authorities upon request"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_47 .

euai:IMPORTER_OBLIGATION__IDENTIFICATION_LABELING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "IMPORTER OBLIGATION: IDENTIFICATION LABELING"@en ;
    skos:definition "Importers must indicate their name, registered trade name/mark, and contact address on the high-risk AI system, packaging, or documentation"@en .

euai:IMPORTER_OBLIGATION__INFORMATION_PROVISION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "IMPORTER OBLIGATION: INFORMATION PROVISION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Importers must provide relevant competent authorities with necessary documentation (certificate, instructions, declaration) in a language easily understood by them"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION .

euai:IMPORTER_OBLIGATION__STORAGE_AND_TRANSPORT rdfs:label "IMPORTER OBLIGATION  STORAGE AND TRANSPORT"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:SECTION_2 .

euai:IMPORTER_OBLIGATION__VERIFICATION_AND_NON_CONFORMITY_REPORTING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "IMPORTER OBLIGATION: VERIFICATION AND NON-CONFORMITY REPORTING"@en ;
    skos:definition "Importer must check for conformity, report risks under Article 79(1) to provider/rep/authorities, and refrain from placing non-conforming systems on the market"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_79_1_ .

euai:INCLUSIVE_AND_DIVERSE_DESIGN a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INCLUSIVE AND DIVERSE DESIGN"@en ;
    skos:definition """**INCLUSIVE AND DIVERSE DESIGN** encompasses a multifaceted approach to development practices that prioritizes accessibility and equity throughout the lifecycle of a project or system. This framework operates through both mandatory and voluntary guidelines aimed at fostering environments that are both representative and accessible to all users.

At its core, INCLUSIVE AND DIVERSE DESIGN is defined by a specific mandate within codes of conduct—referenced under Article 95(2)(d)—which requires the """@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CODE_OF_CONDUCT .

euai:INDEPENDENCE rdfs:label "INDEPENDENCE"@en .

euai:INDEPENDENCE_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INDEPENDENCE REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "The obligation for notified bodies to be independent of providers and economic operators of the AI systems they assess, preventing conflicts of interest and prohibiting involvement in design/development"@en .

euai:INDEPENDENT_EXPERT rdfs:label "INDEPENDENT EXPERT"@en ;
    euai:conductsEvaluationOf euai:EVALUATION .

euai:INDEPENDENT_EXPERTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "INDEPENDENT EXPERTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "**INDEPENDENT EXPERTS** are specialized individuals appointed by the European Commission to perform critical functions regarding the governance and evaluation of artificial intelligence. These experts are tasked with carrying out formal evaluations of general-purpose AI models, adhering strictly to the criteria defined in Article 68(2) of the applicable regulations. This evaluation process is conducted by the experts on behalf of the Commission and includes members of the scientific panel, ensur"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_68_2_,
        euai:ARTICLE_92_EVALUATIONS,
        euai:CODE_OF_PRACTICE,
        euai:EVALUATION_OF_GPAI_MODEL .

euai:INDISCRIMINATE_SURVEILLANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:RiskCategory ;
    rdfs:label "INDISCRIMINATE SURVEILLANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A forbidden outcome in the framework of law enforcement when using post-remote biometric identification systems, as prohibited under Recital 95"@en .

euai:INDUSTRY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "INDUSTRY"@en ;
    skos:definition """**INDUSTRY** consists of private sector stakeholders and economic operators whose expertise is essential to the development and implementation of regulatory frameworks concerning artificial intelligence. 

These entities are formally engaged by the AI Office to provide critical input regarding the establishment of thresholds and benchmarks necessary for systemic risk assessment. Furthermore, in accordance with Article 56(3), these industry stakeholders are invited to actively support and contrib"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CODE_OF_PRACTICE .

euai:INFORMATION_AND_CONSULTATION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "INFORMATION AND CONSULTATION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty for employers to inform or consult workers' representatives under Directive 2002/14/EC regarding the deployment of AI systems (Recital 92)"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:DIRECTIVE_2002_14_EC .

euai:INFORMATION_DISCLOSURE_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "INFORMATION DISCLOSURE OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty to draw up and make available information and documentation for downstream providers of AI systems per Article 53(1)(b)."@en ;
    euai:isBasedOn euai:ANNEX_XII .

euai:INFORMATION_OBLIGATION_FOR_WORKERS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "INFORMATION OBLIGATION FOR WORKERS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty for deployers to inform workers or their representatives about the planned deployment of high-risk AI systems at the workplace (Recital 92)"@en .

euai:INFORMATION_PROVISION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "INFORMATION PROVISION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty of the Board, Member States, and national competent authorities to provide information to the Commission upon request without undue delay"@en .

euai:INITIAL_CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "INITIAL CONFORMITY ASSESSMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "The assessment process where the provider pre-determines changes to the AI system and its performance, referenced in Article 13(3)(c)"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:INSTRUCTIONS_FOR_USE .

euai:INNOVATIVE_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "INNOVATIVE AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "An innovative AI system refers to an artificial intelligence technology that is undergoing development, training, testing, or validation within the structured environment of an AI regulatory sandbox. These systems are specifically designed to be cultivated within this controlled space prior to their formal market entry. The primary purpose of utilizing an AI regulatory sandbox for these systems is to ensure that they are fully compliant with the relevant Regulation and all other applicable laws "@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOX,
        euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT_PROCEDURE,
        euai:LIABILITY_FOR_DAMAGE ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:RISK_MITIGATION .

euai:INPUT_AND_OUTPUT_MODALITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INPUT AND OUTPUT MODALITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "The specific modes of data handling (e.g., text-to-text, multi-modality) and corresponding performance thresholds used to define high-impact capabilities of a model."@en .

euai:INPUT_DATA_RELEVANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INPUT DATA RELEVANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The \"INPUT DATA RELEVANCE\" requirement establishes a specific responsibility for AI deployers. Under this obligation, deployers are mandated to ensure that the input data utilized by an AI system is both relevant and representative of the context in which the AI is intended to operate. This requirement, however, is conditional: it applies specifically to those instances where the deployer exercises control over the selection or processing of the input data. In essence, whenever a deployer has th"@en ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:DEPLOYER .

euai:INTELLECTUAL_PROPERTY_RIGHTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY RIGHTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Rights that must be protected while AI value chain parties cooperate with providers"@en .

euai:INTERNAL_COMPETENCES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INTERNAL COMPETENCES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Sufficient administrative, technical, legal and scientific personnel availability required by notified bodies to evaluate external tasks"@en .

euai:INTERNAL_CONTROL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "INTERNAL CONTROL"@en ;
    skos:definition "A conformity assessment procedure based on internal checks. For high-risk AI systems that are also important and critical products with digital elements, this procedure is subject to specific derogations defined in Recital 78."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT,
        euai:RECITAL_78 .

euai:INTERNAL_GOVERNANCE_AND_RISK_MANAGEMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INTERNAL GOVERNANCE AND RISK MANAGEMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Rules applicable to financial institutions which the AI Act seeks to integrate with to ensure coherence"@en .

euai:INTERNAL_GOVERNANCE_ARRANGEMENTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INTERNAL GOVERNANCE ARRANGEMENTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Rules and processes under Union financial services law that allow financial institutions to fulfill quality management system obligations as per Article 17(4)."@en .

euai:INTERNAL_MARKET a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INTERNAL MARKET"@en ;
    skos:definition "The economic area within the EU that the Regulation aims to improve and harmonize by preventing fragmentation and ensuring free movement of AI-based goods and services"@en .

euai:INTERNAL_MARKET_IMPACT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INTERNAL MARKET IMPACT"@en ;
    skos:definition "A criterion for assessing a model's significance, specifically presumed when the model is available to at least 10,000 registered business users in the Union."@en .

euai:INTERNAL_MARKET_IMPACT_CRITERION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INTERNAL MARKET IMPACT CRITERION"@en ;
    skos:definition "A criterion used to determine a model's impact, specifically presumed high when the model is made available to at least 10,000 registered business users established in the Union."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:REGULATION_2024_1689 .

euai:INTERNAL_MARKET_INTEGRATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INTERNAL MARKET INTEGRATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The objective of ensuring the free movement of AI-based goods and services across borders within the Union"@en .

euai:INTERNAL_PROCEDURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INTERNAL PROCEDURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Procedural requirements for notified bodies to account for provider size, sector, structure, and system complexity"@en .

euai:INTERNAL_PROCESS_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "INTERNAL PROCESS EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The "INTERNAL PROCESS EXCLUSION" refers to a specific regulatory or policy exemption regarding model obligations. This condition establishes that providers of a model are exempt from certain requirements when they utilize their own model exclusively for internal processes. 

For this exclusion to apply, the usage must meet two primary criteria: 
1. The internal processes must not be essential for the provision of a product or service to third parties. 
2. The usage of the model must not adversel"""@en .

euai:INTERNATIONAL_ORGANISATIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "INTERNATIONAL ORGANISATIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition """**INTERNATIONAL ORGANISATIONS**

International organisations are excluded from the scope of the Regulation when they are operating within the framework of cooperation or international agreements specifically related to law enforcement and judicial cooperation. This exclusion is conditional, applying only when these foreign organisations demonstrate that they provide adequate safeguards during their operations."""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:EXCLUSION_FOR_MILITARY__DEFENCE_AND_NATIONAL_SECURITY,
        euai:INTERNATIONAL_COOPERATION_EXCLUSION .

euai:INVESTIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "INVESTIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The process by which the AI Office enforces compliance, involving requests for documentation, evaluations, and measures against non-compliant providers"@en .

euai:JOINT_INVESTIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "JOINT INVESTIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """A "Joint Investigation" refers to collaborative enforcement actions undertaken by market surveillance authorities or the European Commission to address non-compliance issues concerning high-risk AI systems. These actions are conducted in accordance with Article 9 of Regulation (EU) 2019/1020. 

Specifically, these joint investigations are initiated or proposed to effectively manage and rectify situations where high-risk AI systems present serious risks across multiple Member States, ensuring a c"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_9_OF_REGULATION__EU__2019_1020 .

euai:JOINT_INVESTIGATIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "JOINT INVESTIGATIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Collaborative enforcement actions proposed by market surveillance authorities and the Commission to promote compliance or identify non-compliance across Member States"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_9_OF_REGULATION__EU__2019_1020 .

euai:JUDICIAL_AUTHORITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "JUDICIAL AUTHORITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "The **JUDICIAL AUTHORITY** is an independent judicial body mandated with the critical responsibility of overseeing the deployment of biometric identification systems. This entity is exclusively empowered to grant or reject binding, express, and specific authorizations regarding the use of both real-time and post-remote biometric identification systems. By serving as the gatekeeper for these technologies, the **JUDICIAL AUTHORITY** ensures that the application of such invasive identification tool"@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_JUDICIAL_ASSISTANCE ;
    euai:grants euai:AUTHORISATION_FOR_POST_REMOTE_BIOMETRIC_IDENTIFICATION,
        euai:PRIOR_AUTHORISATION ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ADMINISTRATION_OF_JUSTICE_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:KEY_PERFORMANCE_INDICATORS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "KEY PERFORMANCE INDICATORS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Metrics used to measure the achievement of objectives within voluntary codes of conduct"@en .

euai:LARGE_SCALE_IT_SYSTEMS rdfs:label "LARGE SCALE IT SYSTEMS"@en .

euai:LAW_ENFORCEMENT_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "LAW ENFORCEMENT AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "AI systems used for prevention, detection, investigation, and prosecution of criminal offences, excluding specific administrative tasks in tax/customs/financial intelligence units."@en ;
    euai:isExemptFromHighRisk euai:ADMINISTRATIVE_PROCEEDING_EXCLUSION ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_III ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:SECURE_NON_PUBLIC_REGISTRATION .

euai:LAW_ENFORCEMENT_OBJECTIVES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "LAW ENFORCEMENT OBJECTIVES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific objectives allowing the use of real-time remote biometric identification systems, including searching for victims of abduction/trafficking, preventing imminent threats to life, or preventing terrorist attacks."@en .

euai:LAW_ENFORCEMENT__MIGRATION__ASYLUM_AND_BORDER_CONTROL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AnnexIIICategory ;
    rdfs:label "LAW ENFORCEMENT, MIGRATION, ASYLUM AND BORDER CONTROL"@en ;
    skos:definition "High-risk AI use case domains involving sensitive public sector activities"@en .

euai:LAW_ON_THE_PROTECTION_OF_MINORS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "LAW ON THE PROTECTION OF MINORS"@en ;
    skos:definition "National legal provisions for the protection of persons below the age of 18, which remain unaffected by this Regulation insofar as they are not specific to AI systems"@en .

euai:LEGAL_REPRESENTATIVE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "LEGAL REPRESENTATIVE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Entity appointed by a provider established outside the Union to fulfill obligations on their behalf during real-world testing"@en .

euai:LIABILITY_INSURANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "LIABILITY INSURANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Notified bodies must have appropriate liability insurance for conformity assessment activities, unless liability is assumed by the Member State"@en .

euai:LIABILITY_INSURANCE_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "LIABILITY INSURANCE REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Notified bodies must hold appropriate liability insurance for their activities, unless the Member State assumes liability, as per Article 31(9)"@en .

euai:LIABILITY_OF_PROVIDERS_OF_INTERMEDIARY_SERVICES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "LIABILITY OF PROVIDERS OF INTERMEDIARY SERVICES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Legal responsibility of providers of intermediary services as defined in Regulation (EU) 2022/2065, which remains unaffected by this Regulation"@en .

euai:LIST_OF_GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODELS_WITH_SYSTEMIC_RISK rdfs:label "LIST OF GENERAL PURPOSE AI MODELS WITH SYSTEMIC RISK"@en .

euai:LOCAL_PUBLIC_AUTHORITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "LOCAL PUBLIC AUTHORITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Authorities whose needs must be paid special attention to by the Commission when issuing guidelines, as per Article 96(1)"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AWARENESS_RAISING_AND_TRAINING_ACTIVITIES .

euai:LOGGING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "LOGGING"@en ;
    skos:definition "LOGGING, in the context of high-risk AI systems, refers to the essential technical capability to automatically record events over the entire duration of the system's operational lifetime. This process ensures comprehensive traceability and compliance by maintaining a continuous and accurate record of the system's activities and interactions."@en .

euai:LOGGING_CAPABILITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "LOGGING CAPABILITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Technical functionality required by Article 12 to enable the recording of system events"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:LOGS .

euai:LOGGING_MECHANISM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "LOGGING MECHANISM"@en ;
    skos:definition "The **LOGGING MECHANISM** is a necessary technical feature designed to enable deployers to systematically collect, store, and interpret logs. Its primary function is to ensure that these logging activities are conducted in strict accordance with the requirements set forth in Article 12, thereby maintaining full regulatory compliance."@en ;
    euai:regulatedBy euai:ARTICLE_12 .

euai:MANDATE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "MANDATE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The legal instrument establishing the relationship between the provider and the authorised representative, empowering the representative to perform specific tasks."@en .

euai:MARKET_MONITORING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "MARKET MONITORING"@en ;
    skos:definition "The set of rules and measures for overseeing AI systems once placed on the market as defined in Article 1(2)(f)"@en .

euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "MARKET SURVEILLANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The duty to supervise the implementation of the AI Act, including ex post monitoring of AI systems"@en .

euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AND_CONTROL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "MARKET SURVEILLANCE AND CONTROL"@en ;
    skos:definition "The application of Regulation (EU) 2019/1020 to AI systems, including annual reporting to the Commission regarding prohibited practices and competition law interests"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:COMMISSION .

euai:MEASUREMENT_AND_CALCULATION_METHODOLOGIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "MEASUREMENT AND CALCULATION METHODOLOGIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Technical protocols detailed by delegated acts to allow for comparable and verifiable documentation of GPAI model characteristics"@en .

euai:MEMBER_STATE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "MEMBER STATE"@en ;
    skos:definition """A Member State, represented by national experts, plays a multi-faceted and pivotal role in the implementation and oversight of the Act. As the primary national government entities responsible for the Act’s administration, Member States are tasked with transposing the legislation into national law and establishing the necessary domestic frameworks to ensure compliance.

In their oversight capacity, Member States serve as the national entities responsible for enforcing the Regulation and maintaini"""@en ;
    euai:cooperatesWith euai:COMMISSION ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:DOCUMENTATION_KEEPING,
        euai:NOTIFICATION_OF_NATIONAL_RULES ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:COMMON_SPECIFICATIONS,
        euai:CONSULTATION_OF_EXPERTS,
        euai:EUROPEAN_COMMISSION,
        euai:NATIONAL_LAW,
        euai:NOTIFYING_AUTHORITY,
        euai:REAL_TIME_REMOTE_BIOMETRIC_IDENTIFICATION_SYSTEM .

euai:MICROENTERPRISES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "MICROENTERPRISES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Small enterprises (as defined by Recommendation 2003/361/EC) that may benefit from simplified compliance procedures for quality management systems under Article 63"@en ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ARTICLE_9_TO_15_AND_72_TO_73,
        euai:QUALITY_MANAGEMENT_SYSTEM .

euai:MIGRATION__ASYLUM_AND_BORDER_CONTROL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AnnexIIICategory ;
    rdfs:label "MIGRATION, ASYLUM AND BORDER CONTROL"@en ;
    skos:definition "The domain of **MIGRATION, ASYLUM AND BORDER CONTROL** is classified as a high-risk area regarding the deployment of artificial intelligence. Within this sector, AI systems are subject to strict scrutiny when utilized for critical tasks such as risk assessment, the examination of immigration or asylum applications, and the use of polygraph testing. Because these applications directly impact individual rights and legal statuses, these systems must adhere to rigorous standards to ensure fairness, "@en .

euai:MILITARY__DEFENCE_OR_NATIONAL_SECURITY_ACTIVITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "MILITARY, DEFENCE OR NATIONAL SECURITY ACTIVITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Activities related to military, defence, or national security purposes are excluded from the scope of this Regulation"@en .

euai:MILITARY__DEFENCE_OR_NATIONAL_SECURITY_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "MILITARY, DEFENCE OR NATIONAL SECURITY EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The exclusion of AI systems from the Regulation when used for military, defence, or national security purposes, pursuant to Article 4(2) TEU."@en ;
    euai:isBasedOn euai:ARTICLE_4_2__TEU,
        euai:CHAPTER_2_OF_TITLE_V_TEU .

euai:MITIGATING_MEASURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "MITIGATING MEASURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Actions taken by providers to reduce risks, particularly systemic risks, in observance of fundamental rights"@en .

euai:MITIGATION_OF_FORESEEABLE_MISUSE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "MITIGATION OF FORESEEABLE MISUSE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The process of identifying and addressing risks stemming from reasonably foreseeable misuse, distinct from, but related to, standard risk management"@en .

euai:MITIGATION_OF_SIGNIFICANT_RISKS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "MITIGATION OF SIGNIFICANT RISKS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty of providers in sandboxes to act expeditiously and in good faith to mitigate risks to safety, health, and fundamental rights"@en .

euai:MODALITY_THRESHOLD a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "MODALITY THRESHOLD"@en ;
    skos:definition "Assessment of input/output modalities (e.g., text-to-text, text-to-image) and state-of-the-art thresholds determining high-impact capabilities, including specific input types like biological sequences."@en .

euai:MODEL_CAPABILITY_EVALUATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "MODEL CAPABILITY EVALUATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Assessments including benchmarks, task adaptability, autonomy levels, scalability, and access to tools used to evaluate a general-purpose AI model."@en .

euai:MODEL_CARDS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "MODEL CARDS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Documented practice for information sharing along the AI value chain, encouraged for open-source developers"@en .

euai:MODEL_MODIFICATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "MODEL MODIFICATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for providers to update technical documentation and disclose new training data sources when a model is fine-tuned or modified"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION .

euai:MODEL_WEIGHTS_AND_ARCHITECTURE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "MODEL WEIGHTS AND ARCHITECTURE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific information about model parameters and usage that must be publicly available for a model to be considered transparent under an open-source licence, as described in Recital 102 and 104"@en .

euai:MONETISATION_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "MONETISATION EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The condition stating that AI components provided against a price, monetised through technical support/services, or using personal data (excluding microenterprises) do not benefit from open-source exceptions, as described in Recital 103"@en .

euai:MONITORING_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "MONITORING OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The monitoring obligation for deployers of high-risk AI systems requires consistent oversight of the system's operation. This oversight must be conducted in accordance with the provided instructions for use. Specifically, for deployers operating within the financial sector, this obligation is satisfied through compliance with existing governance arrangements established under Union financial services law."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_79_1_ .

euai:MONITORING_OF_SYSTEM_OPERATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "MONITORING OF SYSTEM OPERATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The deployer's duty to monitor the AI system based on the manufacturer's instructions"@en .

euai:MONITORING_OF_THE_FUNCTIONING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "MONITORING OF THE FUNCTIONING"@en ;
    skos:definition "Obligation for deployers to monitor the operation of high-risk AI systems to ensure they function as intended and identify issues (Recital 91)"@en .

euai:MONITORING_OF_THE_PERFORMANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "MONITORING OF THE PERFORMANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty for deployers to observe the functioning of an AI system in a real-life setting"@en .

euai:NATIONAL_ACCREDITATION_BODY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "NATIONAL ACCREDITATION BODY"@en ;
    skos:definition "A body capable of carrying out assessment and monitoring of conformity assessment bodies, as defined under Regulation (EC) No 765/2008"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT_BODY .

euai:NATIONAL_DATA_PROTECTION_AUTHORITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "NATIONAL DATA PROTECTION AUTHORITY"@en ;
    skos:definition """The National Data Protection Authority serves as the competent body responsible for oversight and enforcement concerning data protection laws, particularly those governing biometric identification technologies. Its primary role involves regulatory supervision, including the enforcement of legal prohibitions on the use of remote biometric identification systems outside of specific, authorized law enforcement contexts.

The National Data Protection Authority acts as the central point of contact fo"""@en ;
    euai:enforces euai:ARTICLE_9_1__OF_REGULATION__EU__2016_679,
        euai:PROHIBITION_DECISIONS ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:ANNUAL_REPORTING,
        euai:REPORTING_OBLIGATION ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:EUROPEAN_COMMISSION .

euai:NATIONAL_LABOUR_LAW a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "NATIONAL LABOUR LAW"@en ;
    skos:definition "National legal provisions concerning employment and working conditions that remain unaffected by the Regulation when pursuing legitimate public interest objectives other than those pursued by the AI Act"@en .

euai:NATIONAL_MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "NATIONAL MARKET SURVEILLANCE AUTHORITY"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **National Market Surveillance Authority** serves as a vital regulatory body within a Member State, tasked with the essential dual responsibility of overseeing market surveillance and ensuring data protection compliance. As part of its regulatory mandate, the authority plays a central role in monitoring the implementation of advanced technologies, specifically receiving comprehensive reports regarding the usage of real-time biometric identification systems.

Furthermore, the National Market """@en .

euai:NATIONAL_PUBLIC_AUTHORITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "NATIONAL PUBLIC AUTHORITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Bodies referred to in Article 77(1) that cooperate with market surveillance authorities, particularly regarding risks to fundamental rights"@en .

euai:NATIONAL_REGISTRATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "NATIONAL REGISTRATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for high-risk AI systems referred to in point 2 of Annex III to be registered at the national level instead of the EU database"@en .

euai:NATIONAL_SECURITY_AND_MILITARY_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "NATIONAL SECURITY AND MILITARY EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "AI systems developed and used solely for military, defence, or national security purposes are excluded from the scope of the Regulation"@en .

euai:NATURAL_PERSONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "NATURAL PERSONS"@en ;
    skos:definition """**NATURAL PERSONS** under the scope of the Act are individuals residing within the Union whose fundamental rights, dignity, and protection against non-discrimination are safeguarded against the potential harms of artificial intelligence. These individuals are explicitly shielded by the regulation from prohibited AI practices, such as manipulative profiling and intrusive emotion recognition. 

Furthermore, the Act specifically protects Natural Persons whose biometric data, social behavior, or per"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_SYSTEMS_FOR_EMOTION_INFERENCE .

euai:NEGATIVE_IMPACT_ASSESSMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "NEGATIVE IMPACT ASSESSMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "A specific requirement for codes of conduct focused on assessing and preventing negative impacts on vulnerable persons, including accessibility and gender equality, as per Article 95(2)(e)"@en .

euai:NE_BIS_IN_IDEM_PRINCIPLE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "NE BIS IN IDEM PRINCIPLE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A legal principle that Member States must respect when implementing enforcement measures and penalties for infringements of the Regulation"@en .

euai:NON_COMPLIANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "NON-COMPLIANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A state of failure to meet requirements or obligations, triggering corrective actions or provisional measures by authorities"@en .

euai:NON_COMPLIANCE_PROCEDURE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "NON-COMPLIANCE PROCEDURE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Procedure for addressing non-compliance, including reporting to the Commission and other Member States, and taking restrictive measures such as withdrawal from the market"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_79 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY .

euai:NON_HIGH_RISK a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:RiskCategory ;
    rdfs:label "NON-HIGH-RISK"@en ;
    skos:definition "Classification status granted to AI systems that would normally be high-risk but satisfy the specified exclusion conditions."@en .

euai:NON_HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "NON-HIGH-RISK AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "Any AI system not classified as high-risk, for which providers are encouraged to voluntarily create and adhere to codes of conduct"@en .

euai:NON_REFOULEMENT_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "NON-REFOULEMENT OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The duty to not infringe on the principle of non-refoulement or deny safe and effective legal avenues into the Union when deploying AI systems."@en .

euai:NOTIFICATION_OBJECTION_DEADLINE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "NOTIFICATION OBJECTION DEADLINE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The timeframe within which the Commission or other Member States may raise objections to a notification: two weeks if based on accreditation, two months if based on documentary evidence, as per Article 30(4)"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_30 .

euai:NOTIFICATION_OBLIGATION_TO_NATURAL_PERSONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "NOTIFICATION OBLIGATION TO NATURAL PERSONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty for deployers to inform natural persons when they are subject to the use of a high-risk AI system, including the intended purpose and the type of decisions it makes (Recital 93)"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_13_OF_DIRECTIVE__EU__2016_680 .

euai:NOTIFICATION_OF_AUTHORISATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "NOTIFICATION OF AUTHORISATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The duty of the market surveillance authority to inform the Commission and Member States of any issued authorization for the exceptional use of high-risk AI systems."@en .

euai:NOTIFICATION_OF_CHANGE_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "NOTIFICATION OF CHANGE OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The notified body must inform providers within 10 days if its designation is suspended, restricted, or withdrawn"@en .

euai:NOTIFICATION_TO_MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "NOTIFICATION TO MARKET SURVEILLANCE AUTHORITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Deployers must notify the market surveillance authority of the results of their fundamental rights impact assessment, submitting a completed template"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY .

euai:NOTIFYING_AUTHORITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "NOTIFYING AUTHORITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Authorities responsible for the assessment and notification of notified bodies, cooperating within the Board's standing sub-groups as per Article 65(6)."@en .

euai:OBLIGATION_TO_COMPLY_WITH_MEASURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "OBLIGATION TO COMPLY WITH MEASURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Provider must comply with measures requested under Article 93 and requests for documents/information under Article 91"@en .

euai:OBLIGATION_TO_ENSURE_COMPLIANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "OBLIGATION TO ENSURE COMPLIANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The requirement for entities to ensure the compliance of an AI system if it is used for purposes other than the military, defence, or national security purposes for which it was originally excluded."@en .

euai:OBLIGATION_TO_ESTABLISH_RISK_MANAGEMENT_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "OBLIGATION TO ESTABLISH RISK MANAGEMENT SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty of the provider to establish, implement, document, and maintain a risk management system for high-risk AI systems throughout their lifecycle per Article 9(1)"@en .

euai:OBLIGATION_TO_PROVIDE_ACCESS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "OBLIGATION TO PROVIDE ACCESS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Provider must make available to the Commission access to GPAI models (especially those with systemic risk) for evaluation purposes pursuant to Article 92"@en .

euai:OBLIGATION_TO_TEST a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "OBLIGATION TO TEST"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty of the provider to test high-risk AI systems for compliance and appropriate risk management measures prior to market placement per Article 9(6)-(8)"@en .

euai:OBLIGATION_TO_UPDATE_GUIDELINES rdfs:label "OBLIGATION TO UPDATE GUIDELINES"@en .

euai:ONLINE_MARKETPLACE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "ONLINE MARKETPLACE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Commercial service provider, such as an online platform, where ancillary features (e.g., facial filters) are used to support principal services like product sales."@en .

euai:OPERATOR a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "OPERATOR"@en ;
    skos:definition "The term \"OPERATOR\" functions as a collective, comprehensive designation for any natural or legal person involved in the lifecycle of an AI system who bears specific obligations under the AI Act. This umbrella term encompasses a range of entities along the value chain, specifically including providers, product manufacturers, deployers, authorised representatives, importers, and distributors. As defined in Article 3(8) and referenced in Recital 83 of the New Legislative Framework, these entities "@en ;
    euai:cooperatesWith euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_3 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ADMINISTRATIVE_FINE,
        euai:AUTHORISED_REPRESENTATIVE,
        euai:CORRECTIVE_ACTION,
        euai:DEPLOYER,
        euai:DISTRIBUTOR,
        euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:IMPORTER,
        euai:PRODUCT_MANUFACTURER,
        euai:PROHIBITION_OF_AI_PRACTICES,
        euai:PROVIDER,
        euai:TRANSPARENCY_OBLIGATION ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:CONSULTATION_PROCEDURE,
        euai:HARMONISED_RULES,
        euai:TECHNICAL_AND_ORGANISATIONAL_MEASURES .

euai:OPERATOR_OBLIGATIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "OPERATOR OBLIGATIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for operators (importers, distributors, etc.) to fulfill obligations associated with their roles, which may be cumulative if acting in multiple roles."@en .

euai:OTHER_COMPETENT_AUTHORITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "OTHER COMPETENT AUTHORITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Any national or Union authority with supervisory powers over aspects of an AI system (e.g., data protection or product safety) that are involved in the sandbox operation alongside national competent authorities."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:EXEMPTION_FROM_FINES_FOR_OTHER_LAW .

euai:OTHER_NOTIFIED_BODIES rdfs:label "OTHER NOTIFIED BODIES"@en .

euai:OVERSIGHT_OF_SIGNIFICANT_RISKS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "OVERSIGHT OF SIGNIFICANT RISKS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for adequate mitigation of significant risks to health, safety, and fundamental rights identified during sandbox testing."@en .

euai:PENALTIES_IMPLEMENTATION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PENALTIES IMPLEMENTATION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty for Member States to lay down rules on penalties and enforcement measures, ensuring they are effective, proportionate, and dissuasive, and to notify the Commission"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:COMMISSION .

euai:PERFORMANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "PERFORMANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Technical requirement for AI systems to operate effectively and reliably"@en .

euai:PERFORMANCE_CHARACTERISTICS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "PERFORMANCE CHARACTERISTICS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Mandatory information regarding the AI system's intended purpose, accuracy, robustness, cybersecurity, and limitations that must be included in the instructions for use per Article 13(3)(b)"@en .

euai:PERSONAL_NON_PROFESSIONAL_ACTIVITY_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "PERSONAL NON-PROFESSIONAL ACTIVITY EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The "PERSONAL NON-PROFESSIONAL ACTIVITY EXCLUSION" establishes that the AI Act does not apply to the obligations of deployers who are natural persons using AI systems in the course of a purely personal, non-professional activity. 

There is a noted contradiction in the provided data regarding the specific legal citation for this definition; one source references Article 2(10), while the other cites Article 3(10). Based on the context of the AI Act, the scope and exclusions are typically outlined"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_2 .

euai:PHYSICAL_CE_MARKING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PHYSICAL CE MARKING"@en ;
    skos:definition "A physical marking affixed to high-risk AI systems embedded in a product to indicate conformity with the Regulation"@en .

euai:PLACING_ON_THE_MARKET a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PLACING ON THE MARKET"@en ;
    skos:definition "\"Placing on the market\" refers to a regulated activity defined as the initial instance in which an AI system or a general-purpose AI model is made available on the Union market. This process is strictly governed, requiring that any such AI system must fully comply with all harmonized rules, safety requirements, and fundamental rights protections before it can be offered to the market."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:HARMONISED_RULES .

euai:POOL_OF_EXPERTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "POOL OF EXPERTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "A collective body of expertise available to Member States under Article 69"@en .

euai:POST_MARKETING_MONITORING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "POST-MARKETING MONITORING"@en ;
    skos:definition "A procedural obligation for providers to track the performance and risks of AI systems after they are placed on the market"@en .

euai:POST_MARKET_MONITORING_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "POST-MARKET MONITORING OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The duty for all providers of high-risk AI systems to maintain a post-market monitoring system to allow for system improvement and corrective action."@en .

euai:PRACTICAL_IMPLEMENTATION_GUIDELINES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PRACTICAL IMPLEMENTATION GUIDELINES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Commission-issued guidance intended to provide further clarity on the practical implementation of exclusion conditions, including a comprehensive list of high-risk vs. non-high-risk use cases."@en .

euai:PROCEDURAL_REQUIREMENTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROCEDURAL REQUIREMENTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Mandatory compliance for migration AI systems with Regulation (EC) No 810/2009 and Directive 2013/32/EU."@en .

euai:PROCEDURE_FOR_PROMPT_RECALL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROCEDURE FOR PROMPT RECALL"@en ;
    skos:definition "The provider must establish a procedure to promptly recall the AI system if the testing is terminated or a serious incident occurs, per Article 60(7)"@en .

euai:PROCESSING_OF_SPECIAL_CATEGORIES_OF_PERSONAL_DATA rdfs:label "PROCESSING OF SPECIAL CATEGORIES OF PERSONAL DATA"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:BIAS_DETECTION_AND_CORRECTION .

euai:PRODUCT_COMPLIANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "PRODUCT COMPLIANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The obligation for products placed on the market to meet specific safety, accreditation, and harmonized standards, as referenced in Regulation (EC) No 765/2008 and Decision No 768/2008/EC"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:REGULATION__EC__NO_765_2008 .

euai:PROFESSIONAL_SECRECY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROFESSIONAL SECRECY"@en ;
    skos:definition "The binding duty for staff of notified bodies to observe secrecy regarding information obtained during their tasks, with exceptions only for notifying authorities, per Article 31(7)."@en .

euai:PROFILING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "PROFILING"@en ;
    skos:definition """**PROFILING** is defined as any form of automated processing of personal data that involves utilizing such data to evaluate specific personal aspects related to a natural person. This definition is formally established in Article 4, point (4), of Regulation (EU) 2016/679 (the General Data Protection Regulation or GDPR) and is similarly referenced in Article 3(52) of relevant regulatory frameworks.

In addition to its definition under data protection law, profiling holds significant implications """@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_3_52_,
        euai:ARTICLE_4,
        euai:ARTICLE_4_4_,
        euai:DIRECTIVE__EU__2016_680,
        euai:REGULATION__EU__2018_1725 .

euai:PROFILING_OF_NATURAL_PERSONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ClassificationRule ;
    rdfs:label "PROFILING OF NATURAL PERSONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Rule stating that if an AI system performs profiling, it shall always be considered high-risk, regardless of other exemption conditions"@en .

euai:PROHIBITED_PRACTICES_LIST a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ClassificationRule ;
    rdfs:label "PROHIBITED PRACTICES LIST"@en ;
    skos:definition "The list of prohibited AI practices which the Commission must assess for potential amendment annually, as per Recital 174"@en .

euai:PROHIBITION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROHIBITION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The legal duty to not place on the market, put into service, or use specific AI systems classified as unacceptable risk under Article 5."@en .

euai:PROHIBITION_DECISIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROHIBITION DECISIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Decisions made by national data protection authorities to stop the use of remote biometric identification for non-law enforcement purposes"@en .

euai:PROHIBITION_OF_BIOMETRIC_CATEGORISATION_SYSTEMS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROHIBITION OF BIOMETRIC CATEGORISATION SYSTEMS"@en ;
    skos:definition "A ban on systems deducing sensitive personal data via biometric identification, detailed in Recital 30."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_30 .

euai:PROHIBITION_OF_CERTAIN_AI_PRACTICES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROHIBITION OF CERTAIN AI PRACTICES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement to cease practices deemed to carry an unacceptable risk, effective from 2 February 2025"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:APPLICATION_DATE_2_FEBRUARY_2025 .

euai:PROHIBITION_OF_CONSULTANCY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROHIBITION OF CONSULTANCY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Notifying authorities are prohibited from performing activities that conformity assessment bodies perform or providing consultancy services on a commercial or competitive basis, as per Article 29(5)"@en .

euai:PROHIBITION_OF_EXPLOITATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROHIBITION OF EXPLOITATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Prohibition on placing, putting into service, or using AI systems that exploit vulnerabilities of natural persons (Article 5(1)(b))"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_5 .

euai:PROHIBITION_OF_FACIAL_RECOGNITION_SCRAPING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROHIBITION OF FACIAL RECOGNITION SCRAPING"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty not to place on the market, put into service, or use AI systems that create facial recognition databases via untargeted scraping."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_5 .

euai:PROHIBITION_OF_MANIPULATIVE_TECHNIQUES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROHIBITION OF MANIPULATIVE TECHNIQUES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Prohibition on placing, putting into service, or using AI systems that deploy subliminal techniques to distort behavior (Article 5(1)(a))"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_5 .

euai:PROHIBITION_OF_PREDICTIVE_RISK_ASSESSMENTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROHIBITION OF PREDICTIVE RISK ASSESSMENTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty not to deploy AI systems that predict criminal behavior based solely on individual profiling or personality traits."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_5 .

euai:PROMPT_REPORTING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROMPT REPORTING"@en ;
    skos:definition "The requirement to report serious incidents immediately after establishing a causal link between the AI system and the incident (Article 73(2))."@en .

euai:PROPORTIONALITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "PROPORTIONALITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for the use of post-remote biometric identification systems to be targeted and strictly necessary to the goal (Recital 95)"@en .

euai:PROSPECTIVE_PROVIDER a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "PROSPECTIVE PROVIDER"@en ;
    skos:definition """A "Prospective Provider" is a natural or legal person—such as an SME, start-up, or other innovator—that intends to develop, place on the market, or deploy an AI system within the Union. This status characterizes entities currently in the preparatory phases of AI development or implementation rather than those who have already finalized their product.

Prospective Providers are subject to specific regulatory requirements, particularly those concerning the submission and adherence to real-world te"""@en ;
    euai:cooperatesWith euai:DEPLOYER ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:EU_DATABASE,
        euai:MITIGATION_OF_SIGNIFICANT_RISKS,
        euai:REAL_WORLD_TESTING,
        euai:WRITTEN_AGREEMENT ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOX,
        euai:COMPETENT_AUTHORITY,
        euai:EXEMPTION_FROM_FINES_FOR_OTHER_LAW,
        euai:INFORMED_CONSENT,
        euai:REAL_WORLD_TESTING_PLAN,
        euai:TESTING_AND_EXPERIMENTATION_FACILITY ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:EXEMPTION_FROM_ADMINISTRATIVE_FINES .

euai:PROTECTION_OF_CONFIDENTIAL_INFORMATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROTECTION OF CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty of authorities to protect intellectual property, trade secrets, public security, and confidential business information when carrying out their tasks"@en .

euai:PROTECTION_OF_VULNERABLE_GROUPS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "PROTECTION OF VULNERABLE GROUPS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Mandatory safeguards for testing subjects who are vulnerable due to age or disability, per Article 60(g)"@en .

euai:PROTECTION_OF_WHISTLEBLOWERS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROTECTION OF WHISTLEBLOWERS"@en ;
    skos:definition "The requirement to protect individuals reporting infringements of the Regulation, enforced via Directive (EU) 2019/1937, as per Recital 172"@en .

euai:PROTOCOL_NO_22 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "PROTOCOL NO 22"@en ;
    skos:definition "Protocol attached to the TEU and TFEU regarding the position of Denmark, which creates an exclusion condition for the application of specific AI Act provisions."@en .

euai:PROVIDER_NOTIFICATION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROVIDER NOTIFICATION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The requirement for the notified body to inform concerned providers within 10 days of a suspension or restriction."@en .

euai:PROVIDER_TRANSITION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROVIDER TRANSITION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The requirement for a provider to secure a new qualified notified body within three months if the current one is suspended/restricted and lacks the capability to support existing certificates."@en .

euai:PROVISIONAL_MEASURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROVISIONAL MEASURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Measures taken by market surveillance authorities (prohibit, restrict, withdraw, recall) if an operator fails to take adequate corrective action"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:EUROPEAN_COMMISSION .

euai:PROVISION_OF_STANDARDISED_TEMPLATES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROVISION OF STANDARDISED TEMPLATES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty of the AI Office to provide standardised templates for areas covered by the Regulation, upon request by the Board."@en .

euai:PUBLICLY_ACCESSIBLE_SPACES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "PUBLICLY ACCESSIBLE SPACES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Environmental context where the use of real-time remote biometric identification systems is strictly regulated"@en .

euai:PUBLIC_AND_PRIVATE_ACTORS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "PUBLIC AND PRIVATE ACTORS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Entities (including SMEs and startups) involved in creating AI systems within the European ecosystem, adhering to Union values"@en ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:HARMONISED_RULES .

euai:PUTTING_INTO_SERVICE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PUTTING INTO SERVICE"@en ;
    skos:definition "\"Putting into service\" refers to the regulated activity involving the initial launch or utilization of an AI system within the Union for its intended purpose. This process encompasses two primary scenarios: either the supply of an AI system for its first use directly to a deployer, or the use of an AI system for one’s own purposes. As a regulated activity, \"putting into service\" requires that AI systems adhere to all specific regulatory obligations and compliance standards before they are utiliz"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:HARMONISED_RULES .

euai:Provider a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Provider"@en ;
    rdfs:subClassOf euai:Actor ;
    skos:definition "A natural or legal person that develops or places an AI system on the market. (Article 3(3))"@en .

euai:QUALIFIED_ALERTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "QUALIFIED ALERTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "**QUALIFIED ALERTS** are a mechanism designed to enhance the oversight of general-purpose AI models. They serve as a critical notification system where the scientific panel informs the AI Office about potential systemic risks associated with specific AI models—risks that may have been previously overlooked by the European Commission or the model provider. Furthermore, these alerts function as formal notifications regarding general-purpose AI models, which are then reviewed by the Board. Followin"@en .

euai:QUALITY_MANAGEMENT_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "QUALITY MANAGEMENT REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "A specific operational standard that notified bodies must satisfy to fulfill their tasks, ensuring consistency and reliability of conformity assessments under Article 31(2)."@en .

euai:QUESTIONNAIRE_TEMPLATE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "QUESTIONNAIRE TEMPLATE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A tool developed by the AI Office to assist deployers in conducting fundamental rights impact assessments and reducing administrative burden per Recital 96"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:FUNDAMENTAL_RIGHTS_IMPACT_ASSESSMENT .

euai:REASSESSMENT_OF_SYSTEMIC_RISK a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REASSESSMENT OF SYSTEMIC RISK"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty/right involving a process where providers can request a review of their systemic risk designation at least six months after a decision, per Article 53 preamble context."@en .

euai:REASSESSMENT_REQUEST a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REASSESSMENT REQUEST"@en ;
    skos:definition "Providers designated with systemic risk can request a reassessment of their model's status based on new, objective, and detailed reasons, subject to a minimum six-month interval between requests (Article 52(5))"@en .

euai:RECALL_OF_AN_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "RECALL OF AN AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "Measure aiming to achieve the return to the provider, taking out of service, or disabling the use of an AI system made available to deployers"@en .

euai:RECITALS_106_110 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITALS 106-110"@en ;
    skos:definition "The section of the EU AI Act providing context and explanatory justification for transparency obligations for general-purpose AI models and systemic risk definitions"@en .

euai:RECITALS_29_30 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITALS 29-30"@en ;
    skos:definition "Recitals detailing the rationale for prohibiting specific AI practices involving manipulation, deception, exploitation of vulnerabilities, and sensitive biometric categorisation."@en .

euai:RECITAL_13 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 13"@en ;
    skos:definition "RECITAL 13 serves to define the notion of a \"deployer\" specifically within the context and regulatory framework of the AI Act."@en .

euai:RECITAL_14 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 14"@en ;
    skos:definition "Recital 14 serves as a formal provision that references external regulations to establish a precise definition for the term \"biometric data.\" By incorporating these external standards, Recital 14 ensures clarity and consistency in the interpretation of biometric information within the applicable legal framework."@en .

euai:RECITAL_15 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 15"@en ;
    skos:definition """**RECITAL 15**

RECITAL 15 serves as a foundational clarification within the relevant regulatory framework by explicitly defining the concept of "biometric identification." Furthermore, it establishes a clear distinction between this term and "biometric verification," ensuring that the regulatory scope correctly differentiates between the two processes for legal and technical clarity."""@en .

euai:RECITAL_16 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 16"@en ;
    skos:definition "Recital defining 'biometric categorisation' and providing exclusions for ancillary features."@en .

euai:RECITAL_28 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 28"@en ;
    skos:definition "Reference to Recital 28, covering the prohibition of manipulative and exploitative AI practices due to contradictions with Union values"@en .

euai:RECITAL_31 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 31"@en ;
    skos:definition "**RECITAL 31** serves as a critical regulatory provision that addresses the significant risks associated with the use of artificial intelligence (AI) systems for the social scoring of natural persons. It specifically outlines the prohibition of such practices, establishing that AI systems designed or deployed to evaluate or classify individuals based on their social behavior or personal characteristics—often resulting in detrimental or unfavorable treatment—are deemed unacceptable. By providing "@en .

euai:RECITAL_32 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 32"@en ;
    skos:definition "**RECITAL 32** serves as a critical regulatory provision addressing the significant concerns surrounding the deployment of real-time remote biometric identification systems within public spaces. This recital highlights the inherently intrusive nature of such technologies, emphasizing that their usage poses substantial risks, particularly concerning privacy, civil liberties, and the potential for discriminatory outcomes. By identifying these dangers, RECITAL 32 provides essential context regardin"@en .

euai:RECITAL_44 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 44"@en ;
    skos:definition "Recital discussing the risks of emotion recognition AI and the prohibition in workplace and education contexts"@en .

euai:RECITAL_49 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 49"@en ;
    skos:definition "RECITAL 49 is a component of the AI Act preamble that addresses the necessary adjustments to existing legal frameworks. Specifically, this recital concerns the amendment of sector-specific Union harmonisation legislation to ensure that these existing laws are updated to incorporate the new requirements established by the AI Act, particularly those pertaining to high-risk AI systems. By integrating these obligations, RECITAL 49 ensures that the regulatory oversight of high-risk AI is consistently"@en .

euai:RECITAL_50 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 50"@en ;
    skos:definition "**RECITAL 50** of the AI Act serves as a foundational provision within the preamble, delineating the specific criteria used to classify certain artificial intelligence systems as high-risk. Specifically, RECITAL 50 establishes that AI systems functioning as safety components within products—or which are themselves products—must be designated as high-risk if those items are subject to a third-party conformity assessment under existing Union harmonisation legislation. By defining this classificati"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:RECITAL_54 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 54"@en ;
    skos:definition "Recital regarding classification of biometric systems as high-risk or excluded (Recital 54)"@en .

euai:RECITAL_55 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 55"@en ;
    skos:definition "Recital regarding classification of critical infrastructure safety components as high-risk (Recital 55)"@en .

euai:RECITAL_56 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 56"@en ;
    skos:definition "Recital regarding classification of AI systems in education and vocational training as high-risk (Recital 56)"@en .

euai:RECITAL_59 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 59"@en ;
    skos:definition "Recital in the EU AI Act providing context on the high-risk classification of law enforcement AI systems"@en .

euai:RECITAL_66 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 66"@en ;
    skos:definition "Text describing requirements for high-risk AI systems including risk management and provision of instructions for use"@en .

euai:RECITAL_67 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 67"@en ;
    skos:definition "Text defining requirements for high-quality data, data governance, and mitigation of bias for high-risk AI systems"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:DATA_SETS ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CERTIFIED_COMPLIANCE_SERVICES,
        euai:PRIVACY_PRESERVING_TECHNIQUES .

euai:RECITAL_68 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 68"@en ;
    skos:definition "Text identifying actors like providers, notified bodies, and researchers who should have access to data for high-risk AI system assessment"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:EUROPEAN_DIGITAL_INNOVATION_HUBS,
        euai:NOTIFIED_BODY,
        euai:RESEARCHERS,
        euai:TESTING_EXPERIMENTATION_FACILITIES .

euai:RECITAL_74 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 74"@en ;
    skos:definition "The section detailing requirements for consistency, accuracy, robustness, and cybersecurity, and the role of the Commission in metrology."@en .

euai:RECITAL_75 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 75"@en ;
    skos:definition "The section focusing on technical robustness, resilience against harmful behavior, and the need for fail-safe plans."@en .

euai:RECITAL_76 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 76"@en ;
    skos:definition """**RECITAL 76** addresses the critical intersection of safety, security, and operational integrity within AI systems. It outlines the comprehensive landscape of risks associated with AI operations, specifically highlighting the potential for system anomalies that could lead to significant safety impacts. By focusing on these risks, RECITAL 76 emphasizes the necessity of robust oversight to ensure that AI deployments remain safe and predictable under varying conditions.

Furthermore, RECITAL 76 pr"""@en .

euai:RECITAL_78 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 78"@en ;
    skos:definition "Text outlining the conformity assessment procedures for products with digital elements that are also classified as high-risk AI systems."@en .

euai:RECITAL_95 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 95"@en ;
    skos:definition "Recital addressing the use of post-remote biometric identification systems and associated safeguards"@en .

euai:RECITAL_96 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 96"@en ;
    skos:definition "Recital mandating fundamental rights impact assessments for deployers of high-risk AI systems"@en .

euai:RECITAL_97 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 97"@en ;
    skos:definition "Recital outlining the definition of general-purpose AI models"@en .

euai:REFERENCE_DATABASE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "REFERENCE DATABASE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A repository of stored biometric data against which an individual’s biometric data is compared for the purpose of identification."@en .

euai:REFERENCE_DATABASE_OF_PERSONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "REFERENCE DATABASE OF PERSONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "The specific database of persons that must be appropriate for each use case in the context of remote biometric identification."@en .

euai:REGISTRATION_IN_DATABASE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REGISTRATION IN DATABASE"@en ;
    skos:definition "**REGISTRATION IN DATABASE** refers to a mandatory obligation imposed on law enforcement authorities regarding the deployment of real-time remote biometric identification systems. Under the Regulation, these authorities are required to formally register the use of such systems in a designated database prior to their deployment or use. This procedure ensures regulatory compliance and oversight, serving as a prerequisite for operational activity, unless specific exemptions or alternative provision"@en .

euai:REGISTRATION_OBLIGATIONS rdfs:label "REGISTRATION OBLIGATIONS"@en .

euai:REGISTRATION_OF_ENTRY_AND_EXIT_DATA a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "REGISTRATION OF ENTRY AND EXIT DATA"@en ;
    skos:definition "A core functional requirement for the Entry/Exit System to manage border crossing data."@en .

euai:REGULATED_FINANCIAL_INSTITUTIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATED FINANCIAL INSTITUTIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Entities such as credit institutions, insurance and re-insurance undertakings, and insurance intermediaries subject to Union financial services law, which may use AI systems"@en ;
    euai:reducedObligationsApplyTo euai:POST_MARKETING_MONITORING,
        euai:QUALITY_MANAGEMENT_SYSTEM,
        euai:TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:INTERNAL_GOVERNANCE_AND_RISK_MANAGEMENT .

euai:REGULATION_2019_2144 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION 2019/2144"@en ;
    skos:definition "Regulation (EU) 2019/2144 is a legislative framework that has been subject to specific updates through the Artificial Intelligence Act. Notably, this regulation has been amended by Article 109 of the AI Act, with the revisions specifically addressing AI safety components within the scope of the regulation."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_11 .

euai:REGULATION_EVALUATION_AND_REVIEW a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION EVALUATION AND REVIEW"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Commission must evaluate and review the Regulation by 2 August 2029 and every four years thereafter (Recital 174)."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:COUNCIL,
        euai:EUROPEAN_PARLIAMENT .

euai:REGULATION__EC__NO_810_2009 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EC) NO 810/2009"@en ;
    skos:definition "Regulation (EC) No 810/2009, commonly referred to as the Visa Code, establishes the harmonized procedures and conditions for the issuance of visas for short-term stays in the territory of the European Union. Beyond its primary function in facilitating visa processing, this regulation is also significant in the context of the European Union's technological governance, as it is considered relevant to the implementation of high-risk artificial intelligence systems within the fields of migration, as"@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2016_679__GDPR_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2016/679 (GDPR)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Regulation (EU) 2016/679, commonly known as the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), is a piece of European Union legislation designed to protect natural persons with regard to the processing of their personal data. It sets the foundational data processing obligations that must be adhered to by various technologies, including AI systems. Furthermore, this regulation remains fully in effect and remains unaffected by the introduction of the AI Act, continuing to serve as a primary framework "@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_SYSTEM .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2017_2226 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2017/2226"@en ;
    skos:definition "Regulation (EU) 2017/2226 is the legislative act and legal instrument that formally establishes the Entry/Exit System (EES) of the European Union."@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2018_1139 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2018/1139"@en ;
    skos:definition """**REGULATION (EU) 2018/1139** serves as the foundational legal framework establishing common rules in the field of civil aviation and creating the European Union Aviation Safety Agency (EASA). Its primary purpose is to ensure a high and uniform level of civil aviation safety throughout the European Union.

To keep pace with technological advancements, the regulation has been updated to address modern challenges. Notably, REGULATION (EU) 2018/1139 was amended by Article 108 to explicitly incorpor"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:EUROPEAN_UNION_AVIATION_SAFETY_AGENCY .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2018_1240 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2018/1240"@en ;
    skos:definition "Regulation (EU) 2018/1240 is the legislative act and legal instrument that formally established the European Travel Information and Authorisation System (ETIAS)."@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2018_1241 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2018/1241"@en ;
    skos:definition "The legislative act amending Regulation (EU) 2016/794 to establish ETIAS."@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2018_1860 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2018/1860"@en ;
    skos:definition "Legislation on the use of the Schengen Information System for the return of illegally staying third-country nationals"@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2018_1861 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2018/1861"@en ;
    skos:definition "Legislation on the establishment, operation and use of the Schengen Information System (SIS) for border checks"@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2018_1862 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2018/1862"@en ;
    skos:definition "Legislation on the establishment, operation and use of the Schengen Information System (SIS) for police and judicial cooperation"@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2018_858 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2018/858"@en ;
    skos:definition """Regulation (EU) 2018/858 is the primary legislative framework concerning the approval and market surveillance of motor vehicles and their trailers, as well as the systems, components, and separate technical units intended for such vehicles. This regulation establishes a comprehensive set of rules ensuring that vehicles and their associated parts meet rigorous safety and performance standards before they can be placed on the market.

Furthermore, the regulation has been updated to address modern """@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2019_816 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2019/816"@en ;
    skos:definition "Regulation (EU) 2019/816 is a legislative act and legal instrument that established the European Criminal Records Information System for Third-Country Nationals (ECRIS-TCN system). This legislation serves as the foundational framework for the creation and implementation of the ECRIS-TCN, a centralized system designed to facilitate the exchange of criminal record information regarding non-EU citizens within the European Union."@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2019_817 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2019/817"@en ;
    skos:definition "Legislation establishing the interoperability framework for borders and visa systems"@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2019_818 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2019/818"@en ;
    skos:definition "Legislation establishing the interoperability framework for police, judicial, asylum, and migration systems"@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2021_1133 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2021/1133"@en ;
    skos:definition "Legislation amending conditions for accessing EU information systems for the purposes of the Visa Information System"@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2021_1134 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2021/1134"@en ;
    skos:definition "Legislation reforming the Visa Information System"@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2023_988 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2023/988"@en ;
    skos:definition """REGULATION (EU) 2023/988 serves as a pivotal piece of legislation focused on general product safety. It functions as a critical safety net, specifically designed to address AI systems that do not fall under the "high-risk" classification outlined in the AI Act.

Furthermore, this Regulation interacts significantly with the broader market surveillance frameworks established by the AI Act, as noted in Recital 53. By bridging these regulatory gaps, REGULATION (EU) 2023/988 ensures that products—inc"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DIRECTIVE__EU__2019_1937 .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2024_1358 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2024/1358"@en ;
    skos:definition "Regulation (EU) 2024/1358 is a legislative act that serves as the legal instrument establishing the Eurodac system. This regulation is specifically designed to facilitate the comparison of biometric data as part of the European Union’s broader framework for managing asylum and migration."@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2024_900 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2024/900"@en ;
    skos:definition "**Regulation (EU) 2024/900** is a legislative act known as the Regulation on the transparency and targeting of political advertising. This regulation establishes a framework of rules designed to ensure democratic processes are upheld. Furthermore, it operates in conjunction with the AI Act, as explicitly noted in Recital 62 of that legislation, ensuring that the use of artificial intelligence in the context of political advertising adheres to established transparency and fairness standards."@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__NO_182_2011 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) NO 182/2011"@en ;
    skos:definition "Reference to the regulation governing the exercise of implementing powers conferred on the Commission (Recital 175)"@en .

euai:REGULATORY_AUTHORITIES_OF_THIRD_COUNTRIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATORY AUTHORITIES OF THIRD COUNTRIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Entities in third countries with whom the Commission or Member States may exchange confidential information under bilateral or multilateral arrangements"@en .

euai:REGULATORY_SANDBOXES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATORY SANDBOXES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Testing environment for AI systems, applicable even to research and development activities that result in market placement"@en .

euai:REPORTING_DEADLINE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REPORTING DEADLINE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The requirement to report serious incidents not later than 15 days after the provider or deployer becomes aware of the incident (Article 73(2))."@en .

euai:REPORTING_OBLIGATION__RISK_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REPORTING OBLIGATION (RISK)"@en ;
    skos:definition "The requirement for a deployer to inform the provider, distributor, and market surveillance authority if an AI system poses a risk"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY .

euai:REPORTING_OBLIGATION__SERIOUS_INCIDENT_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REPORTING OBLIGATION (SERIOUS INCIDENT)"@en ;
    skos:definition "The requirement for a deployer to immediately inform the provider, importer, distributor, and market surveillance authority of a serious incident"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY .

euai:REPORTING_OF_SERIOUS_INCIDENTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REPORTING OF SERIOUS INCIDENTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "The duty for providers to report serious incidents to market surveillance authorities within specific deadlines (Article 73)."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_73 ;
    euai:hasDeadline euai:REPORTING_DEADLINE ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY ;
    euai:triggers euai:PROMPT_REPORTING .

euai:REQUEST_FOR_INFORMATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REQUEST FOR INFORMATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "A mandatory requirement for a provider to submit documentation (per Articles 53/55) or additional information to the Commission/AI Office, subject to fines for non-compliance"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_91 ;
    euai:hasConsequence euai:ARTICLE_101 ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:PROVIDER_OF_GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL .

euai:REQUIREMENTS_FOR_HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEMS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REQUIREMENTS FOR HIGH-RISK AI SYSTEMS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Mandatory duties imposed on high-risk AI systems to ensure safety and compliance, derived from the risk-based approach of the Regulation"@en .

euai:REQUIREMENTS_SET_OUT_IN_CHAPTER_III__SECTION_2 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "REQUIREMENTS SET OUT IN CHAPTER III, SECTION 2"@en ;
    skos:definition "The specific technical and organisational requirements (such as risk management, data governance, etc.) that the technical documentation must demonstrate compliance with."@en .

euai:RESEARCHERS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "RESEARCHERS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Individuals or groups engaged in research, who may access data for the development and assessment of high-risk AI systems"@en .

euai:RESOURCE_PROVISION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "RESOURCE PROVISION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Member States must ensure national competent authorities have adequate technical, financial, and human resources."@en .

euai:RESOURCE_PROVISION_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RESOURCE PROVISION REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for Member States to ensure national competent authorities have adequate technical, financial, and human resources (Article 70(3))."@en .

euai:RESOURCE_REPORTING_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "RESOURCE REPORTING OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Member States must report to the Commission every two years on the status of financial and human resources of national competent authorities"@en .

euai:REVERSIBILITY_OF_AI_OUTPUTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "REVERSIBILITY OF AI OUTPUTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "A safeguard ensuring that predictions, recommendations, or decisions of an AI system can be effectively reversed and disregarded"@en .

euai:REVERSIBILITY_OF_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "REVERSIBILITY OF AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "The requirement that predictions, recommendations, or decisions of the AI system can be effectively reversed and disregarded, per Article 60(k)"@en .

euai:RIGHTS_OF_DEFENCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RIGHTS OF DEFENCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Procedural guarantees for parties involved in proceedings conducted by the European Data Protection Supervisor, including the right to be heard and access to the file, subject to personal data and business secret protections."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:EUROPEAN_DATA_PROTECTION_SUPERVISOR .

euai:RISK_ANALYTICS_AI_SYSTEMS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "RISK ANALYTICS AI SYSTEMS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Systems using risk analytics not based on individual profiling (e.g., financial fraud detection or narcotics trafficking prediction), which are permitted under Recital 42."@en ;
    euai:isExemptFromHighRisk euai:EXCLUSION_FOR_RISK_ANALYTICS .

euai:RISK_ASSESSMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RISK ASSESSMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "A technical/organizational requirement to evaluate the risks associated with the serious incident as part of the investigation."@en .

euai:RISK_ESTIMATION_AND_EVALUATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RISK ESTIMATION AND EVALUATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The process of estimating and evaluating risks when the system is used as intended or under reasonably foreseeable misuse, as required by Article 9(2)(b)"@en .

euai:RISK_IDENTIFICATION_AND_ANALYSIS rdfs:label "RISK IDENTIFICATION AND ANALYSIS"@en .

euai:RISK_LEVEL_EVALUATION_METHODOLOGY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RISK LEVEL EVALUATION METHODOLOGY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Methodology developed by the AI Office to guide evaluations and reviews regarding risk levels and classification inclusion"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_III,
        euai:ARTICLE_5,
        euai:ARTICLE_50 .

euai:RISK_MANAGEMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RISK MANAGEMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "A requirement for high-risk AI systems to identify, estimate, evaluate, and mitigate risks associated with the intended purpose and reasonably foreseeable misuse"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_66 .

euai:RISK_MANAGEMENT_AND_COMPLIANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RISK MANAGEMENT AND COMPLIANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Mandatory requirements for high-risk AI systems laid down in the Regulation"@en .

euai:RISK_MANAGEMENT_MEASURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RISK MANAGEMENT MEASURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Appropriate and targeted actions adopted to address identified risks, ensuring residual risk is acceptable, as described in Article 9(2)(d) and 9(5)"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_13,
        euai:RESIDUAL_RISK .

euai:RISK_MANAGEMENT_POLICIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RISK MANAGEMENT POLICIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Internal processes (accountability, governance) that providers of GPAI models with systemic risks must implement to identify and mitigate risks."@en .

euai:RISK_MANAGEMENT_POLICY rdfs:label "RISK MANAGEMENT POLICY"@en .

euai:RISK_TO_FUNDAMENTAL_RIGHTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:RiskCategory ;
    rdfs:label "RISK TO FUNDAMENTAL RIGHTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "A specific risk classification used by authorities to determine enforcement actions when AI systems impact the rights of persons"@en .

euai:RISK_TO_HEALTH__SAFETY_OR_FUNDAMENTAL_RIGHTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:RiskCategory ;
    rdfs:label "RISK TO HEALTH, SAFETY OR FUNDAMENTAL RIGHTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "A threshold that triggers specific safeguard procedures for enforcement against AI systems."@en .

euai:SAFEGUARD_PROCEDURE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "SAFEGUARD PROCEDURE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A specific enforcement mechanism for ensuring adequate and timely action against AI systems that present a risk to health, safety, or fundamental rights."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:RISK_TO_HEALTH__SAFETY_OR_FUNDAMENTAL_RIGHTS .

euai:SAFETY_COMPONENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "SAFETY COMPONENT"@en ;
    skos:definition """A "SAFETY COMPONENT" is defined as a critical element within a product that is subject to specific safety legislation, particularly in the context of high-risk AI systems as outlined in Recital 87. These are AI systems or pieces of software functioning as essential components of products, such as autonomous robots, that fall under Union harmonisation legislation based on the New Legislative Framework.

Because of their role in these systems, "SAFETY COMPONENT" entities are subject to strict regu"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_I_PRODUCT_SAFETY_COMPONENT_RULE,
        euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:PRODUCT_MANUFACTURER .

euai:SAFETY_COMPONENT_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "SAFETY COMPONENT AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Safety Component AI Systems**

A Safety Component AI System is defined as an artificial intelligence system that functions as a safety component of a product, or serves as a product in its own right. These systems are specifically characterized by their role in ensuring the safe operation of the technology they are integrated into or constitute. Due to the critical nature of their function, these AI systems are subject to Union harmonization legislation. When an AI system acts as a safety comp"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_47 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:HIGH_RISK_CLASSIFICATION_RULE,
        euai:UNION_HARMONISATION_LEGISLATION .

euai:SAFETY_COMPONENT_DEFINITION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ClassificationRule ;
    rdfs:label "SAFETY COMPONENT DEFINITION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The rule defining a safety component as a system used to directly protect the physical integrity of critical infrastructure or the health and safety of persons/property, provided it is not necessary for the functioning of the system (Recital 55)"@en .

euai:SAFETY_NET a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "SAFETY NET"@en ;
    skos:definition "The application of Regulation (EU) 2023/988 as a mechanism to ensure AI systems not classified as high-risk remain safe"@en .

euai:SANDBOX_REPORTING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "SANDBOX REPORTING"@en ;
    skos:definition "National competent authorities must submit annual and final reports to the AI Office and the Board regarding sandbox progress, results, best practices, and lessons learned."@en .

euai:SCHENGEN_INFORMATION_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "SCHENGEN INFORMATION SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Schengen Information System (SIS) is a large-scale IT system dedicated to the management of security and borders. It is formally recognized as a relevant Union legislative act, specifically listed under Annex X of the applicable regulations governing its operation."@en ;
    euai:regulatedBy euai:REGULATION__EU__2018_1860,
        euai:REGULATION__EU__2018_1861,
        euai:REGULATION__EU__2018_1862 .

euai:SCIENTIFIC_COMMUNITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "SCIENTIFIC COMMUNITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "External experts engaged by the AI Office to provide input on thresholds and benchmarks for systemic risk assessment."@en .

euai:SCIENTIFIC_RESEARCH_AND_DEVELOPMENT_ACTIVITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "SCIENTIFIC RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT ACTIVITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "AI systems and models specifically developed and put into service for the sole purpose of scientific research and development are excluded from the scope of this Regulation prior to being placed on the market or put into service"@en .

euai:SCIENTIFIC_RESEARCH_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "SCIENTIFIC RESEARCH EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "AI systems and models developed and put into service for the sole purpose of scientific research and development are excluded from the scope of the Regulation"@en .

euai:SECTION_2_OF_THIS_CHAPTER a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "SECTION 2 OF THIS CHAPTER"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific requirements applicable to high-risk AI systems as referenced throughout the text (often related to technical documentation, record-keeping, etc.)"@en .

euai:SECTION_A_OF_ANNEX_I a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "SECTION A OF ANNEX I"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific section listing products covered by Union harmonisation legislation, for which only specific derogations apply."@en .

euai:SECTORAL_GROUP_OF_NOTIFIED_BODIES rdfs:label "SECTORAL GROUP OF NOTIFIED BODIES"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:COMMISSION .

euai:SECURE_NON_PUBLIC_REGISTRATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "SECURE NON-PUBLIC REGISTRATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific obligation for certain high-risk AI systems (law enforcement, migration, etc.) to be registered in a secure, non-public section of the EU database rather than the public section"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_71 ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ANNEX_IX,
        euai:ANNEX_VIII .

euai:SECURITY_CONTROLS rdfs:label "SECURITY CONTROLS"@en .

euai:SEGREGATION_OF_DUTIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "SEGREGATION OF DUTIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Operational requirement mandating that decisions relating to the notification of conformity assessment bodies be taken by different persons than those who carried out the assessment, as per Article 29(4)"@en .

euai:SIGNIFICANT_DESIGN_CHANGE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "SIGNIFICANT DESIGN CHANGE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A trigger condition for existing high-risk AI systems to become subject to this Regulation if they undergo major design modifications after 2 August 2026 (Article 111(2))"@en .

euai:SIGNIFICANT_HARM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:RiskCategory ;
    rdfs:label "SIGNIFICANT HARM"@en ;
    skos:definition "The threshold of adverse impact (physical, psychological, financial) required to trigger prohibitions on manipulative AI systems."@en .

euai:SOCIAL_NETWORK_SERVICE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "SOCIAL NETWORK SERVICE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Service provider where ancillary features (e.g., facial/body filters) are used to modify or add to content, intrinsically linked to the service of online content sharing."@en .

euai:SOCIAL_SCORING_AI_SYSTEMS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "SOCIAL SCORING AI SYSTEMS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Social scoring AI systems are technologies designed to evaluate, classify, or rank natural persons or groups based on their social behavior, personality traits, or personal characteristics over a period of time. Because these systems often result in discriminatory or detrimental outcomes for the individuals or groups being assessed, they are subject to strict regulatory prohibition. Specifically, as outlined in Recital 31, these systems are banned due to the risks they pose in unfairly categoriz"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:PROHIBITED_AI_PRACTICE,
        euai:RECITAL_31 ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:PROHIBITION_OF_AI_PRACTICES .

euai:SOLELY_AUTOMATED_INDIVIDUAL_DECISION_MAKING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "SOLELY AUTOMATED INDIVIDUAL DECISION-MAKING"@en ;
    skos:definition "Rights of data subjects regarding profiling and automated decision-making as guaranteed under Union law, which are facilitated by the harmonised rules of the AI Act"@en .

euai:SPECIAL_CATEGORIES_OF_PERSONAL_DATA a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "SPECIAL CATEGORIES OF PERSONAL DATA"@en ;
    skos:definition "Special Categories of Personal Data refer to a sensitive classification of information that requires heightened protection under European Union law. These categories are formally defined in several key legislative frameworks, specifically Article 9(1) of the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), Article 10 of Directive (EU) 2016/680, and Article 10(1) of Regulation (EU) 2018/1725. Due to the sensitive nature of the information involved, the processing of this data is subject to strict limit"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:BIAS_DETECTION_AND_CORRECTION ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:TECHNICAL_LIMITATIONS .

euai:STANDARDISATION_DEVELOPMENT_PROCESS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "STANDARDISATION DEVELOPMENT PROCESS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Process in which Member States must facilitate the participation of SMEs and other relevant stakeholders under Article 62(1)(d)"@en .

euai:STANDARDISATION_DEVELOPMENT_PROCESSES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "STANDARDISATION DEVELOPMENT PROCESSES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Member States are required to facilitate the participation of SMEs and other relevant stakeholders in these processes"@en .

euai:STANDING_SUB_GROUPS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "STANDING SUB-GROUPS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Internal bodies established by the Board (including ADCO) to facilitate cooperation among market surveillance and notifying authorities per Article 65(6)"@en .

euai:STRATEGY_FOR_REGULATORY_COMPLIANCE rdfs:label "STRATEGY FOR REGULATORY COMPLIANCE"@en .

euai:STRUCTURED_DIALOGUE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "STRUCTURED DIALOGUE"@en ;
    skos:definition "**STRUCTURED DIALOGUE** refers to a voluntary and preliminary procedural step initiated by the AI Office. This dialogue takes place between the AI Office and a provider, serving as an initial engagement before any formal requests for information or formal access requests are issued. The primary purpose of this interaction is to gather comprehensive information regarding a provider's model testing methodologies and their strategies for risk mitigation, effectively laying the groundwork prior to p"@en .

euai:SUBCONTRACTOR a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "SUBCONTRACTOR"@en ;
    skos:definition "A third party hired by a notified body to perform specific tasks connected with the conformity assessment; must meet Article 31 requirements"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_31 .

euai:SUBSIDIARY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "SUBSIDIARY"@en ;
    skos:definition "A separate legal entity under the control of a notified body that may perform conformity assessment tasks; must meet Article 31 requirements"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_31 .

euai:SUPPORT_FOR_INNOVATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "SUPPORT FOR INNOVATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Measures intended to support innovation, focusing on SMEs and start-ups, as defined in Article 1(2)(g)"@en .

euai:SUSPENSION_OF_TESTING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "SUSPENSION OF TESTING"@en ;
    skos:definition "Power held by national competent authorities to temporarily or permanently suspend testing or participation in the sandbox if risks cannot be effectively mitigated."@en .

euai:SUSPENSION_OF_USE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "SUSPENSION OF USE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The requirement for a deployer to stop using a system if it presents a risk within the meaning of Article 79(1)"@en .

euai:SYSTEMIC_RISK_MITIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "SYSTEMIC RISK MITIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty to assess and mitigate systemic risks at the Union level stemming from the development, placing on the market, or use of the model per Article 55(1)(b)"@en .

euai:SYSTEM_REGISTRATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "SYSTEM REGISTRATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for law enforcement authorities to register the AI system in the relevant database as set out in the Regulation before use."@en .

euai:SeriousIncident a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "SeriousIncident"@en ;
    skos:definition "An event related to a GPAI model that must be reported."@en .

euai:TACIT_APPROVAL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "TACIT APPROVAL"@en ;
    skos:definition "The condition where a testing plan is deemed approved if the market surveillance authority does not respond within 30 days"@en .

euai:TECHNICAL_LIMITATIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TECHNICAL LIMITATIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Safeguard condition for processing special categories of personal data, including re-use restrictions and security measures"@en .

euai:TECHNICAL_REDUNDANCY_SOLUTIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TECHNICAL REDUNDANCY SOLUTIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Measures such as backup or fail-safe plans used to achieve the robustness of high-risk AI systems, as per Article 15(4)"@en .

euai:TECHNICAL_SOLUTIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TECHNICAL SOLUTIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Mechanisms like fail-safe plans designed to enable systems to safely interrupt operations or prevent/minimize harmful behavior"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ROBUSTNESS .

euai:TECHNICAL_SOLUTIONS_FOR_CYBERSECURITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TECHNICAL SOLUTIONS FOR CYBERSECURITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific measures to prevent, detect, respond to, and resolve attacks like data poisoning, model poisoning, and adversarial examples, as per Article 15(5)"@en .

euai:TECHNICAL_SPECIFICATIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Technical standards to be applied, including harmonised standards, ensuring compliance with Section 2 requirements (Article 17(2)(e))."@en .

euai:TEMPLATE_QUESTIONNAIRE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TEMPLATE QUESTIONNAIRE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A tool/template developed by the AI Office to help deployers comply with fundamental rights impact assessment obligations"@en .

euai:TERMINATE_MANDATE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "TERMINATE MANDATE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The requirement for an authorised representative to formally end their mandate if they have reason to believe the provider is acting contrary to the Regulation, including notifying the AI Office"@en .

euai:TESTING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TESTING"@en ;
    skos:definition "The process of ensuring high-risk AI systems perform consistently for their intended purpose and comply with legal requirements, performed prior to market placement, as per Article 9(6)-(8)"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_60,
        euai:ARTICLE_9 .

euai:TESTING_AND_EXPERIMENTATION_FACILITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "TESTING AND EXPERIMENTATION FACILITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Facilities supported by the Commission/Member States to provide technical and scientific support for compliance and testing"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:PROVIDER .

euai:TESTING_DATA_SETS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TESTING DATA SETS"@en ;
    skos:definition "The specific data scope to which obligations apply for high-risk AI systems that do not use model training techniques"@en .

euai:TESTING_EXPERIMENTATION_FACILITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "TESTING EXPERIMENTATION FACILITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Facilities providing infrastructure and support for testing AI systems, relevant for development and assessment of high-risk AI systems"@en .

euai:TESTING_OF_HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "TESTING OF HIGH-RISK AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "A process where a market surveillance authority organizes testing of an AI system via technical means if documentation is insufficient to determine fundamental rights infringement"@en .

euai:TEXT_AND_DATA_MINING rdfs:label "TEXT AND DATA MINING"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DIRECTIVE__EU__2019_790 .

euai:TFEU a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "TFEU"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU) serves as a primary pillar of the European Union’s legal architecture. As a foundational document, it establishes the legal framework governing various critical functions of the EU, including the judicial review of decisions made by the European Commission. Specifically, the TFEU empowers the Court of Justice of the European Union to oversee and adjudicate upon these Commission decisions, ensuring legal compliance and institutional accou"@en .

euai:THIRD_COUNTRY_PUBLIC_AUTHORITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "THIRD COUNTRY PUBLIC AUTHORITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Third country public authorities, as well as international organizations operating in third countries, may be subject to exemptions under Article 2(4). These entities are potentially exempted from certain regulatory requirements, provided that the specific conditions related to law enforcement and judicial cooperation are fully satisfied as outlined in the referenced article."@en ;
    euai:isExemptFromHighRisk euai:ARTICLE_2 .

euai:THIRD_PARTIES rdfs:label "THIRD PARTIES"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CERTIFIED_COMPLIANCE_SERVICES .

euai:THIRD_PARTY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "THIRD PARTY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Entity that supplies tools, services, components, or processes integrated into a high-risk AI system"@en .

euai:THIRD_PARTY_SUPPLIER a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "THIRD PARTY SUPPLIER"@en ;
    skos:definition "Entity that supplies AI systems, tools, services, components, or processes used or integrated into a high-risk AI system"@en .

euai:TRADE_SECRETS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TRADE SECRETS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Confidential business information that must be protected while AI value chain parties cooperate with providers"@en .

euai:TRAINING_CONTENT_SUMMARY_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "TRAINING CONTENT SUMMARY OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty to draw up and make publicly available a detailed summary about content used for training per Article 53(1)(d)."@en .

euai:TRAINING_DATA_SUMMARY_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "TRAINING DATA SUMMARY OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty to draw up and make publicly available a sufficiently detailed summary of the content used for training the general-purpose AI model"@en .

euai:TRAINING__VALIDATION_AND_TESTING_DATA_SETS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TRAINING, VALIDATION AND TESTING DATA SETS"@en ;
    skos:definition "The specific data inputs used for developing AI models, which must meet quality criteria regarding representativeness, accuracy, and completeness per Article 10"@en ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:DATA_GOVERNANCE_AND_MANAGEMENT_PRACTICES .

euai:TRANSITIONAL_PERIOD a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "TRANSITIONAL PERIOD"@en ;
    skos:definition "The period during which voluntary compliance with obligations is encouraged, specifically for high-risk AI system providers (Recital 178)"@en .

euai:TRANSITION_TO_HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "TRANSITION TO HIGH-RISK AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty for the former provider to cooperate and provide technical access and information when an AI system changes classification to high-risk, provided they have not expressly excluded this possibility"@en .

euai:TRANSLATION_COSTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "TRANSLATION COSTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "A significant cost factor for operators; Member States should facilitate the use of widely understood languages for documentation and communication to mitigate this"@en .

euai:TRANSPARENCY_AND_PROVISION_OF_INFORMATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "TRANSPARENCY AND PROVISION OF INFORMATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty of the provider to ensure the AI system's operation is transparent and accompanied by clear instructions for the deployer per Article 13"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_13 .

euai:TRANSPARENCY_DOCUMENTATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TRANSPARENCY DOCUMENTATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """Transparency Documentation refers to the essential information that general-purpose AI model providers are legally obligated to supply to downstream providers who integrate these models into their own AI systems. As outlined in Article 53(1)(b) of the applicable regulations and detailed in Annex XII, this documentation serves as a critical bridge of information between the original developers and those applying the technology in various use cases.

This documentation is comprehensive in scope, e"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ANNEX_XII .

euai:TRANSPARENCY_INFORMATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TRANSPARENCY INFORMATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Information that providers of general-purpose AI models must provide, which may be modified by delegated acts, as per Recital 173"@en .

euai:TRANSPARENCY_MEASURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "TRANSPARENCY MEASURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for general-purpose AI model providers to draw up, keep up to date, and provide documentation and information regarding the model for downstream users, as described in Recital 101"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_50 .

euai:TRANSPARENCY_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TRANSPARENCY REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for AI systems in migration, asylum, and border control to be transparent to guarantee fundamental rights."@en .

euai:TRANSPARENCY_RULES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TRANSPARENCY RULES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Harmonised obligations regarding the transparency of certain AI systems as defined in Article 1(2)(d)"@en .

euai:TRAVEL_DOCUMENT_VERIFICATION_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "TRAVEL DOCUMENT VERIFICATION EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The \"TRAVEL DOCUMENT VERIFICATION EXCLUSION\" refers to a specific regulatory or operational provision that exempts certain entities or situations from standard procedures involving the scrutiny of travel documents. This exclusion is specifically applicable to scenarios involving high-risk classifications within the broader domains of migration, asylum, and border control. In essence, it serves as a policy mechanism that modifies or suspends the requirement to verify travel documents for individu"@en .

euai:UNACCEPTABLE_AI_PRACTICES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:RiskCategory ;
    rdfs:label "UNACCEPTABLE AI PRACTICES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Unacceptable AI practices refer to specific artificial intelligence systems or applications that are strictly prohibited under the Regulation. These practices are classified as impermissible due to the nature and intensity of the significant risks they pose to individuals, fundamental rights, and society at large. Because of these severe risks, such systems are deemed incompatible with the requirements set forth in the Regulation and are therefore banned from deployment or use."@en .

euai:UNION_COPYRIGHT_LAW rdfs:label "UNION COPYRIGHT LAW"@en .

euai:UNION_DATA_PROTECTION_LAW a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "UNION DATA PROTECTION LAW"@en ;
    skos:definition "Refers to the existing legal framework including Regulation (EU) 2016/679 (GDPR), Regulation (EU) 2018/1725, and Directive (EU) 2016/680, which apply to personal data processing by AI systems."@en .

euai:UNION_ETHICAL_GUIDELINES_FOR_TRUSTWORTHY_AI rdfs:label "UNION ETHICAL GUIDELINES FOR TRUSTWORTHY AI"@en .

euai:UNION_ETHICS_GUIDELINES_FOR_TRUSTWORTHY_AI a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "UNION ETHICS GUIDELINES FOR TRUSTWORTHY AI"@en ;
    skos:definition "A framework containing elements for trustworthy AI, including sustainability and inclusion, which providers are encouraged to apply on a voluntary basis"@en .

euai:UNION_HARMONISATION_LEGISLATION_PRODUCTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "UNION HARMONISATION LEGISLATION PRODUCTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific product categories listed in Recital 50, including machinery, toys, lifts, and medical devices, which may contain high-risk AI safety components"@en .

euai:UNION_INSTITUTIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "UNION INSTITUTIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "**UNION INSTITUTIONS** are designated as EU bodies, offices, or agencies that operate as deployers of technology or systems. In this capacity, they are held to the same registration obligations as public authorities. Furthermore, these institutions are subject to regulatory oversight by the European Data Protection Supervisor, which possesses the authority to issue potential fines to them to ensure strict compliance with the relevant Regulations."@en ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:REGISTRATION_OBLIGATION .

euai:UNION_INSTITUTIONS__AGENCIES_AND_BODIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "UNION INSTITUTIONS, AGENCIES AND BODIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Entities falling within the scope of the Regulation for which the EDPS serves as market surveillance authority."@en .

euai:UNION_INSTITUTIONS__BODIES__OFFICES_AND_AGENCIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "UNION INSTITUTIONS, BODIES, OFFICES AND AGENCIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Union institutions, bodies, offices, and agencies are entities of the European Union that fall under the scope of the AI Act. These institutions are specifically subject to the Regulation whenever they act in the capacity of a provider or deployer of an AI system, a clarification reinforced by Recital 23. Furthermore, these entities are subject to oversight by the European Data Protection Supervisor, which may impose fines for non-compliance. In addition to these regulatory obligations, the Euro"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ADMINISTRATIVE_FINE,
        euai:DEPLOYER,
        euai:PROVIDER,
        euai:TECHNICAL_AND_ORGANISATIONAL_MEASURES .

euai:UNION_MARKET a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "UNION MARKET"@en ;
    skos:definition "The jurisdiction/market where providers place AI models and must comply with the Regulation, ensuring a level playing field"@en .

euai:URGENCY_EXCEPTION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "URGENCY EXCEPTION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Allows for the use of biometric systems without prior authorisation in duly justified cases where obtaining it beforehand is objectively impossible. Requires post-hoc authorisation request within 24 hours."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:PRIOR_AUTHORISATION .

euai:USER_REACH_METRIC a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "USER REACH METRIC"@en ;
    skos:definition "The **USER REACH METRIC** serves as a quantitative measurement based on the total count of registered end-users. This metric is primarily utilized to evaluate and assess the overall scale, significance, and real-world impact of a general-purpose AI model. By tracking the number of users who have registered, organizations can determine the extent of a model's reach and its influence within its target audience."@en .

euai:VALIDATION_AND_TESTING_PROCEDURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "VALIDATION AND TESTING PROCEDURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Processes to measure accuracy, robustness, and compliance, including test logs and reports"@en .

euai:VERY_LARGE_ONLINE_PLATFORM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "VERY LARGE ONLINE PLATFORM"@en ;
    skos:definition "Service provider regulated under Regulation (EU) 2022/2065, subject to specific risk-management frameworks when embedding AI systems or models"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:SYSTEMIC_RISK ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:RISK_MANAGEMENT_FRAMEWORK .

euai:VERY_LARGE_ONLINE_PLATFORMS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "VERY LARGE ONLINE PLATFORMS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Providers of platforms that must identify and mitigate systemic risks arising from artificially generated content, as per Regulation (EU) 2022/2065"@en ;
    euai:regulatedBy euai:REGULATION__EU__2022_2065 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:SYSTEMIC_RISK .

euai:VISA_INFORMATION_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "VISA INFORMATION SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Visa Information System is a large-scale information technology system utilized for the management of visa applications and visa processing. As a critical component of the relevant Union legislative framework, it is explicitly listed in Annex X. Currently, the Visa Information System is subject to ongoing efforts to reform its legal framework, which are also detailed within the regulations listed in Annex X."@en ;
    euai:regulatedBy euai:REGULATION__EU__2021_1133,
        euai:REGULATION__EU__2021_1134 .

euai:VOLUNTARY_COMPLIANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "VOLUNTARY COMPLIANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Providers of high-risk AI systems are encouraged to start complying with obligations voluntarily during the transitional period (Recital 178)."@en .

euai:VOLUNTARY_MODEL_CONTRACTUAL_TERMS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "VOLUNTARY MODEL CONTRACTUAL TERMS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Non-mandatory contractual clauses developed by the Commission to facilitate cooperation between providers and third-party suppliers"@en .

euai:VOLUNTARY_MODEL_TERMS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:CodeOfPractice ;
    rdfs:label "VOLUNTARY MODEL TERMS"@en ;
    skos:definition "The **VOLUNTARY MODEL TERMS** are a set of contractual templates specifically developed and provided by the AI Office. These templates serve as a resource designed to assist providers and third-party suppliers in formalizing their working relationships and establishing clear, mutually beneficial agreements. By offering these standardized documents, the AI Office facilitates the process of structuring legal collaborations between these entities."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:PROVIDER .

euai:WITHDRAWAL_OF_AN_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "WITHDRAWAL OF AN AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "Measure aiming to prevent an AI system in the supply chain from being made available on the market"@en .

euai:WORKERS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "WORKERS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Employees whose rights, working conditions, and health and safety at work are protected by Union and national labour law, independent of this Regulation"@en .

euai:WORKERS__REPRESENTATIVES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "WORKERS' REPRESENTATIVES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Entities representing workers who must be informed by employers before the deployment of a high-risk AI system in the workplace per Article 26/requirements."@en .

euai:WORKER_INFORMATION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "WORKER INFORMATION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Employers deploying high-risk AI systems at the workplace must inform workers' representatives and affected workers about the use of the system before putting it into service."@en .

euai:WORKPLACE_CATEGORY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AnnexIIICategory ;
    rdfs:label "WORKPLACE CATEGORY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Use case domain involving the management and monitoring of employees (Recital 44)"@en .

euai:WRITTEN_PROOF a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "WRITTEN PROOF"@en ;
    skos:definition "Documentation provided by the competent authority upon request, verifying the successful activities carried out by a provider or prospective provider in the sandbox"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT .

euai:ADMINISTRATIVE_FINES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "ADMINISTRATIVE FINES"@en ;
    skos:definition """Administrative fines serve as a critical enforcement measure designed to ensure compliance with the AI Act. These financial penalties are imposed upon various entities—including Member States, Union institutions, and providers of general-purpose AI (GPAI) models—in response to infringements of the Regulation.

The framework for these administrative fines establishes specific monetary limits based on the nature of the entity and the type of violation. For Union institutions, penalties are capped """@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_101,
        euai:ARTICLE_5,
        euai:ARTICLE_99_1_ ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL,
        euai:SME,
        euai:UNION_INSTITUTION__BODY__OFFICE_OR_AGENCY .

euai:ADVERSARIAL_TESTING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "ADVERSARIAL TESTING"@en ;
    skos:definition """Adversarial testing is a specialized evaluation methodology utilized to assess the security and robustness of AI models. As defined by its inclusion in model evaluation frameworks, this process is essential for identifying and mitigating systemic risks, a requirement specifically mandated under Article 55(1)(a). 

This evaluation method functions by employing either internal testing or independent external assessments to rigorously probe the model for potential weaknesses. By simulating various """@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:MODEL_EVALUATION .

euai:AGREEMENT_ON_ROLES_AND_RESPONSIBILITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "AGREEMENT ON ROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Written agreement between the provider/prospective provider and the deployer/prospective deployer specifying their roles and responsibilities, per Article 60(h)"@en .

euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_ASYLUM_AND_VISA_PROCESSING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "AI SYSTEM FOR ASYLUM AND VISA PROCESSING"@en ;
    skos:definition "System used to assist in examining applications for asylum, visa, or residence permits and assessing reliability of evidence, identified in Annex III(7)(c)"@en .

euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_EVIDENCE_EVALUATION_IN_LAW_ENFORCEMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "AI SYSTEM FOR EVIDENCE EVALUATION IN LAW ENFORCEMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "System used to evaluate the reliability of evidence in the investigation or prosecution of criminal offences, identified in Annex III(6)(c)"@en .

euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_JUDICIAL_ASSISTANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "AI SYSTEM FOR JUDICIAL ASSISTANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "System used by or for a judicial authority to research and interpret facts and law, or for alternative dispute resolution, identified in Annex III(8)(a)"@en .

euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_LAW_ENFORCEMENT_PROFILING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "AI SYSTEM FOR LAW ENFORCEMENT PROFILING"@en ;
    skos:definition "System used for profiling natural persons during detection, investigation, or prosecution of criminal offences, identified in Annex III(6)(e)"@en .

euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_MIGRATION_POLYGRAPHS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "AI SYSTEM FOR MIGRATION POLYGRAPHS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Polygraph or similar tool used for migration, asylum, and border control management, identified in Annex III(7)(a)"@en .

euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_MIGRATION_RISK_ASSESSMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "AI SYSTEM FOR MIGRATION RISK ASSESSMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "System used to assess security, irregular migration, or health risks posed by persons entering a Member State, identified in Annex III(7)(b)"@en .

euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_OFFENDING_RISK_ASSESSMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "AI SYSTEM FOR OFFENDING RISK ASSESSMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "System used by law enforcement to assess the risk of a natural person offending or re-offending, or to assess personality/criminal behavior, identified in Annex III(6)(d)"@en .

euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_POLYGRAPHS_IN_LAW_ENFORCEMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "AI SYSTEM FOR POLYGRAPHS IN LAW ENFORCEMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Polygraph or similar tool used by or on behalf of law enforcement to assess reliability of natural persons, identified in Annex III(6)(b)"@en .

euai:ANCILLARY_FEATURE_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "ANCILLARY FEATURE EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Condition under which a biometric categorisation system is excluded from regulation if the feature is purely ancillary, intrinsically linked to a principal commercial service, and not a means of circumventing the Regulation."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ONLINE_MARKETPLACE,
        euai:SOCIAL_NETWORK_SERVICE .

euai:ANNEXES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ANNEXES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific annexes to this Regulation that set out the minimal set of elements to be included in the technical documentation, as described in Recital 101"@en .

euai:ANNEX_III_USE_CASE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AnnexIIICategory ;
    rdfs:label "ANNEX III USE CASE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Domains or contexts for AI systems listed in Annex III that generally carry high risk unless specific exclusion conditions apply."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:HIGH_RISK .

euai:ANNEX_III_USE_CASE_RULE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ClassificationRule ;
    rdfs:label "ANNEX III USE CASE RULE"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **ANNEX III USE CASE RULE** functions as a regulatory classification mechanism within the context of AI governance. This rule serves as the criterion for identifying and categorizing Artificial Intelligence systems as "high-risk" by default, provided they fall within the specific domains enumerated in Annex III of the relevant regulatory framework.

These high-stakes domains encompass critical areas of societal importance, including but not limited to education, employment, and the provision"""@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:EDUCATION_AND_TRAINING_AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:EMPLOYMENT_AND_WORKERS_MANAGEMENT_AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:ESSENTIAL_PUBLIC_SERVICES_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:ANNEX_IX a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ANNEX IX"@en ;
    skos:definition "Annex IX serves as a regulatory component outlining the specific information required for the registration of high-risk AI systems within the EU database. It functions as a definitive guide for the necessary documentation and data points that must be provided when registering these systems. Furthermore, Annex IX extends its scope beyond standard registration, as it also specifies the information requirements pertaining to the real-world testing of high-risk AI systems. Consequently, it acts as a"@en .

euai:ANNEX_I_PRODUCT_SAFETY_COMPONENT_RULE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ClassificationRule ;
    rdfs:label "ANNEX I PRODUCT SAFETY COMPONENT RULE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Rule where an AI system is a safety component of, or is itself, a product covered by Union harmonisation legislation listed in Annex I and requires third-party conformity assessment"@en .

euai:ANNEX_V a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ANNEX V"@en ;
    skos:definition "ANNEX V serves as a formal section of regulatory documentation that outlines the specific content requirements for the EU declaration of conformity. This annex functions as a definitive guide for manufacturers and relevant parties, detailing exactly what information must be included in the declaration to ensure compliance with European Union standards. By specifying these content requirements, ANNEX V provides the necessary framework for drafting a complete and accurate EU declaration of conform"@en .

euai:ANNUAL_REPORTING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "ANNUAL REPORTING"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for national authorities to submit reports to the Commission regarding the use of biometric systems."@en .

euai:APPLICATION_FOR_NOTIFICATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "APPLICATION FOR NOTIFICATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The formal submission by a conformity assessment body to a notifying authority to become a notified body, including proof of competence, accreditation, and descriptions of activities, as per Article 29"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_29 .

euai:ARTICLE_10 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 10"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 10 pertains to the establishment of regulations concerning data and data governance specifically for high-risk artificial intelligence (AI) systems. As a governing provision, this article outlines the necessary standards and requirements that must be adhered to regarding the management, quality, and oversight of data used within the development and operation of high-risk AI technologies."@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:ARTICLE_10_OF_DIRECTIVE__EU__2016_680 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 10 OF DIRECTIVE (EU) 2016/680"@en ;
    skos:definition """Article 10 of Directive (EU) 2016/680 serves as a critical regulatory provision governing the processing of biometric data specifically for law enforcement purposes. This article is closely associated with Recital 94, which provides necessary context for its application.

Functioning as a fundamental component of the broader Directive (EU) 2016/680, Article 10 establishes the legal framework and limitations under which law enforcement authorities may process biometric data. While it sets the fou"""@en .

euai:ARTICLE_10_OF_REGULATION__EU__NO_1025_2012 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 10 OF REGULATION (EU) NO 1025/2012"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific provision detailing the Commission's power to issue standardisation requests."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_110 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 110"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 110 of the AI Act, which provides the amendment to Directive (EU) 2020/1828 to include the AI Act in its annex."@en ;
    euai:modifies euai:DIRECTIVE_2020_1828 .

euai:ARTICLE_112 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 112"@en ;
    skos:definition "**Article 112** serves as a critical component of the AI Act, specifically functioning as a provision that mandates the evaluation and review of the legislation itself. In this capacity, Article 112 establishes a framework for ongoing oversight, wherein the AI Board is tasked with providing essential assistance. Furthermore, Article 112 includes provisions related to the necessary revision of Article 5, ensuring that the legal requirements concerning prohibited AI practices remain dynamic and re"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_12 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 12"@en ;
    skos:definition "**ARTICLE 12** functions as the critical legal provision governing the mandatory record-keeping and logging obligations for high-risk AI systems. As a specific regulatory requirement, Article 12 mandates that providers of such systems implement robust mechanisms for the automatic recording of events, commonly referred to as logs, throughout the lifecycle of the AI system. By defining these essential record-keeping duties, Article 12 ensures transparency, accountability, and traceability, thereby"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_13 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 13"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ARTICLE 13**

Article 13 serves as a pivotal legal provision focused on the requirements for transparency and the provision of information. It specifically mandates that transparency obligations and information-sharing protocols be extended to both users and deployers. Furthermore, the significance of Article 13 is underscored by its formal linkage to other parts of the regulatory framework, as it is explicitly referenced in Article 9(5)(c)."""@en .

euai:ARTICLE_15 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 15"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 15 establishes mandatory requirements concerning the accuracy, robustness, and cybersecurity of high-risk AI systems. This article serves as a key reference for ensuring that such systems meet necessary standards in these three critical areas to maintain safety, reliability, and security throughout their operational lifecycle."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_16_TFEU a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 16 TFEU"@en ;
    skos:definition """Article 16 of the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU) serves as a fundamental legal basis within the European Union's regulatory framework, particularly concerning the governance of Artificial Intelligence. It provides the essential treaty-based authorization for the rules established under the AI Act, which govern the processing of personal data and dictate the limitations on specific technologies. 

Specifically, Article 16 TFEU provides the necessary authority to enact legi"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_5 .

euai:ARTICLE_18 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 18"@en ;
    skos:definition "ARTICLE 18 establishes the regulatory framework regarding the documentation obligations for providers of high-risk AI systems. Specifically, this article mandates that these providers must maintain comprehensive technical documentation, ensuring that all necessary records related to the development, function, and compliance of their high-risk AI systems are properly preserved and accessible."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_20 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 20"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 20 serves as a regulatory provision focused on the management of high-risk AI systems, specifically addressing the requirements for corrective actions and the duty to provide information. It mandates that when an AI system is identified as non-conforming or posing risks, specific measures must be taken to rectify the situation. Furthermore, Article 20 outlines the obligations of relevant parties to ensure transparency and accountability by providing necessary information regarding these "@en .

euai:ARTICLE_26_10_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 26(10)"@en ;
    skos:definition "**Article 26(10)** is a specific provision within the AI Act that governs the processing of personal data by Member States. This article is particularly significant because it concerns processing activities that occur within the specific legislative contexts of Chapter 4 or 5 of Title V of the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU). Furthermore, Article 26(10) is notable for the unique legal status afforded to Ireland, which holds a specific opt-out or positioning status regardin"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_29 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 29"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 29 outlines the comprehensive regulatory framework regarding the status of conformity assessment bodies. Specifically, it details the requirements and the formal application process that these bodies must undergo to achieve official notification. Furthermore, Article 29 addresses the procedural obligations necessary for an already notified body to request an extension to the scope of its existing notification. In essence, this article serves as the governing provision for both the initia"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_33_OF_REGULATION__EU__2019_1020 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 33 OF REGULATION (EU) 2019/1020"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article requiring the Commission to support the activities of the standing subgroup for market surveillance through evaluations or studies"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_35_OF_REGULATION__EU__2016_679 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 35 OF REGULATION (EU) 2016/679"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 35 of Regulation (EU) 2016/679, commonly known as the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), serves as the foundational provision governing Data Protection Impact Assessments (DPIAs). This article outlines the requirements and procedures for controllers to assess the impact of envisaged processing operations on the protection of personal data. By mandating DPIAs, the regulation ensures that organizations proactively identify and mitigate risks associated with data processing activiti"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_38 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 38"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ARTICLE 38**

Article 38 is a provision that specifically addresses the coordination and cooperation of notified bodies. It establishes the requirement for these entities to engage in various coordination activities, mandating that notified bodies actively participate in these collaborative efforts to ensure consistency and efficiency in their regulatory functions."""@en .

euai:ARTICLE_4 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 4"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article addressing AI literacy requirements"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_40 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 40"@en ;
    skos:definition "**Article 40** serves as a regulatory provision that addresses the critical role of harmonised standards and standardisation deliverables within a legal or technical framework. Its primary function is to define and regulate the application of these standards, establishing them as an essential mechanism for ensuring compliance. Specifically, Article 40 designates harmonised standards as the foundational basis for the presumption of conformity, meaning that products or processes adhering to these "@en .

euai:ARTICLE_44 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 44"@en ;
    skos:definition "Governs the issuance, validity, and management of certificates for AI systems by notified bodies"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_49_2_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 49(2)"@en ;
    skos:definition """Article 49(2) serves as a regulatory provision within the context of AI governance, specifically concerning the transparency and oversight obligations of AI system providers. This article encompasses three distinct but related requirements aimed at ensuring proper documentation and database registration for various AI systems.

First, Article 49(2) clarifies the registration obligations for providers of AI systems that, despite being listed in Annex III, have been assessed and deemed not to be h"""@en .

euai:ARTICLE_49_4_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 49(4)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article governing registration in the EU database for high-risk AI systems in law enforcement/migration/asylum/border control"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_49_5_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 49(5)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 49(5) serves as a regulatory provision within the framework governing high-risk AI systems. It specifically dictates the requirements for registration within the designated EU database for those high-risk AI systems that are related to point 2 of Annex III. Furthermore, Article 49(5) mandates that the Commission must provide appropriate guidelines to facilitate this process, ensuring these guidelines are developed only after formally consulting the European Artificial Intelligence Board."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_96 .

euai:ARTICLE_4_2__TEU a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 4(2) TEU"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 4(2) of the Treaty on European Union (TEU) serves as a fundamental provision delineating the division of competence between the European Union and its Member States. This article establishes the principle that the responsibility for safeguarding national security rests solely with the individual Member States. Consequently, it functions as a critical legal justification for excluding national security, as well as military and defense-related activities, from the scope of various European"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_59 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 59"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Article 59** refers to a specific legal provision that functions as an essential component within the framework of artificial intelligence regulation. Primarily, this article governs the processing of personal data necessary for the development of certain AI systems that are designed to operate in the public interest, specifically within the environment of an AI regulatory sandbox. 

Furthermore, Article 59 plays a significant role in the administration of these sandboxes by establishing that """@en .

euai:ARTICLE_61 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 61"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 61 establishes the regulatory framework governing the testing of AI systems in real-world conditions. This article outlines the specific requirements and conditions that must be met to ensure that such testing is conducted safely, ethically, and in accordance with legal standards. A central component of Article 61 is the definition of informed consent, which mandates that participants must be fully informed and provide their consent before their involvement in real-world AI testing can p"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_68_2_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 68(2)"@en ;
    skos:definition "**Article 68(2)** serves as a regulatory provision that establishes the framework for both the composition and the operational requirements of scientific support personnel. This article defines the specific tasks and the necessary criteria that members of the scientific panel must fulfill to execute their responsibilities effectively. Furthermore, Article 68(2) outlines the requisite standards and criteria that independent experts must meet in order to be eligible to assist in evaluations, ensur"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_6_2_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 6(2)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 6(2) serves as a critical provision within the regulatory framework for artificial intelligence, specifically regarding the categorization of high-risk AI systems. This article defines the scope and criteria used to identify these systems, directly referencing the list provided in Annex III of the regulation. By establishing these parameters, Article 6(2) plays a foundational role in determining which AI applications are subject to specific regulatory obligations, including the requireme"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_6_3_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 6(3)"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ARTICLE 6(3)** is a regulatory provision that outlines the framework for classifying AI systems, specifically focusing on the threshold between systems deemed "high-risk" and those that are not. 

This article plays a crucial role in the classification process by establishing the conditions under which an AI system is designated as high-risk, often by referencing criteria found in Annex III. Conversely, it serves as the definitive reference point for determining whether an AI system falls outs"""@en ;
    euai:triggers euai:REGISTRATION .

euai:ARTICLE_71_4_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 71(4)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article governing the registration of real-world testing for certain high-risk AI systems"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_74_8_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 74(8)"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article specifying the market surveillance authorities designated to access technical documentation"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_91 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 91"@en ;
    skos:definition "**ARTICLE 91** acts as the governing provision regarding the authority of the Commission to request documentation and information from providers of general-purpose AI (GPAI) models. This article establishes the legal framework that empowers the Commission to obtain necessary materials from these providers. Furthermore, it explicitly links compliance with these requests to regulatory accountability, as failure to provide the requested documents or information may result in the imposition of fines"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_93_MITIGATION_MEASURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 93 MITIGATION MEASURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Measures requested by the Commission to ensure compliance, address systemic risks, or restrict market access"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_53,
        euai:ARTICLE_54,
        euai:ARTICLE_92,
        euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL_WITH_SYSTEMIC_RISK .

euai:ARTICLE_94 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 94"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 94 serves as a critical component within the legal framework governing AI regulation. It establishes essential procedural guarantees that are specifically referenced in Article 88, ensuring that these protections are upheld during the execution of enforcement actions. Furthermore, Article 94 is identified as a key element concerning the enforcement powers about which the AI Office is obligated to inform the Board, thereby playing a foundational role in both the procedural safeguards of e"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_95_CODES_OF_CONDUCT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:CodeOfPractice ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 95 CODES OF CONDUCT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Voluntary instruments encouraged by the AI Office and Member States for non-high-risk AI systems to adopt requirements from Chapter III, Section 2"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CHAPTER_III_SECTION_2_REQUIREMENTS .

euai:ARTICLE_9_1__OF_REGULATION__EU__2016_679 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 9(1) OF REGULATION (EU) 2016/679"@en ;
    skos:definition "GDPR provision prohibiting the processing of biometric data unless specific exceptions apply"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_9_OF_REGULATION__EU__2019_1020 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 9 OF REGULATION (EU) 2019/1020"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 9 of Regulation (EU) 2019/1020 serves as a critical legal reference within the European Union's regulatory framework. It establishes the legal basis and governs the procedures for conducting joint activities and investigations. The primary purpose of this article is to promote product compliance and to effectively address serious risks that may arise regarding product safety and conformity. By facilitating these cooperative efforts, Article 9 ensures that market surveillance authorities "@en .

euai:AUTHORISATION_FOR_EXCEPTIONAL_USE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "AUTHORISATION FOR EXCEPTIONAL USE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The process by which law enforcement or civil protection authorities may seek permission to use a high-risk AI system in emergencies; if refused, use must cease and results be discarded."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:AUTHORISATION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "AUTHORISATION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **AUTHORISATION OBLIGATION** refers to a regulatory mandate placed on law enforcement agencies regarding the use of remote biometric identification. Under this obligation, law enforcement is generally required to secure authorization—either *ex ante* (prior to the action) or *post-hoc* (within 48 hours after the action)—from a relevant judicial or administrative authority before proceeding with remote biometric identification.

However, there is a specific exception to this mandate. The requ"""@en ;
    euai:hasException euai:EXEMPTION_FROM_AUTHORISATION .

euai:AUTHORISATION_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "AUTHORISATION REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for competent authorities to obtain authorization before deploying certain biometric systems, which does not apply to non-law enforcement uses"@en .

euai:AUTOMATIC_RECORDING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "AUTOMATIC RECORDING"@en ;
    skos:definition "A technical capability that high-risk AI systems must possess to allow for traceability and post-market monitoring of their operations."@en .

euai:AWARENESS_RAISING_AND_TRAINING_ACTIVITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "AWARENESS RAISING AND TRAINING ACTIVITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for Member States to organize specific education for SMEs, deployers, and local public authorities on the AI Act under Article 62(1)(b)"@en .

euai:CERTIFICATE_EXTENSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CERTIFICATE EXTENSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The process of extending a certificate validity for up to five years for Annex I systems or four years for Annex III systems based on re-assessment."@en .

euai:CERTIFICATE_OF_CONFORMITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CERTIFICATE OF CONFORMITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "A document issued by a notified body attesting to a system's conformity; its validity status is subject to specific conditions when the issuing body's designation is changed."@en ;
    euai:belongsToCategory euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:CERTIFICATE_SUSPENSION_OR_WITHDRAWAL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CERTIFICATE SUSPENSION OR WITHDRAWAL"@en ;
    skos:definition "A duty of a notified body to suspend or withdraw a certificate if requirements are not met, unless corrective action is taken."@en .

euai:CHAPTER_V a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "CHAPTER V"@en ;
    skos:definition """CHAPTER V of the AI Act establishes critical obligations for providers of general-purpose AI models. This section specifically addresses the requirements related to transparency and systemic risk, as outlined in its second and third sections. 

Enforcement of these provisions falls under the jurisdiction of the European Commission, as stipulated by Article 88. According to Article 113 of the regulation, CHAPTER V is set to become applicable on 2 August 2025."""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_113 .

euai:COMMUNICATION_CAMPAIGNS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "COMMUNICATION CAMPAIGNS"@en ;
    skos:definition "An obligation for the Commission to raise awareness about the obligations arising from the Regulation among providers and deployers"@en .

euai:CONSULTATION_OF_EXPERTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "CONSULTATION OF EXPERTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Before adopting a delegated act, the Commission must consult experts designated by each Member State in accordance with the principles of the Interinstitutional Agreement of 13 April 2016 per Article 97(4)"@en .

euai:CONTENT_GENERATION_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "CONTENT GENERATION AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "AI systems (including general-purpose AI models) capable of generating synthetic content. Providers are required to embed technical marking and detection solutions to verify AI-generated content."@en ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:MARKING_AND_DETECTION_OBLIGATION .

euai:COOPERATION_WITH_COMPETENT_AUTHORITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "COOPERATION WITH COMPETENT AUTHORITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Providers must provide documentation and logs upon a reasoned request by a competent authority as per Article 21"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_21 .

euai:COPYRIGHT_COMPLIANCE_POLICY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "COPYRIGHT COMPLIANCE POLICY"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **COPYRIGHT COMPLIANCE POLICY** represents a mandatory obligation for providers of General-Purpose AI (GPAI) models. This policy requires providers to establish and implement internal procedures ensuring full adherence to Union copyright law and related rights throughout the entire training process of their AI models. 

Central to this policy is the necessity to respect and comply with specific legal frameworks regarding the reservation of rights. Specifically, providers must align their pra"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_4_3__OF_DIRECTIVE__EU__2019_790,
        euai:DIRECTIVE__EU__2019_790 .

euai:COUNCIL_DIRECTIVE_85_374_EEC a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "COUNCIL DIRECTIVE 85/374/EEC"@en ;
    skos:definition "**COUNCIL DIRECTIVE 85/374/EEC** serves as a foundational piece of legislation concerning liability for defective products. It establishes a comprehensive civil liability framework that provides individuals with rights to compensation for damages caused by such products. In the modern context, this directive is increasingly significant as it applies to damages potentially caused by AI systems, ensuring that there is an established legal structure to address accountability and consumer protection"@en .

euai:CRIMINAL_OFFENCES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "CRIMINAL OFFENCES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific legal threshold (e.g., offenses referred to in Annex II punishable by custodial sentence of at least four years) required for the use of biometric identification"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_II .

euai:CYBERSECURITY_PURPOSE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "CYBERSECURITY PURPOSE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The intent of using systems solely for enabling cybersecurity and personal data protection measures; acts as an exclusion condition for high-risk classification of biometric systems and critical infrastructure safety components (Recital 54, 55)"@en .

euai:DATA_CONTROLLER a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "DATA CONTROLLER"@en ;
    skos:definition """A Data Controller is a specific role defined under the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) (Regulation (EU) 2016/679), as well as the Law Enforcement Directive (LED). An entity assumes the status of a Data Controller when it determines the purposes and means of the processing of personal data. 

This role carries significant legal responsibilities and obligations regarding how data is handled, stored, and protected. Furthermore, the concept of a Data Controller is applicable to both provid"""@en .

euai:DATA_PROTECTION_IMPACT_ASSESSMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DATA PROTECTION IMPACT ASSESSMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Deployers use information provided under Article 13 to comply with their obligation to carry out a DPIA under GDPR or Directive (EU) 2016/680."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_26_8_ .

euai:DELEGATED_ACTS_AMENDING_ANNEX_III a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:DelegatedAct ;
    rdfs:label "DELEGATED ACTS AMENDING ANNEX III"@en ;
    skos:definition "DELEGATED ACTS AMENDING ANNEX III consist of regulatory measures adopted by the European Commission. These acts serve the purpose of updating Annex III by adding, modifying, or refining the list of use-cases classified as high-risk AI systems. These updates are strictly based on the risk criteria established under Article 7, with a specific focus on the requirements and criteria defined in Article 7(2)."@en ;
    euai:isBasedOn euai:ARTICLE_7_1_ ;
    euai:modifies euai:ANNEX_III ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:RISK_ASSESSMENT_CRITERIA .

euai:DELEGATED_ACTS_MODIFYING_CONDITIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:DelegatedAct ;
    rdfs:label "DELEGATED ACTS MODIFYING CONDITIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition """Delegated acts modifying conditions refer to regulatory measures adopted by the European Commission designed to amend specific criteria related to the high-risk classification of AI systems. These acts provide the Commission with the authority to update and refine the regulatory framework established under Article 49 of the relevant AI legislation.

Specifically, these delegated acts serve two primary functions: first, they allow the Commission to amend the conditions outlined in Article 49(3) r"""@en ;
    euai:modifies euai:EXCLUSION_CONDITIONS ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_49 .

euai:DEMONSTRATION_OF_CONFORMITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DEMONSTRATION OF CONFORMITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Upon reasoned request of a national competent authority, providers must demonstrate conformity of the system (Article 16(k))."@en .

euai:DESIGNATION_MANAGEMENT_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DESIGNATION MANAGEMENT OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **DESIGNATION MANAGEMENT OBLIGATION** refers to the comprehensive set of procedural duties imposed on a notifying authority following a change in designation, such as a restriction, suspension, or withdrawal of a notified body. This process ensures regulatory oversight, transparency, and continuity for affected providers and certificates.

Upon a designation change, the notifying authority is mandated to maintain comprehensive files and assess the impact of the change on any certificates pre"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:DIRECTIVE_2014_90_EU a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "DIRECTIVE 2014/90/EU"@en ;
    skos:definition """Directive 2014/90/EU is a key legislative act concerning the regulation of marine equipment. This directive was established to standardize requirements for marine equipment placed on board ships, explicitly repealing the earlier Council Directive 96/98/EC to update and improve the regulatory framework.

In its recent evolution, Directive 2014/90/EU has been amended by Article 105 of the AI Act. This amendment serves to integrate specific requirements for artificial intelligence, ensuring that wh"""@en .

euai:DIRECTIVE__EU__2019_790 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "DIRECTIVE (EU) 2019/790"@en ;
    skos:definition """Directive (EU) 2019/790, widely known as the Directive on Copyright and Related Rights in the Digital Single Market, is a significant piece of European Union legislation. It establishes a modernized legal framework designed to address copyright challenges within the evolving digital landscape.

The directive is instrumental in defining various copyright exceptions and limitations that are applicable across the EU. Notably, it plays a key role in regulating text and data mining (TDM) activities, """@en .

euai:DIRECTIVE__EU__2019_882 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "DIRECTIVE (EU) 2019/882"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Directive (EU) 2019/882**, commonly referred to as the European Accessibility Act, is a critical legislative framework establishing mandatory accessibility requirements for a wide range of products and services within the European Union. Its primary objective is to harmonize accessibility standards, ensuring that digital and physical environments are inclusive, available, and usable by the public, including persons with disabilities and those belonging to vulnerable groups.

This directive pla"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ACCESSIBILITY_REQUIREMENT .

euai:DUTY_OF_INFORMATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DUTY OF INFORMATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Providers must inform distributors, deployers, authorised representatives, and importers of non-conformity, and inform authorities of risks as per Article 20"@en .

euai:EMPLOYMENT_AND_WORKERS_MANAGEMENT_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "EMPLOYMENT AND WORKERS MANAGEMENT AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "The \"Employment and Workers Management AI System\" refers to artificial intelligence technologies deployed within work-related relationships to manage key aspects of the employee lifecycle. These systems are utilized for recruitment, selection, promotion, termination, task allocation, and performance monitoring. Due to their significant impact on individuals' professional lives and livelihoods, these AI systems are officially classified as high-risk."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DATA_PROTECTION_AND_PRIVACY,
        euai:EMPLOYMENT,
        euai:HIGH_RISK,
        euai:NON_DISCRIMINATION,
        euai:NON_DISCRIMINATION_REQUIREMENT .

euai:ENHANCED_HUMAN_OVERSIGHT_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "ENHANCED HUMAN OVERSIGHT REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "The specific duty for certain biometric systems to require verification by at least two natural persons before any action or decision is taken by the deployer."@en .

euai:ENISA a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "ENISA"@en ;
    skos:definition """The European Union Agency for Cybersecurity, commonly referred to as ENISA, serves as the central authority responsible for promoting and ensuring a high level of cybersecurity throughout the European Union. Established and regulated by Regulation (EU) 2019/881—also known as the Cybersecurity Act—ENISA functions as the primary body tasked with developing and managing cybersecurity certification frameworks.

In its capacity as the EU's dedicated cybersecurity agency, ENISA provides vital knowledg"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ADVISORY_FORUM,
        euai:REGULATION__EU__2019_881 .

euai:ESSENTIAL_PUBLIC_SERVICES_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "ESSENTIAL PUBLIC SERVICES AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ESSENTIAL PUBLIC SERVICES AI SYSTEM**

The ESSENTIAL PUBLIC SERVICES AI SYSTEM refers to artificial intelligence technologies utilized by public authorities to make critical determinations regarding individual eligibility for vital services and support. These systems play a central role in managing access to essential resources, including healthcare, social security, and housing assistance. Due to the significant impact these decisions have on the lives and well-being of citizens, such AI syst"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ESSENTIAL_SERVICES,
        euai:HIGH_RISK .

euai:ESSENTIAL_SERVICES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AnnexIIICategory ;
    rdfs:label "ESSENTIAL SERVICES"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ESSENTIAL SERVICES** constitute one of the eight high-risk use case domains identified in Annex III of the relevant regulatory framework. This classification encompasses the critical areas required for the basic functioning of daily life, including both public and private sectors. Specifically, this domain covers public assistance, healthcare, and social security, as well as essential private services such as housing, electricity, and telecommunications.

In the context of modern governance an"""@en .

euai:EUROPEAN_CENTRAL_BANK a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "EUROPEAN CENTRAL BANK"@en ;
    skos:definition "The European Central Bank (ECB) serves as the central banking institution for the European Union. Beyond its monetary policy functions, it acts as a key EU institution responsible for executing prudential supervisory tasks. Within this supervisory framework, the ECB oversees credit institutions that participate in the Single Supervisory Mechanism (SSM). To facilitate this oversight, the ECB receives critical reports from national market surveillance authorities regarding these financial institut"@en .

euai:EVALUATION_AND_REVIEW_REPORT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "EVALUATION AND REVIEW REPORT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty of the Commission to submit reports every four years (or by specific deadlines like 2 August 2028) regarding the regulation, the AI Office, and standardization deliverables"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ADMINISTRATIVE_FINES,
        euai:COMMON_SPECIFICATIONS,
        euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL,
        euai:HARMONISED_STANDARDS,
        euai:SME .

euai:EVALUATION_OF_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "EVALUATION OF AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition """The evaluation of an AI system is a critical procedure performed by market surveillance authorities to ensure that AI technologies adhere to all established requirements and obligations under the Regulation. This process is essential for maintaining safety and accountability standards.

Specifically, the evaluation of an AI system is triggered when a market surveillance authority has reason to believe that a particular AI system may present a risk. In such instances, the authority is required to"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_79 .

euai:EVALUATION_OF_GPAI_MODEL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "EVALUATION OF GPAI MODEL"@en ;
    skos:definition "Assessment procedure conducted by the AI Office (or appointed independent experts) to determine compliance or investigate systemic risks when information requests are insufficient"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_92 .

euai:EXCLUSION_CONDITION__NON_EXPOSURE_TO_OUTPUT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "EXCLUSION CONDITION: NON-EXPOSURE TO OUTPUT"@en ;
    skos:definition """**EXCLUSION CONDITION: NON-EXPOSURE TO OUTPUT**

The "EXCLUSION CONDITION: NON-EXPOSURE TO OUTPUT" refers to specific criteria under which AI systems are exempt from being classified as high-risk, election-related AI systems. This exclusion applies to AI tools that are utilized for administrative, logistical, or organizational tasks within political campaigns. 

The primary determinant for this exclusion is that natural persons—specifically voters or the public—are not directly exposed to the ou"""@en .

euai:EXCLUSION_FOR_MILITARY__DEFENCE_AND_NATIONAL_SECURITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "EXCLUSION FOR MILITARY, DEFENCE AND NATIONAL SECURITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "AI systems placed on the market, put into service, or used for military, defence, or national security purposes are excluded from the scope of the Regulation, unless used for other (civilian/humanitarian) purposes."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_4_2__TEU .

euai:EXEMPTION_FROM_FINES_FOR_OTHER_LAW a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "EXEMPTION FROM FINES FOR OTHER LAW"@en ;
    skos:definition "Exemption from administrative fines regarding compliance with other Union and national law if other competent authorities were actively involved in sandbox supervision and guidance."@en .

euai:EXTENSION_OF_TESTING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "EXTENSION OF TESTING"@en ;
    skos:definition "The ability to extend testing by six months, subject to prior notification to the market surveillance authority"@en .

euai:FINANCIAL_FRAUD_DETECTION_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "FINANCIAL FRAUD DETECTION EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition """**FINANCIAL FRAUD DETECTION EXCLUSION** refers to a regulatory provision regarding the classification of artificial intelligence systems within the financial sector. Specifically, it defines the conditions under which AI systems designed for detecting financial fraud or for calculating prudential capital are exempt from being categorized as "high-risk." 

This exclusion ensures that AI tools used for these critical financial safety and security purposes—such as identifying fraudulent activities """@en .

euai:FINANCIAL_INTELLIGENCE_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "FINANCIAL INTELLIGENCE EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Condition under which AI systems used by financial intelligence units for administrative tasks are not classified as high-risk"@en .

euai:FINE_IMPOSITION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "FINE IMPOSITION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Commission may impose effective, proportionate, and dissuasive fines on providers for infringements, with specific review power by the CJEU"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CODE_OF_PRACTICE .

euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "GENERAL-PURPOSE AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition """A General-Purpose AI System is defined as an AI system based on or integrating a general-purpose AI model. Its core characteristic is its versatility; it is engineered with the capability to serve a wide variety of purposes. This flexibility allows a General-Purpose AI System to be utilized directly for diverse tasks or to be seamlessly integrated as a component within other, more specialized AI systems.

Because of this broad applicability, a General-Purpose AI System carries specific regulator"""@en ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:COOPERATION_OBLIGATION ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL,
        euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:HEALTH__SAFETY_AND_FUNDAMENTAL_RIGHTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "HEALTH, SAFETY AND FUNDAMENTAL RIGHTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "The specific protected interests that the risk-management system must identify, mitigate, and monitor risks against."@en .

euai:HIGH_IMPACT_CAPABILITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "HIGH IMPACT CAPABILITIES"@en,
        "HIGH-IMPACT CAPABILITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "\"High-impact capabilities\" refer to the specific functionalities within a general-purpose AI model that equal or surpass those found in the most advanced existing models. These capabilities serve as a critical benchmark for evaluating and classifying systemic risk, acting as a primary indicator for determining whether such models possess the potential to cause significant harm."@en,
        "A classification category for GPAI models that meet specific computational thresholds or equivalent impact criteria, triggering notification obligations (Article 51(1))"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL_WITH_SYSTEMIC_RISKS .

euai:INSTRUCTIONS_OF_USE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INSTRUCTIONS OF USE"@en ;
    skos:definition """**INSTRUCTIONS OF USE** constitute essential documentation provided by the system provider for high-risk AI systems. These instructions are mandatory for ensuring the safe and compliant operation of the AI system by the deployer.

Under Article 15(3), a critical component of these instructions involves the transparent declaration of the system's accuracy levels and the relevant accuracy metrics used to measure them. Furthermore, as outlined in Recital 91, the deployer is obligated to adhere to t"""@en .

euai:INVESTIGATION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "INVESTIGATION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The "INVESTIGATION OBLIGATION" represents a multifaceted requirement ensuring accountability and oversight within regulatory frameworks. This obligation mandates distinct duties for different stakeholders involved in compliance and safety management.

Primarily, the "INVESTIGATION OBLIGATION" imposes a duty on the provider to proactively manage safety. Following a serious incident, the provider is required to conduct thorough investigations, perform necessary risk assessments, and implement appr"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CORRECTIVE_ACTION,
        euai:RISK_ASSESSMENT .

euai:LAW_ENFORCEMENT_EXCEPTION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "LAW ENFORCEMENT EXCEPTION"@en ;
    skos:definition "An exemption from transparency and notification obligations where the use of the AI system is authorised by law to detect, prevent, investigate or prosecute criminal offences"@en .

euai:LAW_ENFORCEMENT_EXCEPTIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "LAW ENFORCEMENT EXCEPTIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Narrowly defined situations allowing the use of real-time remote biometric identification, including search for crime victims, threats to life/safety/terrorist attacks, and localisation of suspects of serious criminal offences (Recital 33)."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_33 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:REAL_TIME_REMOTE_BIOMETRIC_IDENTIFICATION_SYSTEM .

euai:LAW_ENFORCEMENT_SUPPORT_AI a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "LAW ENFORCEMENT SUPPORT AI"@en ;
    skos:definition "AI systems used by law enforcement for assessing criminal victimisation risk, as polygraphs, or for evaluation purposes."@en ;
    euai:belongsToCategory euai:LAW_ENFORCEMENT .

euai:LIABILITY_FOR_DAMAGE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "LIABILITY FOR DAMAGE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Providers and prospective providers remain liable under Union and national law for damage inflicted on third parties during sandbox experimentation."@en .

euai:LOGS rdfs:label "LOGS"@en .

euai:MANDATE_OF_AUTHORISED_REPRESENTATIVE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "MANDATE OF AUTHORISED REPRESENTATIVE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Third-country providers must appoint an authorised representative via written mandate and empower them to perform tasks like verifying conformity as per Article 22"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_22 .

euai:MANDATORY_REQUIREMENTS_FOR_HIGH_RISK_AI a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "MANDATORY REQUIREMENTS FOR HIGH-RISK AI"@en ;
    skos:definition "Mandatory requirements for high-risk AI systems comprise essential technical and organizational standards designed to ensure that these systems do not pose unacceptable risks. As outlined in Recital 46, these requirements serve the dual purpose of preventing harm in a general sense and specifically safeguarding Union public interests from the potential threats posed by high-risk AI deployment."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_46 .

euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "MARKET SURVEILLANCE AUTHORITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition """Market Surveillance Authorities are national bodies tasked with the responsibility of overseeing and enforcing market regulations. These authorities play a critical role in cross-border market surveillance, a process in which they receive essential support from a dedicated scientific panel to enhance the effectiveness of their operations.

Furthermore, Market Surveillance Authorities are empowered with specific access rights to information that is registered within the European Union database, a"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ADMINISTRATIVE_COOPERATION_GROUP,
        euai:EU_DATABASE_FOR_HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEMS .

euai:MARKING_AND_DETECTION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "MARKING AND DETECTION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for providers of content-generating AI systems to embed machine-readable technical solutions (watermarks, metadata, etc.) to identify AI-generated/manipulated content. Excludes assistive editing tools or systems not substantially altering input data."@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:CONTENT_GENERATION_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:MATERIAL_INFLUENCE_CRITERION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ClassificationRule ;
    rdfs:label "MATERIAL INFLUENCE CRITERION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The criterion that an AI system must materially influence the outcome of decision-making to be considered high-risk; systems that do not are potentially exempt (Recital 53)"@en .

euai:METROLOGY_AND_BENCHMARKING_AUTHORITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "METROLOGY AND BENCHMARKING AUTHORITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition """**METROLOGY AND BENCHMARKING AUTHORITIES**

Metrology and benchmarking authorities serve as critical stakeholders and expert organizations that collaborate directly with the Commission. Their primary mandate involves cooperating with the Commission to establish and refine rigorous benchmarks and measurement methodologies. Specifically, these authorities focus on evaluating the accuracy and robustness of artificial intelligence systems, ensuring that AI technologies meet established standards thr"""@en .

euai:MIGRATION__ASYLUM_AND_BORDER_CONTROL_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "MIGRATION, ASYLUM AND BORDER CONTROL AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition """The Migration, Asylum and Border Control AI System encompasses artificial intelligence technologies deployed by competent public authorities to manage the critical processes of migration, asylum, and border control. These systems are designed to assist officials in various administrative and security functions, playing a significant role in the oversight of international arrivals and residency applications.

Key functionalities of these AI systems include, but are not limited to, the utilization"""@en ;
    euai:alwaysClassifiedAs euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ACCURACY,
        euai:ACCURACY_REQUIREMENT,
        euai:MIGRATION__ASYLUM_AND_BORDER_CONTROL,
        euai:NON_DISCRIMINATION,
        euai:NON_DISCRIMINATION_REQUIREMENT,
        euai:NON_REFOULEMENT_OBLIGATION,
        euai:PROCEDURAL_REQUIREMENTS,
        euai:TRANSPARENCY,
        euai:TRANSPARENCY_REQUIREMENT,
        euai:TRAVEL_DOCUMENT_VERIFICATION_EXCLUSION .

euai:NATIONAL_COMPETENT_AUTHORITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "NATIONAL COMPETENT AUTHORITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition """National Competent Authorities serve as key regulatory bodies tasked with the oversight and supervision of artificial intelligence systems. Operating in conjunction with the European Commission, these authorities hold significant responsibilities regarding both high-risk AI systems and General Purpose AI (GPAI) models. 

Specifically, regarding high-risk AI systems, National Competent Authorities are responsible for overseeing their placement on the market. In this capacity, they are empowered t"""@en .

euai:NATIONAL_LAW a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "NATIONAL LAW"@en ;
    skos:definition "Reference to the specific national legal frameworks of Member States which define appropriate safeguards and conditions for urgent use of AI systems, or authorize the deployment of such systems."@en .

euai:NOTIFICATION_OF_LIST_OF_AUTHORITIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "NOTIFICATION OF LIST OF AUTHORITIES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Member States must notify the Commission and other Member States of the list of public authorities protecting fundamental rights by 2 November 2024"@en .

euai:NOTIFICATION_OF_SERIOUS_INCIDENTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "NOTIFICATION OF SERIOUS INCIDENTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty to report serious incidents for high-risk AI systems (medical devices) to the chosen national competent authority"@en .

euai:OBJECTION_PERIOD a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "OBJECTION PERIOD"@en ;
    skos:definition """The term "OBJECTION PERIOD" refers to specific, defined timeframes during which authorized bodies—such as the Commission, Member States, the European Parliament, or the Council—may challenge or halt proposed actions or regulations. While the duration and purpose of these periods vary depending on the specific regulatory context, they all serve as a mechanism to pause implementation until concerns are addressed.

In the context of notified bodies, the objection period acts as a regulatory safegua"""@en .

euai:OFFICIAL_JOURNAL_OF_THE_EUROPEAN_UNION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "OFFICIAL JOURNAL OF THE EUROPEAN UNION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Official Journal of the European Union serves as the official publication medium for references to harmonised standards and common specifications. Its role is pivotal in the regulatory framework of the European Union, as the publication of these references within the Journal is the required mechanism to trigger specific legal effects. Notably, this publication is the formal step necessary to establish the presumption of conformity for products or services adhering to these standards."@en ;
    euai:triggers euai:HARMONISED_STANDARD .

euai:OPEN_SOURCE_EXCEPTION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "OPEN SOURCE EXCEPTION"@en,
        "OPEN-SOURCE EXCEPTION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Condition where providers of open-source GPAI models are exempt from certain transparency obligations, unless the model presents a systemic risk"@en,
        "Obligations under Article 53(1)(a) and (b) do not apply to models released under free and open-source licenses, provided parameters are public, unless the model has systemic risk."@en ;
    euai:isExemptFromHighRisk euai:TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION_OBLIGATION .

euai:PENALTIES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PENALTIES"@en ;
    skos:definition """Penalties serve as a critical enforcement mechanism designed to address non-compliance with the Regulation. To ensure their legitimacy and impact, these measures must be effective, proportionate, and dissuasive. 

Under the established framework, Member States are mandated to lay down, notify, and effectively implement rules regarding these penalties—which include administrative fines—by the deadline of 2 August 2025. Furthermore, the state and ongoing effectiveness of these penalties are subjec"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:APPLICATION_DATE_2_AUGUST_2025 .

euai:PRIVACY_PRESERVING_TECHNIQUES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "PRIVACY-PRESERVING TECHNIQUES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Techniques used during development and testing of AI systems to protect personal data while meeting data set requirements"@en .

euai:PRODUCT_MANUFACTURER a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "PRODUCT MANUFACTURER"@en ;
    skos:definition """A Product Manufacturer is defined as any natural or legal person who either manufactures a product themselves or arranges for a product to be designed or manufactured, ultimately marketing that product under their own name or trademark. This definition extends to entities that place a product on the market or put it into service, including those incorporating AI systems.

Within the specific context of AI regulation, a Product Manufacturer holds significant responsibilities. When a manufacturer """@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_2,
        euai:NEW_LEGISLATIVE_FRAMEWORK ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:COMMON_SPECIFICATIONS,
        euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT,
        euai:HARMONISED_STANDARDS,
        euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:UNION_HARMONISATION_LEGISLATION ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ARTICLE_16 .

euai:PROFESSIONAL_SECRECY_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROFESSIONAL SECRECY OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Notified body staff must maintain secrecy regarding information obtained during their tasks, except when required by law or in relation to notifying authorities"@en .

euai:PROJECT_SUMMARY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROJECT SUMMARY"@en ;
    skos:definition "A short summary of the AI project developed in the sandbox, including objectives and results, which must be published by the competent authority"@en .

euai:PUBLICLY_ACCESSIBLE_SPACE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "PUBLICLY ACCESSIBLE SPACE"@en ;
    skos:definition """A "Publicly Accessible Space" is defined as any physical location—whether publicly or privately owned—that is open to an undetermined number of natural persons. As detailed in the provided references, this category encompasses a wide range of environments, including but not limited to commercial, service, transport, sport, and entertainment areas.

The designation of a Publicly Accessible Space is largely independent of ownership, specific activities, or minor entry requirements. For instance, t"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_3_44_ .

euai:PUBLIC_AUTHORITIES_OF_A_THIRD_COUNTRY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "PUBLIC AUTHORITIES OF A THIRD COUNTRY"@en ;
    skos:definition "**PUBLIC AUTHORITIES OF A THIRD COUNTRY** are foreign entities that may be excluded from the scope of the Regulation when they are operating within the framework of cooperation or international agreements specifically related to law enforcement and judicial cooperation. This exclusion is not automatic; rather, it is conditional, requiring these public authorities to provide adequate safeguards in their activities to qualify for this exemption."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:EXCLUSION_FOR_MILITARY__DEFENCE_AND_NATIONAL_SECURITY,
        euai:INTERNATIONAL_COOPERATION_EXCLUSION .

euai:PUBLIC_PROCUREMENT_PROCEDURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "PUBLIC PROCUREMENT PROCEDURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Public procurement procedures represent a critical area where the Commission is tasked with evaluating and promoting the convergence of best practices concerning the implementation and use of AI systems. Specifically, under Article 62(3)(d), the AI Office is mandated to carry out this evaluation and promotion, ensuring that consistent and high-quality standards are applied when integrating artificial intelligence within public sector procurement."@en .

euai:QUALIFIED_ALERT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "QUALIFIED ALERT"@en ;
    skos:definition """A "QUALIFIED ALERT" is a formal notification issued by the scientific panel to the AI Office. Its primary purpose is to draw official attention to specific concerns related to General Purpose AI (GPAI) models or broader Union-level regulatory compliance. Specifically, a QUALIFIED ALERT serves as the mechanism for communicating the following issues:

*   **Systemic or Identifiable Risks:** Under Article 90, the panel utilizes this alert to notify the AI Office regarding suspected systemic risks o"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_OFFICE,
        euai:ARTICLE_90,
        euai:SYSTEMIC_RISK .

euai:REAL_WORLD_TESTING_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REAL-WORLD TESTING OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty for providers to comply with specific conditions (e.g., registration, plan submission, EU establishment) when conducting real-world testing of high-risk AI systems. Includes time limits (6 months, extendable by 6 months) and specific registration requirements per Annex IX"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_49_4_,
        euai:ARTICLE_49_5_,
        euai:ARTICLE_71_4_ ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:VULNERABLE_GROUPS ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ARTICLE_5,
        euai:ETHICAL_REVIEW .

euai:REASSESSMENT_PROCEDURE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REASSESSMENT PROCEDURE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A process where a provider, upon reasoned request, can ask the Commission to re-evaluate whether a model designated as having systemic risk still presents such risks."@en .

euai:RECITAL_17 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 17"@en ;
    skos:definition "Recital defining 'remote biometric identification system', its variants (real-time/post), and exclusions for biometric verification."@en .

euai:RECITAL_29 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 29"@en ;
    skos:definition "**RECITAL 29** is a critical section of the Act that establishes prohibitions concerning manipulative and exploitative artificial intelligence practices. Specifically, it outlines the prohibition of AI systems designed to materially distort human behavior through the use of manipulative techniques. By addressing these harmful applications, RECITAL 29 serves as a regulatory safeguard against AI deployments that aim to exploit users or undermine their autonomy."@en .

euai:RECITAL_30 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 30"@en ;
    skos:definition """**RECITAL 30** functions as a key provision within the Act, specifically addressing the regulatory framework surrounding biometric categorisation systems. Its primary purpose is to delineate the strict limitations imposed on these technologies. 

RECITAL 30 establishes a clear prohibition against the use of biometric categorisation systems that attempt to infer sensitive or protected attributes—such as race, political opinions, trade union membership, religious or philosophical beliefs, sex life"""@en .

euai:RECITAL_33 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 33"@en ;
    skos:definition "**RECITAL 33** serves as a critical regulatory component, specifically outlining the narrow and exhaustively listed exceptions under which the use of real-time remote biometric identification is permissible for law enforcement purposes. It provides the necessary legal framework and constraints for law enforcement agencies regarding the deployment of these biometric technologies, ensuring that such use is strictly limited to the specific scenarios defined within the text."@en .

euai:RECITAL_47 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 47"@en ;
    skos:definition "Recital addressing safety risks of AI systems acting as safety components in products"@en .

euai:RECITAL_72 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 72"@en ;
    skos:definition "RECITAL 72 is a specific section of the EU AI Act that establishes the framework for critical transparency and oversight obligations regarding artificial intelligence systems. This recital explicitly addresses the essential requirements for technical documentation, automatic logging, and post-market monitoring. By detailing these provisions, RECITAL 72 ensures that developers and deployers of AI systems maintain rigorous standards for accountability, performance tracking, and the ongoing assessm"@en .

euai:RECITAL_73 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 73"@en ;
    skos:definition """**RECITAL 73**

RECITAL 73 of the EU AI Act serves as a critical provision regarding the governance of high-risk artificial intelligence systems. It establishes fundamental requirements for transparency, operational functionality, and human oversight, ensuring that these systems are deployed safely and ethically.

Central to RECITAL 73 is the requirement for comprehensive transparency. This necessitates that providers of high-risk AI systems furnish clear, accessible, and detailed instructions f"""@en .

euai:REGULATION_2024_1689 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION 2024/1689"@en ;
    skos:definition """Regulation 2024/1689, widely known as the EU Artificial Intelligence Act, serves as the definitive legislative framework governing artificial intelligence within the European Union. This regulation establishes a comprehensive system of harmonized rules designed to oversee the development, deployment, and utilization of artificial intelligence technologies.

By providing a structured classification system, Regulation 2024/1689 sets out clear standards for the regulation of various AI models. The """@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_109,
        euai:ARTICLE_110,
        euai:ARTICLE_19,
        euai:ARTICLE_43,
        euai:ARTICLE_47,
        euai:ARTICLE_57,
        euai:ARTICLE_58 .

euai:REGULATION__EC__NO_300_2008 rdfs:label "REGULATION  EC  NO 300 2008"@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2017_745 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2017/745"@en ;
    skos:definition """**REGULATION (EU) 2017/745**, also known as the Medical Device Regulation (MDR), serves as the primary piece of Union legislation governing medical devices. This regulation establishes a comprehensive framework for the safety and performance requirements of such devices within the European Union.

Crucially, **REGULATION (EU) 2017/745** functions as a key component of Union harmonisation legislation. It contains specific provisions that are designed to prevail over general modifications introduc"""@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:PROVIDER_CLASSIFICATION_RULE .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2017_746 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2017/746"@en ;
    skos:definition "**REGULATION (EU) 2017/746** is a piece of European Union legislation that governs in vitro diagnostic (IVD) medical devices. Beyond setting the standard for the regulation of these devices, the regulation plays a critical role in the oversight of modern medical technologies; specifically, it impacts the scope of serious incident reporting requirements for artificial intelligence (AI) systems that function as safety components within these diagnostic devices. By establishing these regulatory fra"@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__NO_1025_2012 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) NO 1025/2012"@en ;
    skos:definition """**REGULATION (EU) NO 1025/2012** is the central legislative framework governing the European standardisation system. It serves as the definitive EU regulation that establishes the rules and procedures for the development of harmonised standards, which are critical for the functioning of the European Single Market. 

This regulation is fundamental to the standardisation process, as it mandates specific requirements regarding stakeholder representation, ensuring that the development of standards i"""@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__NO_167_2013 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) NO 167/2013"@en ;
    skos:definition """Regulation (EU) No 167/2013 serves as the primary legislative framework governing the approval and market surveillance of agricultural and forestry vehicles. This regulation establishes the essential requirements for ensuring that these vehicles meet safety, environmental, and performance standards before they can be placed on the market.

Beyond its foundational role, Regulation (EU) No 167/2013 is dynamic and subject to updates to align with evolving technological landscapes. Specifically, it """@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__NO_168_2013 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) NO 168/2013"@en ;
    skos:definition """Regulation (EU) No 168/2013 is a significant legislative act established to govern the approval and market surveillance of two- or three-wheel vehicles and quadricycles within the European Union. This regulation sets the framework for the type-approval requirements, ensuring that these vehicles meet necessary safety, environmental, and functional standards before they can be placed on the market.

Beyond its foundational role, the regulation has evolved to address contemporary technological adva"""@en .

euai:REPORTING_SERIOUS_INCIDENTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REPORTING SERIOUS INCIDENTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Providers are required to have a system to report serious incidents resulting from the use of their AI systems to relevant authorities."@en .

euai:RESEARCH_AND_PROTOTYPING_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "RESEARCH AND PROTOTYPING EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "**RESEARCH AND PROTOTYPING EXCLUSION** refers to a regulatory provision that exempts certain AI models from specific definitions and obligations established under the Regulation. This exclusion applies exclusively to AI models that are utilized solely for the purposes of research, development, and prototyping activities. The exemption is time-bound, remaining valid only for the duration of these activities before the AI model is officially placed on the market. Consequently, as long as these mod"@en .

euai:RESERVATION_OF_RIGHTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "RESERVATION OF RIGHTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Right exercised by rightsholders to prevent text and data mining of their works, which providers must respect pursuant to Article 4(3) of Directive (EU) 2019/790"@en .

euai:RESIDUAL_RISK a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:RiskCategory ;
    rdfs:label "RESIDUAL RISK"@en ;
    skos:definition "The level of risk remaining after risk management measures have been applied, which must be judged to be acceptable under Article 9(5)"@en .

euai:RIGHT_TO_AN_EXPLANATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "RIGHT TO AN EXPLANATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **Right to an Explanation** is a crucial protection afforded to individuals interacting with artificial intelligence systems. It establishes a clear obligation for the deployer—the entity utilizing the technology—to proactively inform natural persons of their specific entitlement to receive an explanation regarding decisions rendered by high-risk AI systems. 

Under this framework, affected individuals have the right to obtain a clear, meaningful, and understandable explanation when a decisi"""@en .

euai:RIGHT_TO_EXPLANATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "RIGHT TO EXPLANATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The "Right to Explanation" is a key provision, specifically detailed in Article 86, that centers on the transparency and accountability of artificial intelligence systems. This right ensures that individuals who are impacted by decisions made by AI systems are entitled to receive a clear and meaningful explanation regarding the role the AI played in that individual decision-making process.

Essentially, Article 86 establishes a corresponding obligation for deployers of these AI systems. These de"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_86 .

euai:RIGHT_TO_WITHDRAW a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "RIGHT TO WITHDRAW"@en ;
    skos:definition "The provider must ensure subjects can withdraw from testing at any time, without justification or detriment, and exercise their right to data deletion, per Article 60(5)"@en .

euai:RISK_ASSESSMENT_CRITERIA a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RISK ASSESSMENT CRITERIA"@en ;
    skos:definition """The Risk Assessment Criteria, as outlined in Article 7(2), serve as the fundamental framework used by the Commission to evaluate and determine whether specific AI systems should be classified as high-risk and subsequently added to the Annex III list of high-risk use cases.

These criteria encompass a broad spectrum of factors designed to assess the potential impact and safety of AI technologies. They include critical operational and functional elements such as an AI system’s intended purpose, it"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_7_2_ .

euai:RISK_MITIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RISK MITIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "**RISK MITIGATION** refers to the essential and mandatory protocols established to address significant risks identified throughout the development and testing phases of an AI system. These measures are not optional; they are critical safeguards designed to ensure the safety and reliability of the technology. The process emphasizes a strict adherence to these requirements: if the identified significant risks cannot be adequately addressed or mitigated, the development process must be suspended im"@en .

euai:RISK_MITIGATION_MEASURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RISK MITIGATION MEASURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific measures mandated by the AI Office to address identified systemic risks in general-purpose AI models"@en .

euai:SANDBOX_PLAN a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "SANDBOX PLAN"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **SANDBOX PLAN** is a formal, mandatory document established as a prerequisite for participation in an AI regulatory sandbox. Defined in Article 3(54) of the relevant regulations, it functions as a specific agreement between a provider (or a prospective provider) and the competent authority overseeing the sandbox.

This document serves as the structural framework for testing activities, outlining the necessary scope, objectives, conditions, timeframe, and specific requirements for the sandbo"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOX,
        euai:COMPETENT_AUTHORITY,
        euai:PROVIDER .

euai:SINGLE_DEDICATED_INTERFACE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "SINGLE DEDICATED INTERFACE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A platform developed by the Commission to provide information, facilitate interactions with sandboxes, and allow stakeholder enquiries (Recital 17)."@en .

euai:STAKEHOLDERS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "STAKEHOLDERS"@en ;
    skos:definition """Stakeholders constitute a diverse group of entities that play a critical role in the regulatory and developmental framework of AI systems. These parties are essential for providing expert insight, oversight, and collaborative input at various stages of governance and standardization.

Broadly, stakeholders encompass a wide array of sectors, including business entities, civil society organizations, academic institutions, research organizations, trade unions, and consumer protection groups. These """@en .

euai:STANDARDISATION_ORGANISATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "STANDARDISATION ORGANISATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Standardisation organisations comprise national or European-level bodies tasked with the development of technical standards. Within the framework of the AI regulatory sandbox, as outlined in Article 58(2)(f), these organisations play a crucial role by cooperating with sandbox participants. Their primary function in this context is to provide expert assistance, helping entities navigate compliance requirements and effectively integrate relevant standards into their development processes."@en .

euai:STANDING_SUBGROUP_FOR_MARKET_SURVEILLANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "STANDING SUBGROUP FOR MARKET SURVEILLANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A subgroup responsible for market surveillance activities whose activities the Commission should support."@en .

euai:STATE_OF_THE_ART_ON_AI a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "STATE OF THE ART ON AI"@en ;
    skos:definition "The baseline technological and safety standard that providers must take into account when adopting measures to comply with the mandatory requirements of the Regulation."@en .

euai:STOP_BUTTON a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "STOP BUTTON"@en ;
    skos:definition "A specific technical measure or procedure allowing natural persons to interrupt the system and bring it to a safe state"@en .

euai:SUBSTANTIAL_MODIFICATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ClassificationRule ;
    rdfs:label "SUBSTANTIAL MODIFICATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "A \"Substantial Modification\" refers to a specific type of alteration made to a high-risk AI system, such as changes to its software architecture or its intended purpose. When such a modification occurs, it triggers a regulatory requirement for the system to undergo a new conformity assessment to ensure it remains compliant. Furthermore, the act of implementing a substantial modification carries significant legal implications: the party responsible for making these changes is legally considered t"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_6,
        euai:CHAPTER_III__SECTION_2,
        euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT,
        euai:PROVIDER .

euai:SUBSTANTIATED_ARGUMENTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "SUBSTANTIATED ARGUMENTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Documentation provided by a GPAI model provider to demonstrate that, despite meeting computation thresholds, the model does not present systemic risks (Article 52(2))"@en .

euai:SYSTEMIC_RISK_CRITERIA a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "SYSTEMIC RISK CRITERIA"@en ;
    skos:definition "Criteria used by the Commission to designate general-purpose AI models with systemic risk. Includes: number of parameters, dataset quality/size, computation amount (FLOPs/cost/time/energy), input/output modalities, and model benchmarks/evaluations, as specified in Annex XIII."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ANNEX_XIII .

euai:SYSTEMIC_RISK_THRESHOLD a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:SystemicRisk ;
    rdfs:label "SYSTEMIC RISK THRESHOLD"@en ;
    skos:definition "A classification triggered by general-purpose AI models that meet specific criteria (such as 10^25 FLOPs or significant scale), resulting in additional obligations under Article 55"@en .

euai:TAX_AND_CUSTOMS_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "TAX AND CUSTOMS EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Condition under which AI systems used for tax/customs administrative proceedings are not classified as high-risk"@en .

euai:TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION_ASSESSMENT_CERTIFICATE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "TECHNICAL DOCUMENTATION ASSESSMENT CERTIFICATE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A formal certificate issued by a notified body to a provider confirming that an AI system conforms with the requirements set out in Chapter III, Section 2"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_IV .

euai:TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "TECHNICAL DOCUMENTATION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty to draw up and keep up-to-date technical documentation of the model (including training/testing process and results) per Article 53(1)(a)."@en ;
    euai:isBasedOn euai:ANNEX_XI .

euai:TESTING_AND_EXPERIMENTATION_FACILITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "TESTING AND EXPERIMENTATION FACILITY"@en ;
    skos:definition """The TESTING AND EXPERIMENTATION FACILITY represents a critical component of the broader artificial intelligence ecosystem. These organizations provide the essential infrastructure and environments necessary to support the ongoing development and experimentation of AI technologies. 

Functioning as a resource for prospective AI providers, a TESTING AND EXPERIMENTATION FACILITY offers a secure, controlled environment—often referred to as a sandbox—where developers can build, refine, and rigorously"""@en .

euai:TESTING_DURATION_LIMIT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TESTING DURATION LIMIT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Testing in real world conditions must not exceed six months, extendable for another six months upon notification, per Article 60(f)"@en .

euai:TESTING_PLAN a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TESTING PLAN"@en ;
    skos:definition "The plan governing the testing of an AI system in real world conditions, against which market surveillance authorities evaluate compliance"@en .

euai:TRANSPARENCY_OBLIGATIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "TRANSPARENCY OBLIGATIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Transparency Obligations**

Transparency Obligations under the current AI regulatory framework refer to a set of binding rules designed to ensure accountability and clarity regarding the use of specific artificial intelligence systems. These obligations are implemented as a core component of the Regulation's overarching risk-based approach, which categorizes AI systems based on their potential impact and risks.

At the heart of these requirements is the duty to inform both users and deployers """@en .

euai:UNACCEPTABLE_RISK a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:RiskCategory ;
    rdfs:label "UNACCEPTABLE RISK"@en ;
    skos:definition "\"UNACCEPTABLE RISK\" is the classification level assigned to specific artificial intelligence practices that are prohibited under regulatory frameworks, as detailed in Article 5 of the relevant legislation. This category represents the highest level of risk associated with AI applications. The prohibition of practices falling under this classification is further elaborated in Recitals 29 and 30, which provide context regarding the nature of these prohibited activities. According to Recital 179, t"@en ;
    euai:triggers euai:PROHIBITION_OF_CERTAIN_AI_PRACTICES .

euai:UNION_AI_TESTING_SUPPORT_STRUCTURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "UNION AI TESTING SUPPORT STRUCTURES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Union AI Testing Support Structures are specialized entities designated by the European Commission. Their primary mandate is to perform essential testing tasks in accordance with Regulation (EU) 2019/1020. Beyond their testing responsibilities, these structures are tasked with providing independent, expert technical and scientific advice. Furthermore, these structures are established to support the enforcement of AI regulations and to reinforce the overall capacities of Member States concerning "@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_84 .

euai:UNION_INSTITUTION__BODY__OFFICE_OR_AGENCY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "UNION INSTITUTION, BODY, OFFICE OR AGENCY"@en ;
    skos:definition """A Union institution, body, office, or agency refers to the organizational entities within the European Union that are subject to regulatory oversight regarding their use of artificial intelligence. These entities are accountable under specific regulations concerning non-compliance with established AI practices and obligations and may be subject to administrative fines should they fail to meet these standards.

Within this regulatory framework, such Union institutions, bodies, offices, and agenci"""@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_LAW_ENFORCEMENT_VICTIM_ASSESSMENT .

euai:UNION_LAW rdfs:label "UNION LAW"@en .

euai:URGENT_DEPLOYMENT_AUTHORISATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "URGENT DEPLOYMENT AUTHORISATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "An authorization mechanism allowing law enforcement or civil protection authorities to deploy high-risk AI systems in urgent, life-threatening situations without prior authorization, subject to post-hoc request."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:URGENT_DEPLOYMENT_EXCEPTION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "URGENT DEPLOYMENT EXCEPTION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Law enforcement and civil protection authorities may put a high-risk AI system into service without prior authorisation from market surveillance authorities in duly justified situations, provided authorisation is requested during or after use without undue delay"@en .

euai:VOLUNTARY_CODES_OF_CONDUCT_EVALUATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "VOLUNTARY CODES OF CONDUCT EVALUATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Commission must evaluate the impact and effectiveness of voluntary codes of conduct by 2 August 2028 and every three years thereafter (Recital 174)."@en .

euai:VOLUNTARY_CODE_OF_CONDUCT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:CodeOfPractice ;
    rdfs:label "VOLUNTARY CODE OF CONDUCT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Instruments drawn up by the Commission and Member States in cooperation with stakeholders to advance AI literacy among persons dealing with the development, operation, and use of AI."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_LITERACY .

euai:VULNERABLE_GROUPS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "VULNERABLE GROUPS"@en ;
    skos:definition """"VULNERABLE GROUPS" refers to specific populations that require special attention, heightened protection, and nuanced consideration during the implementation of AI systems and related regulatory processes. This category primarily encompasses individuals under the age of 18, as well as persons with disabilities or other conditions that might render them particularly susceptible to adverse impacts.

The identification of these groups is central to robust risk management processes. Because these in"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:TRANSPARENCY_OBLIGATION .

euai:WITHDRAWAL_OF_AUTHORISATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "WITHDRAWAL OF AUTHORISATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The duty of a market surveillance authority to revoke an authorization if the Commission deems said authorization unjustified."@en .

euai:WRITTEN_MANDATE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "WRITTEN MANDATE"@en ;
    skos:definition "A legal requirement for providers established in third countries to appoint an authorised representative in the Union via a written mandate (Recital 82)"@en .

euai:ACCESSIBILITY_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "ACCESSIBILITY REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ACCESSIBILITY REQUIREMENT**

An Accessibility Requirement represents a set of mandatory standards established to ensure that products and services remain fully accessible to all individuals, with a specific focus on promoting equal access for persons with disabilities. These requirements are formalized through key legal frameworks, most notably Directive (EU) 2016/2102 and Directive (EU) 2019/882. Under these mandates, providers are under a strict obligation to ensure full compliance, thereby """@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:DIRECTIVE__EU__2019_882 .

euai:ACCESS_TO_SOURCE_CODE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "ACCESS TO SOURCE CODE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific access right granted to market surveillance authorities under strict conditions: necessity for conformity assessment and exhaustion of other testing methods"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_LAW_ENFORCEMENT_VICTIM_ASSESSMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "AI SYSTEM FOR LAW ENFORCEMENT VICTIM ASSESSMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "System used to assess the risk of a natural person becoming the victim of criminal offences, identified in Annex III(6)(a)"@en .

euai:ANNEX_VI a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ANNEX VI"@en ;
    skos:definition "Annex VI serves as a foundational regulatory component that details the conformity assessment procedure based on internal control. This specific procedure is established as a critical mechanism for demonstrating compliance with the requirements set forth for high-risk AI systems. By outlining this internal control-based approach, Annex VI provides the necessary framework for organizations to verify that their high-risk AI systems meet the mandated standards."@en ;
    euai:belongsToCategory euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT_PROCEDURE .

euai:ANNEX_XI a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ANNEX XI"@en ;
    skos:definition "**ANNEX XI** is a specific and essential component of the EU AI Act. It serves as the formal section that outlines the comprehensive requirements for the technical documentation of general-purpose AI models. By detailing the specific content that must be included within these documents, ANNEX XI ensures transparency and regulatory compliance for developers working with these advanced systems."@en .

euai:ANNEX_XIII a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ANNEX XIII"@en ;
    skos:definition "**ANNEX XIII** serves as a regulatory component that explicitly outlines the criteria used to determine whether a general-purpose AI (GPAI) model should be designated as presenting systemic risks. This annex provides the specific framework utilized by the European Commission for assessing and designating such models, directly supporting the requirements established in Article 51 of the underlying AI legislation."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_51 .

euai:ARTICLE_101 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 101"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 101 serves as a specific provision within the legal framework, functioning primarily as an exception to the general application date of 2 August 2025 established for other chapters. Beyond its timing provisions, Article 101 is fundamentally an enforcement mechanism centered on financial penalties. It defines the fines applicable to entities for supplying incorrect, incomplete, or misleading information to the relevant authorities. Furthermore, the article establishes fines specifically t"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_113 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:COMMISSION .

euai:ARTICLE_18_OF_REGULATION__EU__2019_1020 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 18 OF REGULATION (EU) 2019/1020"@en ;
    skos:definition """Article 18 of Regulation (EU) 2019/1020 serves as a critical legal provision that delineates the procedural rights afforded to concerned operators during market surveillance procedures. By establishing these rights, the regulation ensures that operators are afforded due process and necessary protections when their products are subject to regulatory oversight.

Furthermore, Article 18 of Regulation (EU) 2019/1020 is extended to the domain of artificial intelligence regulation. It applies *mutatis"""@en .

euai:ARTICLE_42 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 42"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 42 addresses the presumption of conformity for high-risk AI systems. Specifically, it establishes provisions under which these systems are presumed to satisfy certain requirements based on their adherence to specific standards. This presumption is granted when high-risk AI systems demonstrate compliance through either the quality of their training data or by obtaining relevant cybersecurity certification. Consequently, Article 42 serves as a mechanism to streamline regulatory compliance "@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:REGULATION__EU__2019_881 .

euai:ARTICLE_51 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 51"@en ;
    skos:definition "**Article 51** serves as the regulatory framework establishing the classification and specific criteria used to identify general-purpose AI (GPAI) models that pose systemic risks. It defines the conditions under which a GPAI model is categorized as having systemic risk, a designation that includes criteria for high-impact capabilities and specific compute thresholds. Furthermore, this article is cross-referenced in Article 90, highlighting its pivotal role in the governance structure for high-im"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL_WITH_SYSTEMIC_RISK ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_XIII .

euai:ARTICLE_56 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 56"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 56 functions as a critical regulatory provision specifically addressing the codes of practice for general-purpose AI models. It defines the meaning and scope of these codes, establishing the essential framework and outlining the development process required for their implementation. By setting these standards, Article 56 provides the necessary guidance and structure for the governance of general-purpose AI technologies."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_58 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 58"@en ;
    skos:definition """Article 58 of the AI Act is a regulatory provision that serves two primary functions: establishing the framework for AI regulatory sandboxes and dictating specific considerations for safety-critical AI systems.

First, Article 58 acts as the governing provision for AI regulatory sandboxes. It outlines the detailed arrangements and procedures required for their operation, ensuring that these sandboxes function effectively within the broader AI regulatory framework.

Second, Article 58 has been am"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DELEGATED_ACTS,
        euai:REQUIREMENTS_IN_CHAPTER_III_SECTION_2 .

euai:ARTICLE_6 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 6"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Article 6** serves as a critical regulatory provision that establishes the classification rules for high-risk AI systems. Central to its function, this article defines the criteria and specific conditions under which an AI system is categorized as "high-risk," while also delineating the circumstances under which such systems may be granted exemptions from these rigorous classifications.

Furthermore, **Article 6** integrates broader regulatory frameworks by explicitly referencing the requireme"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_97 ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ARTICLE_96 .

euai:ARTICLE_67 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 67"@en ;
    skos:definition """Article 67 serves as the foundational provision that establishes the Advisory Forum. This article outlines the formal framework for the Forum, explicitly detailing its membership structure, core duties, term of office, and the operational rules that govern its conduct. 

In addition to defining its organizational structure, Article 67 mandates the Advisory Forum’s role in specific regulatory processes, stipulating that the Forum must be consulted regarding the development or implementation of co"""@en .

euai:ARTICLE_79_1_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 79(1)"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ARTICLE 79(1)**

ARTICLE 79(1) serves as a foundational provision for establishing the regulatory framework surrounding artificial intelligence. Its primary purpose is to define the concept of "risk" specifically within the context of AI systems. This definition is critical for identifying and categorizing potential hazards that may arise during the operation of AI technologies.

Furthermore, ARTICLE 79(1) delineates the specific thresholds and parameters that constitute a "risk" requiring for"""@en .

euai:ARTICLE_81 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 81"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 81 serves as the governing provision for the Union safeguard procedure. It establishes the formal mechanism for evaluating and handling national measures taken against AI systems, providing the necessary framework for ensuring consistent oversight and regulatory compliance across the Union."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_9 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 9"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 9 outlines the mandatory requirements regarding risk management systems specifically designed for high-risk AI systems. This article establishes a regulatory framework that mandates the creation, implementation, documentation, and ongoing maintenance of a comprehensive risk management system. By requiring these processes, Article 9 ensures that organizations developing or operating high-risk AI systems have structured protocols in place to identify, assess, and mitigate potential risks t"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_92 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 92"@en ;
    skos:definition "**Article 92** functions as the governing regulation concerning the evaluation of general-purpose AI (GPAI) models. It establishes the legal framework and authority for conducting these critical assessments. Furthermore, Article 92 outlines the enforcement mechanisms related to these evaluations, specifically mandating that GPAI providers grant necessary access for the assessment process; failure to provide such access can result in the imposition of financial penalties on the providers."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_97 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 97"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ARTICLE 97** serves as the pivotal legal provision governing the European Commission's authority to adopt delegated acts within the framework of the regulation. It establishes the procedural rules for the exercise of this power, ensuring that the Commission operates within the scope and duration specified by the regulation.

Functionally, **ARTICLE 97** provides the necessary legal basis for the Commission to update, amend, or adjust specific annexes, articles, and rules. This includes, notabl"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DELEGATED_ACT,
        euai:DELEGATED_ACTS_AMENDING_ANNEX_III,
        euai:DELEGATED_ACTS_MODIFYING_CONDITIONS .

euai:ARTIFICIAL_CONTENT_DISCLOSURE_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "ARTIFICIAL CONTENT DISCLOSURE OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for providers and deployers to enable detection and disclosure that outputs are artificially generated or manipulated"@en .

euai:AUTHORISATION_FOR_POST_REMOTE_BIOMETRIC_IDENTIFICATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "AUTHORISATION FOR POST-REMOTE BIOMETRIC IDENTIFICATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Deployers must request ex-ante authorisation (or no later than 48 hours) from a judicial or administrative authority for the use of post-remote biometric identification systems, except in specific cases of initial identification."@en .

euai:BIAS_DETECTION_AND_CORRECTION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "BIAS DETECTION AND CORRECTION"@en ;
    skos:definition """**BIAS DETECTION AND CORRECTION** refers to the critical obligation to assess, identify, and mitigate biases within datasets, particularly those utilized in high-risk artificial intelligence systems. This process is essential for ensuring fairness and preventing discriminatory outcomes in algorithmic decision-making. 

Because achieving this level of fairness often requires analyzing sensitive information, BIAS DETECTION AND CORRECTION functions as a specific, legally recognized objective that p"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_10 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DATA_BIAS_MITIGATION .

euai:BIOMETRIC_VERIFICATION_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "BIOMETRIC VERIFICATION EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **BIOMETRIC VERIFICATION EXCLUSION** refers to specific regulatory conditions under which an AI-driven biometric system is exempt from certain requirements or oversight. This exclusion applies to biometric systems whose sole and exclusive function is biometric verification—often referred to as authentication—designed to confirm that a natural person is indeed the individual they claim to be. 

Such systems are typically utilized for straightforward access control, such as logging into a devi"""@en .

euai:CERTIFIED_COMPLIANCE_SERVICES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "CERTIFIED COMPLIANCE SERVICES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Services provided by third parties to assist providers in meeting data governance obligations, including data training, validation, and testing verification."@en .

euai:CHAPTER_V__SECTIONS_2_AND_3 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "CHAPTER V, SECTIONS 2 AND 3"@en ;
    skos:definition "The specific sections of the AI Act setting out obligations for general-purpose AI models."@en .

euai:COMPLIANCE_WITH_THE_REGULATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "COMPLIANCE WITH THE REGULATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Duty imposed on providers to adhere to the Act, enforceable by penalties and fines tailored to factors such as nature, gravity, duration, and provider size"@en .

euai:CONSULTATION_PROCEDURE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CONSULTATION PROCEDURE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The process triggered when objections are raised against an authorization, requiring the Commission to consult with the relevant Member State and affected operators."@en .

euai:COOPERATION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "COOPERATION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """**COOPERATION OBLIGATION**

The "COOPERATION OBLIGATION" represents a mandatory requirement for AI system providers to collaborate with relevant stakeholders and regulatory bodies to ensure full compliance with established standards. This obligation manifests in two primary contexts within the AI regulatory framework.

First, providers of general-purpose AI systems are required to cooperate with providers of high-risk AI systems and competent authorities. This collaboration is essential to ensur"""@en .

euai:CYBERSECURITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "CYBERSECURITY"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Cybersecurity** in the context of high-risk AI systems is a critical requirement designed to ensure that these systems remain resilient against a wide array of malicious threats and unauthorized activities. It encompasses a comprehensive set of technical and operational measures aimed at safeguarding AI systems, their underlying infrastructure, and their associated data from exploitation.

At its core, **cybersecurity** mandates that high-risk AI systems must be fortified to withstand unauthor"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_76 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:REGULATION__EU__2019_881 .

euai:CYBERSECURITY_PROTECTION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "CYBERSECURITY PROTECTION"@en ;
    skos:definition """**CYBERSECURITY PROTECTION**

CYBERSECURITY PROTECTION represents a mandatory obligation to ensure an adequate and robust level of security for AI models and their supporting physical infrastructure. As stipulated by Article 55(1)(d), this duty requires that rigorous security measures be implemented to safeguard the integrity and safety of the technology.

This protection extends to the entire operational ecosystem, encompassing critical components such as the models themselves, their specific w"""@en .

euai:CYBERSECURITY_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "CYBERSECURITY REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition """A cybersecurity requirement encompasses a multifaceted set of obligations designed to ensure robust protection within the digital landscape, particularly concerning artificial intelligence (AI) systems and the regulatory bodies governing them. 

For high-risk AI systems, cybersecurity requirements are mandatory. These systems must adhere to specific security standards as outlined in Article 15 of the governing regulations. A key mechanism for demonstrating compliance involves Regulation (EU) 201"""@en .

euai:DATA_GOVERNANCE_AND_MANAGEMENT_PRACTICES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DATA GOVERNANCE AND MANAGEMENT PRACTICES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Practices covering design choices, data collection, preparation, and bias mitigation required for training, validation, and testing data sets for high-risk AI systems per Article 10"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_10 .

euai:DIRECTIVE__EU__2019_1937 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "DIRECTIVE (EU) 2019/1937"@en ;
    skos:definition """**DIRECTIVE (EU) 2019/1937** is a critical piece of legislation concerning the protection of persons who report breaches of Union law. It establishes a comprehensive framework for whistleblowing and complaint mechanisms, ensuring that individuals who report infringements are protected from retaliation.

Within the broader legal context—specifically regarding its interaction with other regulations such as the EU AI Act—DIRECTIVE (EU) 2019/1937 serves as an essential governance tool. It mandates t"""@en .

euai:EURODAC a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "EURODAC"@en ;
    skos:definition """EURODAC is a large-scale information technology system designed for the comparison of biometric data, primarily fingerprints. Established under Regulation (EU) 2024/1358, which also identifies the system as a relevant Union legislative act listed in Annex X, EURODAC serves a critical function in managing migration and security within the European Union.

The primary purpose of EURODAC is to facilitate the identification of third-country nationals and stateless persons who are staying in the EU i"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:COMPARISON_OF_BIOMETRIC_DATA,
        euai:REGULATION__EU__2024_1358 .

euai:EU_DATABASE_DATA_ENTRY_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "EU DATABASE DATA ENTRY OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Providers, authorised representatives, and public sector deployers must enter specific data (Annex VIII) into the EU database"@en .

euai:EU_DATABASE_FOR_HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEMS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "EU DATABASE FOR HIGH-RISK AI SYSTEMS"@en ;
    skos:definition "A database set up and maintained by the Commission containing information on high-risk AI systems and specific other AI systems as required by the Act"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_71 .

euai:FUNDAMENTAL_RIGHTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "FUNDAMENTAL RIGHTS"@en ;
    skos:definition """Fundamental Rights, as enshrined in the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union, serve as a critical benchmark for the regulation and governance of Artificial Intelligence (AI) systems. The primary purpose of AI-related regulation is to ensure that these technologies do not infringe upon, but rather protect, the essential liberties and protections guaranteed to individuals under the Charter.

When assessing the potential adverse impacts of AI systems, it is mandatory to consider a co"""@en .

euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODELS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "GENERAL-PURPOSE AI MODELS"@en ;
    skos:definition "**GENERAL-PURPOSE AI MODELS** are subject to specific monitoring activities conducted by the AI Office. These models may also be subject to qualified alerts, regarding which the Board is tasked with providing opinions to the Commission, in accordance with Article 66(n)."@en .

euai:HIGH_RISK_CLASSIFICATION_RULE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ClassificationRule ;
    rdfs:label "HIGH-RISK CLASSIFICATION RULE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Criteria for classifying an AI system as high-risk, including being a safety component of products subject to third-party assessment or operating in pre-defined high-risk areas"@en .

euai:IDENTITY_CHECK a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "IDENTITY CHECK"@en ;
    skos:definition """IDENTITY CHECK refers to the authorized procedural process of identifying individuals who are either unable or unwilling to provide proof of identity. This measure is preserved under both Union and national law, ensuring that specific designated authorities retain the power to verify the identities of such persons.

As a functional capability, IDENTITY CHECK is designated for use by key state actors, including law enforcement, border control, immigration, and asylum authorities. By maintaining t"""@en .

euai:IMPLEMENTING_ACT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:DelegatedAct ;
    rdfs:label "IMPLEMENTING ACT"@en ;
    skos:definition """The "IMPLEMENTING ACT" is a specific type of legal instrument adopted by the European Commission to ensure the uniform application and enforcement of regulations across member states. It serves as a versatile tool used by the Commission to address various operational and regulatory needs, ranging from administrative templates to scientific oversight and the standardization of technical rules.

In its regulatory capacity, the IMPLEMENTING ACT is utilized to establish common specifications for pro"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_56_6_ ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_98_2_,
        euai:OFFICIAL_JOURNAL_OF_THE_EUROPEAN_UNION,
        euai:SCIENTIFIC_PANEL ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:REQUIREMENTS_OF_CHAPTER_III_SECTION_2 .

euai:INTERNATIONAL_COOPERATION_EXCLUSION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ExclusionCondition ;
    rdfs:label "INTERNATIONAL COOPERATION EXCLUSION"@en ;
    skos:definition "The exclusion from the Regulation for public authorities of third countries and international organisations when acting in the framework of law enforcement or judicial cooperation agreements."@en .

euai:INVESTIGATIVE_AND_CORRECTIVE_POWERS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "INVESTIGATIVE AND CORRECTIVE POWERS"@en ;
    skos:definition """**INVESTIGATIVE AND CORRECTIVE POWERS** refer to the essential authorities and mandates granted to oversight bodies, regulators, and enforcement agencies, enabling them to effectively carry out their official duties. These powers allow authorities to access necessary personal data and specific information required to perform their prescribed tasks and functions.

In the context of law enforcement and the justice domain, these powers are critical, as they provide the legal framework for authoriti"""@en .

euai:LABELING_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "LABELING OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Specific requirement to label AI-generated or manipulated output; limited by exceptions for assistive functions, standard editing, or human-reviewed content"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:REGULATION__EU__2022_2065 .

euai:LOG_KEEPING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "LOG KEEPING"@en ;
    skos:definition """Regarding the log keeping requirements for high-risk AI systems, both providers and deployers have specific responsibilities to ensure accountability and traceability. 

Providers are mandated to retain automatically generated logs created by their high-risk AI systems, provided these systems remain under their control. This requirement is explicitly outlined under Article 16(e) and Article 19 of the relevant regulations. Furthermore, deployers are also required to maintain logs generated by the"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_19 .

euai:MANDATORY_REQUIREMENTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "MANDATORY REQUIREMENTS"@en ;
    skos:definition """**MANDATORY REQUIREMENTS** constitute a comprehensive set of obligations and standards established by the AI Act to ensure the safe and ethical deployment of artificial intelligence. These measures are designed to guide providers in ensuring compliance, with a core focus on balancing strict adherence with the state of the art and the principle of proportionality, as highlighted in Recital 64.

At their core, these requirements serve as the fundamental framework for high-risk AI systems. They enc"""@en .

euai:MARKING_OF_SYNTHETIC_CONTENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "MARKING OF SYNTHETIC CONTENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for providers to mark AI-generated outputs in a machine-readable format to ensure they are detectable as artificially generated"@en .

euai:NON_DISCRIMINATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "NON-DISCRIMINATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """In the context of artificial intelligence, Non-Discrimination is both an essential quality and a mandatory requirement designed to ensure fairness and equity. It serves as a critical safeguard to prevent AI systems from perpetuating or amplifying historical patterns of prejudice, bias, or exclusion.

To be effective, Non-Discrimination must be deeply integrated into the development and deployment of AI technologies to protect individuals against discrimination based on protected characteristics,"""@en .

euai:NON_DISCRIMINATION_REQUIREMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "NON-DISCRIMINATION REQUIREMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Non-Discrimination Requirement mandates that AI systems deployed within the domains of migration, asylum, and border control must operate without bias to ensure the protection and guarantee of fundamental human rights. This obligation necessitates proactive measures to ensure that these technologies do not perpetuate, amplify, or solidify historical patterns of discrimination. Consequently, the Non-Discrimination Requirement strictly prohibits the unfair treatment of individuals based on pro"@en .

euai:NOTIFICATION_OF_NATIONAL_RULES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "NOTIFICATION OF NATIONAL RULES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Regarding the \"NOTIFICATION OF NATIONAL RULES,\" Member States are required to notify the European Commission of any national regulations they adopt concerning the authorization and use of biometric identification systems. This mandate specifically pertains to remote biometric identification systems. Such notifications must be submitted to the Commission no later than 30 days following the formal adoption of these rules."@en .

euai:PENALTIES_FOR_PROHIBITED_PRACTICES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PENALTIES FOR PROHIBITED PRACTICES"@en ;
    skos:definition "Administrative fines for non-compliance with prohibited AI practices under Article 5. Amount: up to EUR 35,000,000 or 7% of total worldwide annual turnover, whichever is higher"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_99 .

euai:PERSONAL_DATA_PROTECTION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "PERSONAL DATA PROTECTION"@en ;
    skos:definition """**PERSONAL DATA PROTECTION** is a mandatory regulatory standard that safeguards the privacy and rights of natural persons concerning the processing of their personal information. This framework is anchored in legal requirements, most notably the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) (Regulation 2016/679), which establishes the protocols for how personal data must be handled, stored, and managed. 

Furthermore, PERSONAL DATA PROTECTION extends to modern technological landscapes, serving as a """@en .

euai:PROHIBITION_OF_EMOTION_RECOGNITION_AI a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROHIBITION OF EMOTION RECOGNITION AI"@en ;
    skos:definition "Prohibition on the placing on the market, putting into service, or use of AI systems intended to detect emotional states in workplace and education contexts (Recital 44)"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_44 .

euai:REGISTRATION_OF_TESTING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REGISTRATION OF TESTING"@en ;
    skos:definition """**REGISTRATION OF TESTING**

Under Article 60 of the relevant regulations, the "REGISTRATION OF TESTING" framework mandates that entities conducting testing for AI systems in real-world conditions must fulfill a specific duty to register and disclose comprehensive information. This registration process is required to ensure transparency and oversight during real-world trials.

To comply with this mandate, the entity must provide five key categories of information:

1.  **Identification:** Unique"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_60 .

euai:REGULATION_ON_HORIZONTAL_CYBERSECURITY_REQUIREMENTS_FOR_PRODUCTS_WITH_DIGITAL_ELEMENTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION ON HORIZONTAL CYBERSECURITY REQUIREMENTS FOR PRODUCTS WITH DIGITAL ELEMENTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "A legislative framework that defines essential cybersecurity requirements for products with digital elements, which high-risk AI systems may leverage for compliance."@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2016_679 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2016/679"@en ;
    skos:definition """Regulation (EU) 2016/679, widely known as the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), serves as a fundamental framework for data protection and privacy within the European Union. Its provisions impose strict limitations on the processing of personal data, ensuring that such activities are conducted lawfully, fairly, and transparently.

In addition to these general processing limits, Regulation (EU) 2016/679 establishes mandatory compliance requirements for specific technological applications."""@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2019_881 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2019/881"@en ;
    skos:definition """Regulation (EU) 2019/881, widely known as the Cybersecurity Act, is a pivotal piece of European Union legislation that addresses the safety and resilience of digital infrastructure. Its primary function is to establish a comprehensive framework for the cybersecurity certification of information and communications technology (ICT) products, services, and processes.

Central to this regulation is the formal establishment and reinforcement of ENISA, the European Union Agency for Cybersecurity. Regu"""@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2022_2065 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2022/2065"@en ;
    skos:definition """**REGULATION (EU) 2022/2065**, formally known as the **Regulation on a Single Market for Digital Services** and commonly referred to as the **Digital Services Act (DSA)**, serves as a pivotal piece of legislation governing the digital ecosystem within the European Union.

This regulation establishes a comprehensive framework for online platforms and search engines, focusing on their responsibilities regarding content moderation and the mitigation of systemic risks. Specifically, it provides crit"""@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:VERY_LARGE_ONLINE_PLATFORMS ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:PROVIDER .

euai:REGULATION__EU__NO_575_2013 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) NO 575/2013"@en ;
    skos:definition "Regulation (EU) No 575/2013 is a piece of legislation that establishes prudential requirements for credit institutions and investment firms. This regulation is explicitly referenced in Recital 46 of relevant financial services legislation, particularly in the context of the scope of artificial intelligence (AI) applications within the financial sector. By setting these foundational prudential standards, the regulation plays a critical role in framing the operational and regulatory environment fo"@en .

euai:REQUIREMENTS_OF_SECTION_2 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "REQUIREMENTS OF SECTION 2"@en ;
    skos:definition "The \"REQUIREMENTS OF SECTION 2\" constitute the essential criteria that high-risk AI systems must satisfy to achieve and maintain their regulatory compliance and certification status under the AI Act. Specifically, these mandates, which are referenced in Article 47(2), encompass a comprehensive framework of both technical and organizational requirements. By adhering to these standards, AI systems ensure they are operating within the established legal and safety parameters required by the legislat"@en .

euai:RISK_MANAGEMENT_FRAMEWORK a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RISK MANAGEMENT FRAMEWORK"@en ;
    skos:definition "A framework provided by Regulation (EU) 2022/2065 for managing risks associated with very large online platforms and search engines"@en .

euai:ROBUSTNESS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "ROBUSTNESS"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Robustness**, in the context of artificial intelligence, refers to a critical technical requirement for AI systems to maintain stable, reliable, and consistent performance under varying conditions, adverse circumstances, and unforeseen situations. Specifically, for high-risk AI systems, robustness is a fundamental prerequisite for regulatory compliance.

This characteristic demands that systems remain resilient against errors, faults, inconsistencies, and harmful or undesirable behaviors. To a"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_75 .

euai:SECTION_2 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "SECTION 2"@en ;
    skos:definition "Refers to the section of the AI Act containing requirements that high-risk AI systems must meet"@en .

euai:SECTION_2_OF_CHAPTER_II a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "SECTION 2 OF CHAPTER II"@en ;
    skos:definition "The specific section of the AI Act setting out requirements for high-risk AI systems."@en .

euai:SIMPLIFIED_TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION_FORM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "SIMPLIFIED TECHNICAL DOCUMENTATION FORM"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Simplified Technical Documentation Form is a specific template established by the Commission for use by small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs). This form is designed to facilitate the provision of technical documentation in a simplified format, as permitted under Article 11(1). By utilizing this standardized template, SMEs can streamline the process of submitting the necessary technical information required for regulatory compliance."@en .

euai:SINGLE_INFORMATION_PLATFORM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "SINGLE INFORMATION PLATFORM"@en ;
    skos:definition """The Single Information Platform is a digital tool developed and maintained by the AI Office to serve as a comprehensive resource for operators, providers, and deployers under the AI Act. Its primary purpose is to offer accessible, easy-to-use information regarding the Regulation.

Additionally, the Single Information Platform functions as a mechanism for transparency regarding sandbox projects. Under the provisions of the Article, it serves as a designated space where exit reports from these pro"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:PROVIDER .

euai:STANDARDISED_TEMPLATES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "STANDARDISED TEMPLATES"@en ;
    skos:definition "STANDARDISED TEMPLATES are essential documentation aids designed to streamline regulatory adherence. These documents are provided by the Commission with the specific objective of addressing the unique needs of small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs), thereby facilitating their compliance efforts. Furthermore, these templates are furnished by the AI Office, in accordance with specifications set forth by the Board, to assist organizations in meeting the compliance requirements mandated under Art"@en .

euai:TECHNICAL_AND_ORGANISATIONAL_MEASURES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TECHNICAL AND ORGANISATIONAL MEASURES"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Technical and organisational measures** represent a crucial framework of strategies, procedures, and design requirements that operators and Union institutions must implement to mitigate risks, ensure the safety and compliance of systems, and protect personal data. 

In the context of data privacy, **technical and organisational measures** are essential for safeguarding personal data processed within environments such as sandboxes. These measures must ensure that data remains protected througho"""@en .

euai:TECHNICAL_SOLUTIONS_FOR_MARKING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TECHNICAL SOLUTIONS FOR MARKING"@en ;
    skos:definition "Mandatory methods such as watermarks, metadata identifications, cryptographic methods, or logging methods to identify AI-generated or manipulated content."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CONTENT_GENERATION_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:TRAINING_DATA_SUMMARY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "TRAINING DATA SUMMARY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Requirement for providers to draw up and make publicly available a sufficiently detailed summary of the content used for training a general-purpose AI model"@en .

euai:UNION_SAFEGUARD_PROCEDURE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "UNION SAFEGUARD PROCEDURE"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Union Safeguard Procedure is a formal regulatory mechanism defined under Article 81 of the relevant legislation. Within this framework, the European Commission is tasked with evaluating specific national measures implemented by market surveillance authorities in response to concerns regarding AI systems. This procedure serves as a structured oversight process, ensuring that actions taken against AI systems at a national level are subject to central review and assessment by the Commission."@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_81 .

euai:ANNEX_IV a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ANNEX IV"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ANNEX IV**

ANNEX IV serves as a critical regulatory component, defining the mandatory requirements for the technical documentation associated with AI systems. It functions as a foundational reference document that specifies the minimum elements that must be included in this documentation to ensure compliance and transparency.

The scope of ANNEX IV is referenced across various provisions of the regulatory framework. Specifically, it is explicitly cited in Article 11(1) regarding general techn"""@en .

euai:ANNEX_VII a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ANNEX VII"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ANNEX VII**

ANNEX VII outlines the conformity assessment procedure utilized to verify that products meet regulatory standards. Specifically, ANNEX VII describes a process that centers on the thorough assessment of both the manufacturer's quality management system and the associated technical documentation. This procedure is a critical regulatory step, requiring oversight and evaluation by a notified body to ensure full compliance. Furthermore, ANNEX VII details the specific requirements for o"""@en ;
    euai:belongsToCategory euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT_PROCEDURE .

euai:ANNEX_XII a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ANNEX XII"@en ;
    skos:definition "**ANNEX XII** outlines the specific transparency requirements regarding information and documentation that must be provided by providers of general-purpose AI models to downstream AI system providers. This annex serves to ensure that those developing systems further down the AI value chain have access to the necessary data to operate, integrate, and manage these models effectively. Specifically, it details the transparency obligations referenced in Article 53(1)(b) of the applicable regulations,"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_11 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 11"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Article 11** serves two distinct functions within the regulatory landscape, depending on the specific legislative context in which it is cited.

First, within the framework of the **EU AI Act**, **Article 11** establishes the mandatory requirements for the technical documentation of high-risk AI systems. It serves as the primary provision ensuring that creators and operators of such systems generate and maintain comprehensive documentation. This documentation is essential for demonstrating com"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:IMPLEMENTING_ACTS,
        euai:REQUIREMENTS_IN_CHAPTER_III_SECTION_2 .

euai:ARTICLE_14 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 14"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ARTICLE 14** serves as the primary legal provision governing the mandate for human oversight of high-risk AI systems. It establishes the critical framework for ensuring that such technologies remain subject to meaningful human control, thereby defining both the overarching requirements and the specific implementation measures necessary for compliance.

As the regulation governing human oversight, **ARTICLE 14** mandates that high-risk AI systems must be designed and developed in such a way tha"""@en .

euai:ARTICLE_16 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 16"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 16 serves as the section of the regulation that defines and specifies the obligations of providers of high-risk AI systems. It outlines the fundamental duties, general requirements, and specific responsibilities that these providers must adhere to in the context of high-risk AI system deployment."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:PENALTIES_FOR_GENERAL_NON_COMPLIANCE ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:PROVIDER .

euai:ARTICLE_19 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 19"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ARTICLE 19**

ARTICLE 19, within the context of the AI Act, serves as a provision with distinct functional responsibilities concerning the regulation of artificial intelligence systems.

Primarily, ARTICLE 19 acts as an amendment to an existing regulation. As amended, it mandates that when the European Commission adopts delegated acts concerning AI systems classified as safety components, it must explicitly take into account the requirements outlined in Chapter III, Section 2 of the AI Act. Th"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DELEGATED_ACTS,
        euai:REQUIREMENTS_IN_CHAPTER_III_SECTION_2 .

euai:ARTICLE_49 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 49"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 49 serves as a key regulatory provision concerning the administrative management of artificial intelligence technologies within the European Union. Specifically, it establishes and outlines the registration obligations for high-risk AI systems. This article functions as the primary legal mandate governing the mandatory registration of these systems in the centralized EU database, thereby defining the specific requirements that must be met to ensure compliance and transparency for high-ri"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_54 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 54"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ARTICLE 54**

ARTICLE 54 serves as a critical component of the regulatory framework for artificial intelligence, specifically establishing the core obligations for providers of general-purpose AI (GPAI) models. This article defines the responsibilities that these providers must adhere to, ensuring accountability and oversight in the development and deployment of such technologies.

Furthermore, ARTICLE 54 explicitly governs the role and mandate of authorised representatives for GPAI models. Th"""@en .

euai:ARTICLE_72 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 72"@en ;
    skos:definition """Article 72 serves as a critical regulatory provision within the legal framework governing artificial intelligence, specifically focusing on the post-market monitoring of AI systems. Its primary objective is to establish comprehensive requirements for the post-market monitoring systems that providers of high-risk AI systems must implement.

By formalizing these requirements, Article 72 functions as the legal basis for ensuring ongoing oversight and accountability after an AI system has been deplo"""@en .

euai:ARTICLE_92_EVALUATIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 92 EVALUATIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Evaluations conducted by the Commission or independent experts on GPAI models to assess compliance or investigate systemic risks"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_68,
        euai:ARTICLE_90_1__A_,
        euai:ARTICLE_91 .

euai:ARTICLE_96 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 96"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 96 serves as the governing provision regarding the development and implementation of guidelines by the Commission. Specifically, it establishes the legal framework that authorizes the Commission to create guidelines necessary for the proper implementation of the Regulation. Furthermore, Article 96 provides the procedural basis for the implementation of specific guidance concerning Article 6, acting as the primary reference article for these related regulatory requirements."@en .

euai:BIOMETRIC_DATA a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "BIOMETRIC DATA"@en ;
    skos:definition "Biometric data refers to personal information that is derived from the specific technical processing of a natural person's physical, physiological, or behavioural characteristics, such as facial images. This classification of data is officially defined and governed by Regulation (EU) 2016/679, Regulation (EU) 2018/1725, and Directive (EU) 2016/680. As outlined in Recital 14 of these legal frameworks, biometric data is utilized for the purposes of authentication, identification, categorisation, o"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_14 .

euai:BOARD a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "BOARD"@en ;
    skos:definition """The European Artificial Intelligence Board is a key regulatory entity designed to support the implementation and oversight of artificial intelligence governance. Its responsibilities are multifaceted, serving as a pivotal link between the European Commission, national competent authorities, and the AI Office.

The European Artificial Intelligence Board plays a crucial advisory role, particularly regarding the European Commission. The Commission is required to consult the Board when preparing sta"""@en ;
    euai:cooperatesWith euai:EVALUATION_AND_REVIEW_REPORT ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CODE_OF_PRACTICE,
        euai:COMMISSION,
        euai:STANDARDISED_TEMPLATES .

euai:COMPLAINT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Complaint ;
    rdfs:label "COMPLAINT"@en ;
    skos:definition """A **COMPLAINT** acts as a formal procedural instrument used to report alleged infringements of the AI Act. This mechanism is utilized by natural or legal persons, including downstream providers and other relevant stakeholders, to seek recourse or initiate oversight regarding regulatory violations.

The **COMPLAINT** functions through two primary channels depending on the nature of the alleged infringement:

1.  **General Infringements:** Any natural or legal person with sufficient grounds may su"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_85,
        euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY,
        euai:PROVIDER_OF_GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL .

euai:COMPLIANCE_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "COMPLIANCE OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """**COMPLIANCE OBLIGATION**

The Compliance Obligation for AI systems entails a multi-faceted duty imposed on providers to ensure their technologies adhere to the requirements set forth by the Regulation and relevant Union harmonisation legislation. This obligation is designed to maintain consistency across the regulatory landscape while simultaneously avoiding the imposition of unnecessary administrative burdens on developers and operators.

Central to this mandate is the requirement that provide"""@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:AI_SYSTEM .

euai:COMPLIANCE_WITH_THIS_REGULATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "COMPLIANCE WITH THIS REGULATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "**COMPLIANCE WITH THIS REGULATION** represents the overarching obligation imposed on AI operators—including providers and deployers—to strictly adhere to the requirements set forth by the AI Act. This mandatory duty ensures that any given AI system fully meets all regulatory standards whenever the system is utilized for non-excluded purposes. Furthermore, this obligation is triggered when research activities evolve and result in the placement of an AI system on the market. To assist operators in"@en .

euai:CORRECTIVE_ACTION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CORRECTIVE ACTION"@en ;
    skos:definition """**CORRECTIVE ACTION** refers to the mandatory steps that operators, including providers and distributors, must undertake to ensure that an AI system aligns with regulatory requirements. When an AI system is identified as non-compliant, or when it poses risks to health, safety, or fundamental rights, the responsible entity is obligated to take immediate measures to rectify the situation.

These actions involve bringing the system into conformity, restricting its availability, withdrawing it from """@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY .

euai:COUNCIL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "COUNCIL"@en ;
    skos:definition """The Council is an EU legislative body that plays a crucial role in the oversight, evaluation, and regulatory implementation of European Union law, including the AI Act. Functioning as a central point for administrative review, the Council receives various critical documents from the Commission, including enforcement assessment reports, as well as comprehensive reports concerning the evaluation and review of the AI Act and other regulations.

Beyond its role as a recipient of these reports, the C"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DELEGATED_ACT .

euai:DATA_GOVERNANCE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "DATA GOVERNANCE"@en ;
    skos:definition """Data Governance, within the context of high-risk AI systems as specified by relevant legislation, encompasses a comprehensive set of practices and methodologies designed to ensure the integrity and quality of data throughout the AI lifecycle. It functions as a critical requirement for managing data sets, specifically regarding their use in training, validation, and testing practices.

At its core, Data Governance involves the implementation of rigorous methodologies for data cleaning and managem"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_67 .

euai:DIRECTIVE__EU__2016_680 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "DIRECTIVE (EU) 2016/680"@en ;
    skos:definition "**Directive (EU) 2016/680**, often referred to as the Law Enforcement Directive (LED), is a critical legal instrument of the European Parliament and of the Council established to govern the protection of natural persons regarding the processing of personal data. Specifically, it concerns the processing of such data by competent authorities for the purposes of the prevention, investigation, detection, or prosecution of criminal offences, or the execution of criminal penalties, including the safeg"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:INVESTIGATIVE_AND_CORRECTIVE_POWERS .

euai:DOCUMENTATION_KEEPING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "DOCUMENTATION KEEPING"@en ;
    skos:definition "Under the framework of \"DOCUMENTATION KEEPING,\" providers are subject to specific obligations regarding the retention of essential records as stipulated in Article 18. This requirement mandates that providers maintain comprehensive technical documentation, as well as quality management records and conformity declarations. These materials must be kept at the disposal of relevant authorities for a period of 10 years following the product's placement on the market to ensure ongoing regulatory compl"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_18 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:NATIONAL_COMPETENT_AUTHORITY .

euai:EUROPEAN_PARLIAMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition """The European Parliament is a central legislative body within the European Union that serves as one of the co-legislating institutions responsible for the adoption of Regulation (EU) 2024/1689 (the AI Act). 

Beyond its legislative function, the European Parliament plays a critical role in oversight and governance. It is the institution empowered to revoke delegated acts, oppose extensions of delegation, or object to specific delegated acts, ensuring democratic control over regulatory implementat"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:DELEGATED_ACT,
        euai:REGULATION__EU__2024_1689 .

euai:HARMONISED_STANDARD a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "HARMONISED STANDARD"@en ;
    skos:definition """A Harmonised Standard is a technical standard, as defined in Article 2(1)(c) of Regulation (EU) No 1025/2012, that serves as a critical mechanism for ensuring compliance with regulatory obligations. These standards are developed by recognized European standardisation organisations and are intended to provide concrete technical solutions that facilitate adherence to the requirements set forth by the AI Act.

When a Harmonised Standard is referenced in the Official Journal of the European Union, i"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_2 ;
    euai:grants euai:PRESUMPTION_OF_CONFORMITY ;
    euai:presumesConformity euai:PROVIDER_OF_GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODELS ;
    euai:regulatedBy euai:COMMON_SPECIFICATION ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_10_1__REGULATION__EU__NO_1025_2012 .

euai:IMPORTER a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "IMPORTER"@en ;
    skos:definition """An **IMPORTER** is defined as any natural or legal person established or located within the European Union that introduces AI systems from a third country (a country outside the Union) onto the Union market.

In the context of the AI regulatory framework, an **IMPORTER** fulfills a crucial role in the value chain by bridging the gap between foreign providers and the Union market. Specifically, the designation applies to entities that perform one of the following actions:

*   Placing a high-risk"""@en ;
    euai:cooperatesWith euai:COMPETENT_AUTHORITY ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_2,
        euai:ARTICLE_3 ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:IMPORTER_OBLIGATION__DOCUMENTATION_AND_RECORDS,
        euai:IMPORTER_OBLIGATION__IDENTIFICATION_LABELING,
        euai:IMPORTER_OBLIGATION__INFORMATION_PROVISION,
        euai:IMPORTER_OBLIGATION__STORAGE_AND_TRANSPORT,
        euai:IMPORTER_OBLIGATION__VERIFICATION_AND_NON_CONFORMITY_REPORTING ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_IV,
        euai:ARTICLE_11,
        euai:ARTICLE_22_1_,
        euai:ARTICLE_43,
        euai:ARTICLE_47,
        euai:CE_MARKING,
        euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT_PROCEDURE,
        euai:EU_DECLARATION_OF_CONFORMITY,
        euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:INSTRUCTIONS_FOR_USE,
        euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY,
        euai:PROVIDER,
        euai:TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:PROVIDER_CLASSIFICATION_RULE .

euai:INFORMATION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "INFORMATION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The "INFORMATION OBLIGATION" encompasses specific transparency requirements aimed at both providers and deployers of regulated systems to ensure clarity and accountability.

For providers, the obligation mandates the clear disclosure of their identity. Specifically, providers are required to prominently indicate their name, their registered trade name or trademark, and a valid contact address. This information must be made available directly on the system itself, on its packaging, or within the """@en .

euai:INFORMED_CONSENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "INFORMED CONSENT"@en ;
    skos:definition """Informed Consent is a critical regulatory requirement mandated for individuals participating in real-world testing. Defined under Article 3(59) as a subject's voluntary and unambiguous expression of willingness to participate, Informed Consent ensures that subjects are fully aware of all relevant aspects before agreeing to take part.

Prospective providers are obligated to obtain this consent from natural persons prior to their participation in testing under real-world conditions. This process m"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_61 .

euai:INSTRUCTIONS_FOR_USE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "INSTRUCTIONS FOR USE"@en ;
    skos:definition """"INSTRUCTIONS FOR USE" constitute mandatory documentation that must accompany high-risk AI systems when they are placed on the market. Provided by the system's provider to the deployer, these instructions serve as a critical bridge of information, ensuring the deployer understands how to operate the technology safely and effectively.

The documentation, which can be delivered in digital or other formats, encompasses a comprehensive range of details regarding the AI system. This includes the syst"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_15,
        euai:ARTICLE_9_2_,
        euai:RECITAL_73 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DEPLOYER,
        euai:PERFORMANCE_CHARACTERISTICS .

euai:MANIPULATIVE_OR_DECEPTIVE_AI_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "MANIPULATIVE OR DECEPTIVE AI SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "AI systems that deploy subliminal components or other manipulative/deceptive techniques to distort human behaviour, impair autonomy, or exploit vulnerabilities, causing significant harm. Prohibited under the Act."@en ;
    euai:regulatedBy euai:PROHIBITION_OF_MANIPULATIVE_AI_PRACTICES ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:SIGNIFICANT_HARM,
        euai:UNACCEPTABLE_RISK ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:PROHIBITED_AI_PRACTICE .

euai:MODEL_EVALUATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "MODEL EVALUATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Model Evaluation** refers to a critical and mandatory requirement for providers of General Purpose AI (GPAI) models that pose systemic risks. Under Article 55 of the relevant regulatory framework, these providers are legally obligated to conduct thorough assessments of their models prior to making them available on the market.

The primary purpose of this Model Evaluation process is to proactively identify, assess, and mitigate systemic risks associated with the AI technology. To ensure consis"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_55 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ADVERSARIAL_TESTING .

euai:NEW_LEGISLATIVE_FRAMEWORK a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "NEW LEGISLATIVE FRAMEWORK"@en ;
    skos:definition """The "New Legislative Framework" is a comprehensive regulatory structure designed to oversee Union harmonisation legislation. It serves as the foundational legal architecture upon which existing conformity assessments for various products are conducted, ensuring consistent safety standards across the Union. 

This framework encompasses several key legislative instruments, specifically including Regulation (EC) No 765/2008, Decision No 768/2008/EC, and Regulation (EU) 2019/1020. By aligning its pr"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:OPERATOR_OBLIGATIONS .

euai:NOTIFYING_AUTHORITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "NOTIFYING AUTHORITY"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **Notifying Authority** is a designated national competent authority established by each European Union Member State, playing a critical role in the oversight of conformity assessment procedures under the AI Act. Specifically mandated by Article 70(1) and Article 28 of the Regulation, the **Notifying Authority** is responsible for the assessment, designation, notification, and continuous monitoring of conformity assessment bodies, often referred to as "notified bodies."

To ensure the integr"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_30 ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:COMPETENT_PERSONNEL_REQUIREMENT,
        euai:DOCUMENTATION_PRESERVATION_OBLIGATION,
        euai:INVESTIGATION_OBLIGATION ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:APPLICATION_FOR_NOTIFICATION,
        euai:ARTICLE_28,
        euai:COMMISSION,
        euai:COMPETENCE_EVIDENCE,
        euai:COMPETENT_PERSONS,
        euai:CONFIDENTIALITY_REQUIREMENT,
        euai:CONFLICT_OF_INTEREST_PREVENTION,
        euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT_BODY,
        euai:DESIGNATION_MANAGEMENT_OBLIGATION,
        euai:ELECTRONIC_NOTIFICATION_TOOL,
        euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY,
        euai:MEMBER_STATES,
        euai:NATIONAL_ACCREDITATION_BODY,
        euai:NATIONAL_COMPETENT_AUTHORITY,
        euai:NOTIFIED_BODY,
        euai:SEGREGATION_OF_DUTIES ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:PROHIBITION_OF_CONSULTANCY .

euai:PENALTIES_FOR_MISLEADING_INFORMATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PENALTIES FOR MISLEADING INFORMATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "Administrative fines for supplying incorrect, incomplete, or misleading information to notified bodies or national competent authorities. Amount: up to EUR 7,500,000 or 1% of total worldwide annual turnover, whichever is higher"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_99 .

euai:POST_MARKET_MONITORING_PLAN a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "POST-MARKET MONITORING PLAN"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Post-Market Monitoring Plan is a critical component of the technical documentation, specifically outlined in Annex IV, which serves as the foundational framework for an AI system’s post-market monitoring system. As mandated by Article 72 and Article 72(3) of the relevant regulations, this plan is designed to continuously evaluate the performance of an AI system once it has been placed on the market. By establishing this systematic approach, the Post-Market Monitoring Plan ensures ongoing ove"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_72,
        euai:TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION .

euai:PROHIBITION_OF_AI_PRACTICES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROHIBITION OF AI PRACTICES"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Prohibition of AI Practices encompasses a critical regulatory framework designed to safeguard individuals and society from harmful artificial intelligence technologies. At its core, this framework establishes an overarching requirement to ban specific AI systems deemed to violate human rights, undermine dignity, or pose excessive risks to fundamental freedoms, as detailed in Recitals 30, 31, and 33. To enforce these protections, Article 5 explicitly outlines a set of specific prohibitions re"@en .

euai:PROVIDER_CLASSIFICATION_RULE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:ClassificationRule ;
    rdfs:label "PROVIDER CLASSIFICATION RULE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Rule stating that distributors, importers, or deployers become providers if they put their name on a system, make substantial modifications, or change the intended purpose of an AI system to become high-risk."@en .

euai:ProhibitedAIPractice a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Prohibited AI Practice"@en ;
    rdfs:subClassOf euai:AISystem ;
    skos:definition "An AI practice that is banned under Article 5 due to unacceptable risk."@en .

euai:REAL_WORLD_TESTING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REAL-WORLD TESTING"@en ;
    skos:definition "The process of testing AI systems in real-world conditions, subject to specific guarantees, consent requirements, and registration obligations"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:REGULATION__EU__2016_679 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:COMPETENT_MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY,
        euai:DATA_TRANSFER_SAFEGUARDS,
        euai:EFFECTIVE_OVERSIGHT,
        euai:EU_DATABASE,
        euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY,
        euai:REAL_WORLD_TESTING_PLAN,
        euai:WRITTEN_AGREEMENT .

euai:REGISTRATION_IN_EU_DATABASE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REGISTRATION IN EU DATABASE"@en ;
    skos:definition """The registration process within the EU database involves specific obligations for different stakeholders regarding AI systems.

Regarding providers of AI systems, there is a duty to register a system in the EU database if the provider has formally determined that the system is non-high-risk based on established exclusion conditions.

Additionally, the EU database serves as a platform for public authority deployers. Under Article 71, these deployers are required to register themselves, select the"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_71 .

euai:REGULATION__EC__NO_765_2008 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EC) NO 765/2008"@en ;
    skos:definition "**REGULATION (EC) NO 765/2008** serves as a foundational component of the European Union’s New Legislative Framework. It is the primary regulation that establishes the general principles and requirements for CE marking, which signifies that a product conforms to EU health, safety, and environmental protection standards. Furthermore, REGULATION (EC) NO 765/2008 provides essential rules to ensure consistency regarding the placing of products on the market, including those categorized as high-risk "@en .

euai:SERIOUS_INCIDENT_REPORTING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "SERIOUS INCIDENT REPORTING"@en ;
    skos:definition """**SERIOUS INCIDENT REPORTING**

Serious incident reporting within the context of high-risk AI systems is a mandatory regulatory requirement designed to ensure transparency, accountability, and public safety. This process encompasses specific obligations for various stakeholders, including providers, deployers, importers, and distributors.

Under these regulations, duty holders are required to diligently track, document, and report any serious incidents to the appropriate bodies. Specifically, in"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_OFFICE .

euai:STANDARDISATION_REQUEST a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "STANDARDISATION REQUEST"@en ;
    skos:definition """A **STANDARDISATION REQUEST** is a formal instrument issued by the European Commission to European standardisation organisations. Its primary purpose is to mandate and guide the development of harmonised standards that address specific requirements or obligations set forth under the AI Act.

Under the regulatory framework of the AI Act, specifically Article 40(2), it is the official duty of the Commission to issue such requests to ensure that standards are developed to cover the requirements out"""@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:EUROPEAN_STANDARDISATION_ORGANISATION ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_10_OF_REGULATION__EU__NO_1025_2012,
        euai:REGULATION__EU__NO_1025_2012 .

euai:TRANSPARENCY_RELATED_REQUIREMENTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "TRANSPARENCY-RELATED REQUIREMENTS"@en ;
    skos:definition """**TRANSPARENCY-RELATED REQUIREMENTS**

The transparency-related requirements for general-purpose AI (GPAI) models encompass a set of obligations designed to ensure accountability and regulatory compliance. Providers of GPAI models are mandated to adhere to specific documentation and information-provision standards. Central to these transparency obligations is the requirement for providers to generate and publish a comprehensive summary of the content used for training their models. Furthermore, """@en .

euai:WRITTEN_AGREEMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "WRITTEN AGREEMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "A Written Agreement is a mandatory formal contract established between a provider and a third party within the AI value chain. This agreement functions as a critical requirement, ensuring that all relevant parties involved in the AI value chain are obligated to furnish the provider with necessary technical assistance and information access. By formalizing these obligations, the Written Agreement ensures seamless cooperation and the provision of essential resources required for the effective func"@en .

euai:ACCURACY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "ACCURACY"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ACCURACY** is a critical technical requirement for artificial intelligence systems, particularly those classified as high-risk. It refers to the fundamental capability of an AI system to produce correct, reliable, and consistent outputs throughout its entire lifecycle while actively minimizing errors and bias. 

As a prerequisite for regulatory compliance, **ACCURACY** is not merely a technical performance metric but an essential quality for ensuring that high-risk AI systems function reliably"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_74 .

euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOXES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "AI REGULATORY SANDBOXES"@en ;
    skos:definition """AI Regulatory Sandboxes serve as controlled environments specifically designed for the development, testing, and validation of artificial intelligence (AI) systems. These frameworks provide a secure, regulated space where innovation can be assessed before products are formally placed on the market, including research activities that may lead to commercial deployment.

To foster innovation, AI Regulatory Sandboxes prioritize accessibility for small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) and start-up"""@en .

euai:ARTICLE_30 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 30"@en ;
    skos:definition "ARTICLE 30 outlines the specific procedures for the notification of conformity assessment bodies, as well as the mandate and usage of electronic notification tools. This article serves to detail the regulatory framework for notifying authorities regarding their process for designating these bodies, ensuring transparency and clarity in the notification mechanism. Additionally, it establishes the requirements and functionalities for the electronic tools used to facilitate these notifications, ensu"@en .

euai:ARTICLE_31 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 31"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Article 31** serves as a critical regulatory provision establishing the comprehensive requirements that must be met by conformity assessment bodies to achieve the status of a "notified body." Under this article, these entities are subjected to rigorous standards to ensure they are qualified, impartial, and capable of performing their designated oversight functions.

Specifically, Article 31 outlines the operational and organizational obligations necessary for a body to be authorized to control"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:PENALTIES_FOR_GENERAL_NON_COMPLIANCE .

euai:ARTICLE_53 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 53"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ARTICLE 53** serves as a foundational provision regarding the regulatory requirements for providers of general-purpose AI (GPAI) models. It establishes a comprehensive framework of obligations aimed at ensuring accountability and clarity in the development and deployment of these technologies.

Specifically, **ARTICLE 53** mandates rigorous transparency obligations for providers of general-purpose AI models. These requirements are designed to ensure that downstream providers and other relevant"""@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:PROVIDER_OF_GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODELS ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_XII .

euai:ARTICLE_55 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 55"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 55 establishes the regulatory framework and specific requirements for providers of general-purpose AI (GPAI) models that are classified as presenting systemic risks. This article outlines the obligations these providers must adhere to, ensuring that models with significant impact or potential for systemic disruption are managed responsibly and safely within the regulatory landscape."@en .

euai:ARTICLE_57 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 57"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Article 57** of the AI Act serves as a key provision within the regulation, primarily governing the establishment and operation of AI regulatory sandboxes. Its function is to define the frameworks under which these controlled environments operate, ensuring that the Board can effectively harmonize practices related to the sandboxes.

The scope and application of Article 57 are multi-faceted. In addition to its primary role concerning regulatory sandboxes, the article includes specific mandates """@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:IMPLEMENTING_ACTS,
        euai:REQUIREMENTS_IN_CHAPTER_III_SECTION_2 .

euai:ARTICLE_73 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 73"@en ;
    skos:definition """Article 73 establishes the regulatory framework and specific requirements for the reporting of serious incidents involving high-risk AI systems. It defines the necessary procedures that must be followed when such incidents occur, ensuring a systematic approach to incident management.

Crucially, Article 73 governs the specific obligations of deployers in situations where they are unable to establish contact with the provider of a high-risk AI system. In addition to outlining these reporting mand"""@en .

euai:AUTHORISED_REPRESENTATIVE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "AUTHORISED REPRESENTATIVE"@en ;
    skos:definition "An **Authorised Representative** is defined as any natural or legal person established within the European Union who has received and accepted a formal, written mandate from an AI system provider. This role is primarily essential for providers who are based in a third country (i.e., outside the Union) and wish to place AI systems or general-purpose AI models on the market or put them into service within the Union. By acting on behalf of the provider, the Authorised Representative ensures that th"@en ;
    euai:cooperatesWith euai:AI_OFFICE,
        euai:COMPETENT_AUTHORITY,
        euai:NATIONAL_COMPETENT_AUTHORITY ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_2,
        euai:ARTICLE_3,
        euai:ARTICLE_54 ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:REGISTRATION_OBLIGATIONS,
        euai:TERMINATE_MANDATE ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_11,
        euai:ARTICLE_12_1_,
        euai:ARTICLE_47,
        euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT_PROCEDURE,
        euai:DOCUMENTATION_KEEPING,
        euai:EU_DATABASE_DATA_ENTRY_OBLIGATION,
        euai:EU_DECLARATION_OF_CONFORMITY,
        euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:MANDATE,
        euai:MANDATE_OF_AUTHORISED_REPRESENTATIVE,
        euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY,
        euai:NOTIFIED_BODY,
        euai:PROVIDER,
        euai:QUALITY_MANAGEMENT_SYSTEM,
        euai:REGISTRATION,
        euai:TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION,
        euai:WRITTEN_MANDATE .

euai:CONFIDENTIALITY_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CONFIDENTIALITY OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """**CONFIDENTIALITY OBLIGATION**

The Confidentiality Obligation serves as a critical regulatory requirement mandated for national competent authorities, notified bodies, and experts. This obligation dictates that all parties involved in the execution of their professional tasks must maintain strict confidentiality regarding the information and data obtained during their work.

This duty is primarily anchored to the standards set forth in Article 78, which governs the handling and protection of se"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_78 .

euai:CRITICAL_INFRASTRUCTURE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AnnexIIICategory ;
    rdfs:label "CRITICAL INFRASTRUCTURE"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Critical Infrastructure** refers to systems, assets, or domains whose disruption or failure would pose an imminent threat to life or physical safety. Due to the significant risks associated with their operation, they are frequently categorized as a high-risk domain for the deployment of artificial intelligence (AI) systems.

The scope of critical infrastructure encompasses vital societal functions, specifically those related to the safety components in the management and operation of critical """@en ;
    euai:isBasedOn euai:ARTICLE_2 .

euai:DELEGATED_ACTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:DelegatedAct ;
    rdfs:label "DELEGATED ACTS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Delegated Acts refer to specific legislative instruments adopted by the European Commission within the framework of the AI Act. These acts serve two critical functions regarding the regulation of artificial intelligence. First, they provide the Commission with the authority to amend and update the classification conditions for high-risk AI systems, specifically those outlined in Article 6(3) of the AI Act. This ensures that the categorization of high-risk systems remains current and adaptable to"@en ;
    euai:modifies euai:ARTICLE_6 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:REQUIREMENTS_IN_CHAPTER_III_SECTION_2 .

euai:DISTRIBUTOR a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "DISTRIBUTOR"@en ;
    skos:definition """A **Distributor** is defined as any natural or legal person operating within the supply chain who makes an AI system available on the Union market. Crucially, this definition excludes the provider or the importer of the AI system.

While some descriptions suggest the exclusion of the deployer, the prevailing consensus within the provided regulatory context—specifically referencing Article 3(7) and Article 2(1)(d)—establishes that a Distributor is distinct from the provider and the importer. As a"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_2,
        euai:ARTICLE_25,
        euai:ARTICLE_3 ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:DISTRIBUTOR_OBLIGATION__STORAGE_AND_TRANSPORT,
        euai:DISTRIBUTOR_OBLIGATION__VERIFICATION_AND_CORRECTIVE_ACTION,
        euai:NOTIFICATION_OBLIGATION ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_79_1_,
        euai:COMPETENT_AUTHORITY,
        euai:CONFORMITY_REQUIREMENTS,
        euai:CORRECTIVE_ACTION,
        euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ARTICLE_16,
        euai:PROVIDER_CLASSIFICATION_RULE .

euai:EMPLOYMENT__WORKERS__MANAGEMENT_AND_ACCESS_TO_SELF_EMPLOYMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AnnexIIICategory ;
    rdfs:label "EMPLOYMENT, WORKERS’ MANAGEMENT AND ACCESS TO SELF-EMPLOYMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "High-risk domain covering recruitment, selection, and performance evaluation in work-related relationships."@en .

euai:ETHICAL_PRINCIPLES_FOR_TRUSTWORTHY_AI a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "ETHICAL PRINCIPLES FOR TRUSTWORTHY AI"@en ;
    skos:definition """The Ethical Principles for Trustworthy AI consist of a set of seven non-binding guidelines designed to steer the development, drafting of codes of practice, and overall design of coherent artificial intelligence systems. These principles act as a foundational framework for ensuring AI technologies are developed and deployed responsibly.

The seven core principles are as follows:

1.  **Human Agency and Oversight:** AI systems should support human autonomy and decision-making, ensuring appropriat"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CODE_OF_PRACTICE .

euai:EXIT_REPORT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "EXIT REPORT"@en ;
    skos:definition "A document provided by the competent authority to a participant detailing activities carried out in the sandbox, results, and learning outcomes. It can be used by providers to demonstrate compliance during conformity assessments"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOX,
        euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT,
        euai:SINGLE_INFORMATION_PLATFORM .

euai:LAW_ENFORCEMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AnnexIIICategory ;
    rdfs:label "LAW ENFORCEMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition """The category of "LAW ENFORCEMENT" is classified as a high-risk domain concerning the deployment of artificial intelligence systems. This domain encompasses any AI tools that are used by, or on behalf of, law enforcement authorities. 

Specifically, this area includes AI systems designed to perform critical functions such as assessing the risk of criminal victimization, evaluating evidence, and assessing the risk of reoffending or committing a crime. As detailed in Annex III(6), these high-risk a"""@en ;
    euai:alwaysClassifiedAs euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM ;
    euai:belongsToCategory euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_EVIDENCE_EVALUATION_IN_LAW_ENFORCEMENT,
        euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_LAW_ENFORCEMENT_PROFILING,
        euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_LAW_ENFORCEMENT_VICTIM_ASSESSMENT,
        euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_OFFENDING_RISK_ASSESSMENT,
        euai:AI_SYSTEM_FOR_POLYGRAPHS_IN_LAW_ENFORCEMENT ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_3_46_ ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:HARMONISED_RULES .

euai:POST_MARKET_MONITORING_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "POST-MARKET MONITORING SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition """The Post-Market Monitoring System is a mandatory technical and organizational structure that providers of high-risk AI systems must establish, implement, and maintain. As outlined in Article 72 of the relevant regulatory framework (and supported by Recital 81), this system is essential for the continuous oversight of AI systems once they have been placed on the market or put into service.

The primary function of the Post-Market Monitoring System is to facilitate the active and systematic collec"""@en ;
    euai:hasException euai:DEPLOYER,
        euai:EXEMPTION_FROM_POST_MARKET_MONITORING ;
    euai:isBasedOn euai:POST_MARKET_MONITORING_PLAN ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:UNION_HARMONISATION_LEGISLATION .

euai:PROVIDER_OF_GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "PROVIDER OF GENERAL-PURPOSE AI MODEL"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Provider of General-Purpose AI Model**

A "Provider of General-Purpose AI Model" is defined as any natural or legal person, or their representative, who develops a general-purpose AI model or places such a model on the Union market. 

As the entity primarily responsible for the general-purpose AI model, the provider is subject to a robust framework of compliance and oversight. This includes strict adherence to obligations mandated by regulatory bodies, specifically the AI Office, which conduct"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_18_OF_REGULATION__EU__2019_1020 ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:ALTERNATIVE_ADEQUATE_MEANS_OF_COMPLIANCE ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_53,
        euai:ARTICLE_55,
        euai:ARTICLE_56,
        euai:AUTHORISED_REPRESENTATIVE,
        euai:CODE_OF_PRACTICE ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ARTICLE_18_REGULATION_2019_1020,
        euai:ARTICLE_92_EVALUATIONS,
        euai:EUROPEAN_HARMONISED_STANDARD,
        euai:OBLIGATION_TO_COMPLY_WITH_MEASURES,
        euai:OBLIGATION_TO_PROVIDE_ACCESS,
        euai:RISK_MITIGATION_MEASURES,
        euai:TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION .

euai:PROVIDER_OF_GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODELS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "PROVIDER OF GENERAL-PURPOSE AI MODELS"@en ;
    skos:definition """A Provider of General-Purpose AI Models is defined as any natural or legal person responsible for the development of a general-purpose AI model or for placing such a model onto the market. As the entity behind the creation and distribution of these models, the provider carries significant regulatory responsibilities.

Specifically, a Provider of General-Purpose AI Models is subject to various obligations mandated under Article 53, which governs the accountability and operational standards for th"""@en ;
    euai:cooperatesWith euai:EUROPEAN_COMMISSION,
        euai:NATIONAL_COMPETENT_AUTHORITIES ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:INFORMATION_DISCLOSURE_OBLIGATION,
        euai:REASSESSMENT_OF_SYSTEMIC_RISK,
        euai:TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION_OBLIGATION,
        euai:TRAINING_CONTENT_SUMMARY_OBLIGATION,
        euai:TRAINING_DATA_SUMMARY ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CODE_OF_PRACTICE,
        euai:COMPETITIVE_ADVANTAGE,
        euai:COPYRIGHT_COMPLIANCE_POLICY,
        euai:TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ADMINISTRATIVE_FINES .

euai:RECITAL_46 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "RECITAL 46"@en ;
    skos:definition "Recital outlining mandatory requirements for high-risk AI systems and the relationship with Union harmonisation legislation"@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2018_1725 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2018/1725"@en ;
    skos:definition """Regulation (EU) 2018/1725 serves as the primary legal framework concerning the protection of natural persons with regard to the processing of personal data by European Union institutions, bodies, offices, and agencies. It establishes the standards for how these entities must manage and safeguard personal information.

Beyond its general mandate on data protection, the regulation is instrumental in specific regulatory and operational contexts. It serves as the reference regulation for the consult"""@en .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2019_1020 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2019/1020"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Regulation (EU) 2019/1020** is the Union regulation governing market surveillance and product compliance. It serves as a fundamental pillar within the New Legislative Framework, providing the essential legal structure for ensuring that products placed on the market meet established safety and regulatory standards.

Within the context of the European Union's regulatory landscape, Regulation (EU) 2019/1020 plays a critical role in supporting the EU AI Act. It functions as the primary mechanism f"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DIRECTIVE_2004_42_EC,
        euai:REGULATION__EC__NO_765_2008 .

euai:REGULATION__EU__2024_1689 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "REGULATION (EU) 2024/1689"@en ;
    skos:definition "The Artificial Intelligence Act, providing a uniform legal framework for AI in the Union"@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:AI_SYSTEM ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:INTERNAL_MARKET .

euai:REMOTE_BIOMETRIC_IDENTIFICATION_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "REMOTE BIOMETRIC IDENTIFICATION SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition """A **Remote Biometric Identification System** is an AI-driven technology designed to identify natural persons by comparing their biometric data against a reference database. This process typically occurs at a distance and often without the active involvement or cooperation of the individual being identified. As defined in Article 3(41) of the relevant regulation, these systems encompass both "real-time" and "post" identification variants.

Because of the nature of the data processing involved, Re"""@en ;
    euai:alwaysClassifiedAs euai:HIGH_RISK,
        euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM ;
    euai:belongsToCategory euai:AISYSTEM ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_3_41_,
        euai:RECITAL_54 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:ANNEX_III_USE_CASE,
        euai:BIOMETRICS,
        euai:BIOMETRIC_VERIFICATION_EXCLUSION,
        euai:BIOMETRIC_VERIFICATION_PURPOSE,
        euai:CYBERSECURITY_PURPOSE,
        euai:PERSONAL_DATA_PROTECTION .

euai:REQUIREMENTS_OF_CHAPTER_III_SECTION_2 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "REQUIREMENTS OF CHAPTER III SECTION 2"@en ;
    skos:definition "A set of requirements from the EU AI Act (Regulation 2024/1689) which must be taken into account when specific EU acts (directives/regulations) are adopted or implemented regarding AI safety components"@en .

euai:AI_LITERACY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "AI LITERACY"@en ;
    skos:definition "**AI Literacy** is a critical set of notions, skills, knowledge, and understanding that enables individuals—specifically providers, deployers, and affected persons—to make informed decisions regarding the deployment and use of artificial intelligence systems. As defined in Article 3(56), it encompasses the ability to understand the technical elements of AI, interpret system outputs, and comprehend the potential impacts of AI on individuals and society, including an awareness of associated risks."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_4 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AFFECTED_PERSON,
        euai:DEPLOYER,
        euai:PROVIDER .

euai:ARTICLE_43 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 43"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ARTICLE 43**

Article 43 within the AI Act serves as a foundational provision defining the specific conformity assessment procedures required for high-risk AI systems. As a critical regulatory component, it establishes the frameworks that both manufacturers and notified bodies must adhere to ensure compliance.

Specifically, Article 43 outlines the necessary conformity assessment procedures applicable to different categories of high-risk AI systems. This includes detailing the procedural requi"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:IMPLEMENTING_ACTS,
        euai:REQUIREMENTS_IN_CHAPTER_III_SECTION_2 .

euai:ARTICLE_50 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 50"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Article 50** serves as a critical regulatory framework dedicated to establishing specific transparency obligations for the providers and deployers of AI systems. The article outlines detailed requirements that ensure clarity and accountability regarding the operation and usage of these technologies. 

Central to its purpose, Article 50 defines the nature and scope of transparency measures applicable to certain AI systems that require heightened scrutiny or public disclosure. It delineates the """@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:PENALTIES_FOR_GENERAL_NON_COMPLIANCE .

euai:ARTICLE_60 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 60"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ARTICLE 60**

Article 60 serves as a critical regulatory provision governing the testing of AI systems in real-world conditions. Specifically, it establishes the necessary conditions, requirements, and procedures for such testing, particularly for high-risk AI systems operating outside of dedicated AI regulatory sandboxes. 

The article delineates the registration obligations and transparency requirements that developers must adhere to when conducting these real-world tests. It functions as a """@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:REAL_WORLD_TESTING_PLAN .

euai:ARTICLE_71 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 71"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 71 serves as the regulatory provision responsible for the establishment, definition, and ongoing maintenance of the EU database for the registration of high-risk AI systems. This article acts as the formal reference governing how this specific database is created and operated within the framework of European Union AI regulations. By defining the scope and purpose of the database, Article 71 ensures there is a centralized, mandated system for the registration of high-risk artificial intel"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_6_2_ .

euai:ARTICLE_79 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 79"@en ;
    skos:definition """Article 79 establishes a comprehensive legal framework for addressing AI systems that present risks to health, safety, or fundamental rights, even when those systems are ostensibly in compliance with regulatory requirements. Serving as a crucial mechanism for safeguarding the public, this article defines the procedure at the national level for competent authorities to handle AI systems that, despite being compliant, still pose a risk.

Furthermore, Article 79 details the enforcement procedures n"""@en .

euai:ARTICLE_98_2_ a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 98(2)"@en ;
    skos:definition """Article 98(2) serves as the legal provision that establishes and governs the examination procedure used by the European Commission for the adoption of implementing acts. This mechanism is central to the regulatory framework, ensuring a consistent approach when the Commission is tasked with finalizing technical or administrative details.

The scope of Article 98(2) is broad and encompasses various specific applications across different regulatory contexts. It is explicitly identified as the gover"""@en .

euai:ARTICLE_99 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 99"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article 99 functions as the definitive framework within the AI Act governing the imposition of penalties for non-compliance and circumvention of its requirements. It establishes the legal basis for regulatory enforcement, detailing the structure for fines and penalties applicable to operators. Specifically, Article 99 outlines the mechanisms for calculating administrative fines, including the relevant circumstances and factors that authorities must consider when determining the appropriate sanct"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_96 .

euai:CE_MARKING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CE MARKING"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **CE marking** serves as a mandatory indicator of conformity for products within the European Economic Area. It signifies that a product, particularly high-risk AI systems, complies with the requirements outlined in applicable Union harmonization legislation, including the provisions set forth in Chapter III, Section 2 of the AI Act. This marking is essential for ensuring the free movement of these systems within the internal market.

Subject to the general principles of Regulation (EC) No 7"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CHAPTER_III__SECTION_2 ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:REGULATION__EC__NO_765_2008 .

euai:COMPETENT_AUTHORITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "COMPETENT AUTHORITY"@en ;
    skos:definition "Public body or authority responsible for law enforcement or other official activities that may deploy AI systems, subject to specific rules under the Regulation"@en ;
    euai:cooperatesWith euai:DISTRIBUTOR ;
    euai:enforces euai:COOPERATION_WITH_COMPETENT_AUTHORITIES ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_ECOSYSTEM,
        euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOX,
        euai:AUTHORISATION_REQUIREMENT,
        euai:COOPERATION_OBLIGATION,
        euai:EXIT_REPORT,
        euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:PROJECT_SUMMARY,
        euai:PROVIDER,
        euai:REAL_TIME_REMOTE_BIOMETRIC_IDENTIFICATION_SYSTEM,
        euai:TESTING_IN_REAL_WORLD_CONDITIONS,
        euai:WRITTEN_PROOF .

euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT_BODY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "CONFORMITY ASSESSMENT BODY"@en ;
    skos:definition """A Conformity Assessment Body is a designated third-party organization responsible for performing conformity assessment activities, which include testing, certification, and inspection. These bodies play a critical role under Union harmonization legislation, where their involvement in certain contexts, such as the evaluation of Artificial Intelligence systems, can determine high-risk classifications.

To operate in this capacity, a Conformity Assessment Body must first apply for notification to a"""@en ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:APPLICATION_FOR_NOTIFICATION ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT,
        euai:NOTIFIED_BODY ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ARTICLE_31 ;
    euai:triggers euai:SAFETY_COMPONENT_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:CodeOfPractice a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "CodeOfPractice"@en ;
    skos:definition "A voluntary compliance instrument for GPAI model providers."@en .

euai:EUROPEAN_DATA_PROTECTION_SUPERVISOR a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "EUROPEAN DATA PROTECTION SUPERVISOR"@en ;
    skos:definition """The European Data Protection Supervisor (EDPS) serves as a central regulatory body responsible for overseeing the implementation of the AI Act as it pertains to Union institutions, bodies, offices, and agencies. Acting within the scope of this regulation, the EDPS is designated as the competent authority for the supervision of these entities.

Specifically, the EDPS functions as the market surveillance authority for all Union institutions, agencies, and bodies, with the sole exception of the Cou"""@en ;
    euai:conductsEvaluationOf euai:UNION_INSTITUTIONS__AGENCIES_AND_BODIES ;
    euai:enforces euai:UNION_INSTITUTIONS ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:ANNUAL_NOTIFICATION ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ADMINISTRATIVE_FINE,
        euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOX,
        euai:EUROPEAN_ARTIFICIAL_INTELLIGENCE_BOARD,
        euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY,
        euai:NATIONAL_COMPETENT_AUTHORITY,
        euai:REGULATION__EU__2018_1725,
        euai:RIGHTS_OF_DEFENCE,
        euai:UNION_INSTITUTIONS__BODIES__OFFICES_AND_AGENCIES,
        euai:UNION_INSTITUTION__BODY__OFFICE_OR_AGENCY .

euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL_WITH_SYSTEMIC_RISKS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:SystemicRisk ;
    rdfs:label "GENERAL-PURPOSE AI MODEL WITH SYSTEMIC RISKS"@en ;
    skos:definition """**GENERAL-PURPOSE AI MODEL WITH SYSTEMIC RISKS**

A "General-Purpose AI Model with Systemic Risks" is a classification assigned to general-purpose AI (GPAI) models that possess the potential to cause significant harm or disruption. These models are identified based on two primary criteria: the possession of high-impact capabilities or a significant market reach that could lead to widespread consequences. Due to the inherent dangers associated with such models, they are subject to strict regulato"""@en ;
    euai:belongsToCategory euai:SYSTEMIC_RISK ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:POST_MARKET_MONITORING,
        euai:RISK_MANAGEMENT_POLICY .

euai:IMPLEMENTING_ACTS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:DelegatedAct ;
    rdfs:label "IMPLEMENTING ACTS"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Implementing Acts** are legal instruments adopted by the European Commission that serve various regulatory and procedural functions within the framework of the AI Act. These acts are utilized to ensure the effective application and standardization of requirements across different contexts.

Specifically, Implementing Acts are employed to establish detailed arrangements and procedural safeguards concerning infringement proceedings, as outlined under Article 101(6). They also play a crucial role"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_98_2_,
        euai:REQUIREMENTS_IN_CHAPTER_III_SECTION_2 .

euai:NOTIFICATION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "NOTIFICATION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **NOTIFICATION OBLIGATION** encompasses a variety of reporting requirements mandated across different stakeholders involved in the regulatory frameworks for AI and legislative processes, ensuring transparency, safety, and oversight. These obligations apply differently depending on the role of the entity involved:

For the European Commission, a specific notification duty exists regarding delegated acts. Upon the adoption of any delegated act, the Commission is required to notify both the Eur"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_5,
        euai:ARTICLE_52 .

euai:POST_MARKET_MONITORING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "POST MARKET MONITORING"@en,
        "POST-MARKET MONITORING"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Post-market monitoring** refers to the essential regulatory system designed to oversee the performance and associated risks of an artificial intelligence (AI) system after it has been officially placed on the market. As referenced in Article 72, this framework functions as an ongoing requirement that extends throughout the entire lifecycle of the AI system.

The primary objective of post-market monitoring is to ensure that AI systems maintain consistent standards and adhere to regulatory oblig"""@en,
        "A duty of the provider to monitor the operation of a high-risk AI system after it has been placed on the market or put into service to ensure ongoing compliance and identify risks."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_72 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_72 ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:PROHIBITION_OF_MANIPULATIVE_AI_PRACTICES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PROHIBITION OF MANIPULATIVE AI PRACTICES"@en ;
    skos:definition "A ban on AI systems that distort human behavior or exploit vulnerabilities to cause significant harm, detailed in Recital 29."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_29 .

euai:RECORD_KEEPING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RECORD-KEEPING"@en ;
    skos:definition """**RECORD-KEEPING** in the context of AI systems refers to the essential obligation to maintain thorough logs and data trails regarding the operation, activities, and performance of these systems. This practice serves as a critical component of monitoring and accountability frameworks.

For high-risk AI systems, RECORD-KEEPING is not merely a best practice but a mandatory capability and regulatory requirement, specifically mandated by Article 12. This provision requires such systems to possess th"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_12,
        euai:POST_MARKET_MONITORING .

euai:REGISTRATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REGISTRATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "**REGISTRATION** refers to the mandatory process required for providers, authorised representatives, and specific deployers of high-risk AI systems within the European Union. This regulatory obligation mandates that these entities input detailed information regarding their high-risk AI systems into the designated EU database. This registration must be completed prior to the systems being placed on the market or put into service, ensuring transparency and compliance with EU standards for AI deplo"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_III,
        euai:EU_DATABASE .

euai:REGISTRATION_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REGISTRATION OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The "REGISTRATION OBLIGATION" constitutes a critical regulatory requirement under the EU AI Act, mandating that specific AI systems be documented and submitted to the centralized EU database to ensure transparency and compliance. This duty applies broadly to both providers and deployers, including public authorities and Union institutions, to ensure that all relevant high-risk AI systems are accounted for and traceable.

Primarily, the REGISTRATION OBLIGATION requires providers to submit and mai"""@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_49_2_,
        euai:ARTICLE_49_3_ ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_IX,
        euai:ARTICLE_49,
        euai:ARTICLE_71 .

euai:RISK_MANAGEMENT_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "RISK MANAGEMENT SYSTEM"@en,
        "RISK-MANAGEMENT SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "A risk-management system is a mandatory, systematic process designed for implementation throughout the entire lifecycle of a high-risk AI system. This framework functions as a continuous and iterative operation that is both carefully planned and actively executed to ensure ongoing oversight. The primary objective of the risk-management system is to proactively identify and mitigate potential hazards that could compromise health, safety, and the protection of fundamental rights."@en,
        """The **Risk Management System** is a mandatory, continuous, and iterative component of the quality management system for high-risk AI systems, as required by Article 9. It serves as a vital framework that providers must establish to ensure the trustworthiness of their AI systems by identifying, analyzing, estimating, evaluating, and mitigating foreseeable risks and unintended outcomes.

At its core, the **Risk Management System** is designed to protect health, safety, and fundamental rights throu"""@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_72 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_9,
        euai:HEALTH__SAFETY_AND_FUNDAMENTAL_RIGHTS,
        euai:POST_MARKET_MONITORING_SYSTEM,
        euai:PROVIDER,
        euai:RISK_ESTIMATION_AND_EVALUATION,
        euai:RISK_IDENTIFICATION_AND_ANALYSIS,
        euai:RISK_MANAGEMENT_MEASURES,
        euai:STATE_OF_THE_ART_ON_AI,
        euai:UNION_HARMONISATION_LEGISLATION .

euai:SCIENTIFIC_PANEL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "SCIENTIFIC PANEL"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **Scientific Panel** is a body of independent experts established by the Commission to support the implementation and enforcement of the AI Act. Its primary purpose is to integrate the broader scientific community into the regulation’s operational framework.

Specifically, the Scientific Panel is established pursuant to Article 68 and plays a crucial role in assisting the Commission with evaluations, as referenced in Article 92. Its mandate includes supporting enforcement and regulatory acti"""@en ;
    euai:providesInstructionsTo euai:CODE_OF_PRACTICE ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_68_2_,
        euai:ARTICLE_81,
        euai:ARTICLE_92_EVALUATIONS,
        euai:COMMISSION,
        euai:DECLARATION_OF_INTERESTS,
        euai:EUROPEAN_ARTIFICIAL_INTELLIGENCE_BOARD,
        euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL,
        euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL_WITH_SYSTEMIC_RISK,
        euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITIES,
        euai:MEMBER_STATES,
        euai:QUALIFIED_ALERT,
        euai:QUALIFIED_ALERTS,
        euai:SYSTEMIC_RISK ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:IMPARTIALITY_AND_OBJECTIVITY_OBLIGATION ;
    euai:triggers euai:AI_OFFICE,
        euai:CONCRETE_AND_IDENTIFIABLE_RISK .

euai:SERIOUS_INCIDENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:SeriousIncident ;
    rdfs:label "SERIOUS INCIDENT"@en ;
    skos:definition "A \"Serious Incident\" refers to a critical event or malfunctioning associated with an AI system that necessitates urgent regulatory and operational oversight. As defined under Article 3(49), it encompasses any incident directly or indirectly resulting in the death or serious harm to an individual’s health, the serious and irreversible disruption of the management and operation of critical infrastructure, the infringement of fundamental rights, or substantial damage to property or the environment."@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_3_49_,
        euai:ARTICLE_73 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:REPORTING_SERIOUS_INCIDENTS,
        euai:SERIOUS_INCIDENT_REPORTING,
        euai:TESTING_IN_REAL_WORLD_CONDITIONS ;
    euai:triggers euai:REPORTING_OBLIGATION .

euai:SystemicRisk a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "SystemicRisk"@en ;
    skos:definition "Risk classification for GPAI models exceeding the compute threshold."@en .

euai:TRANSPARENCY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TRANSPARENCY"@en ;
    skos:definition """In the context of the AI Act, "Transparency" serves as a fundamental requirement for AI systems, designed to ensure that their operations, outputs, and underlying processes are both understandable and well-documented. This core obligation mandates that AI systems must be explainable and transparent, a necessity for upholding accountability and protecting fundamental rights. 

By demanding clarity and openness, Transparency functions as a critical mechanism that allows stakeholders to comprehend """@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:AISYSTEM rdfs:label "AISYSTEM"@en .

euai:ANNEX_I a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ANNEX I"@en ;
    skos:definition """**ANNEX I** is a critical component of the EU AI Regulation, serving as a comprehensive reference document that lists Union harmonisation legislation relevant to high-risk AI systems. By establishing a clear scope of applicable laws, this annex functions as a foundational guide for product safety, compliance, and regulatory oversight.

Central to its purpose, Annex I catalogues the specific Union harmonisation legislation to which products incorporating AI systems must comply. It is explicitly r"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:UNION_HARMONISATION_LEGISLATION .

euai:ARTICLE_47 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 47"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Article 47** of the EU AI Act establishes and governs the requirements for the EU declaration of conformity, specifically concerning high-risk AI systems. This article mandates that providers of such systems must issue an EU declaration of conformity, which is required to accompany the high-risk AI system to ensure compliance. 

Furthermore, Article 47 has been amended to include specific procedural obligations regarding delegated acts. When adopting delegated acts that concern AI systems clas"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DELEGATED_ACTS,
        euai:REQUIREMENTS_IN_CHAPTER_III_SECTION_2 .

euai:ARTICLE_83 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 83"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article defining the procedure for handling formal non-compliance of high-risk AI systems"@en .

euai:BIOMETRICS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AnnexIIICategory ;
    rdfs:label "BIOMETRICS"@en ;
    skos:definition """**BIOMETRICS** are classified as a high-risk AI system domain under Annex III of the EU AI Act. This domain encompasses AI systems designed for remote biometric identification, biometric categorisation, and emotion recognition. As a high-risk area, these technologies are subject to stringent oversight and specific market surveillance powers, as highlighted in Recital 54.

Due to their classification as high-risk, AI systems used for biometrics are subject to rigorous regulatory standards. Unlike"""@en ;
    euai:belongsToCategory euai:BIOMETRIC_CATEGORISATION_SYSTEM,
        euai:REMOTE_BIOMETRIC_IDENTIFICATION_SYSTEM ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_III,
        euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:HARMONISED_RULES .

euai:EU_DECLARATION_OF_CONFORMITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "EU DECLARATION OF CONFORMITY"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **EU Declaration of Conformity** is a critical, formal document that serves as an official assertion by a provider that a high-risk AI system complies with the requirements set out in the AI Act—specifically those detailed in Section 2—as well as other relevant Union law. As mandated by Article 47 and Annex V of the AI Act, this declaration must be drawn up by the provider to attest that the AI system meets all necessary regulatory standards.

Functioning as a legal instrument of compliance,"""@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:NATIONAL_COMPETENT_AUTHORITIES ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_83 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_V,
        euai:ARTICLE_47,
        euai:AUTHORISED_REPRESENTATIVE,
        euai:NOTIFIED_BODY,
        euai:REGULATION_ON_HORIZONTAL_CYBERSECURITY_REQUIREMENTS_FOR_PRODUCTS_WITH_DIGITAL_ELEMENTS,
        euai:REQUIREMENTS_OF_SECTION_2,
        euai:UNION_HARMONISATION_LEGISLATION .

euai:HUMAN_OVERSIGHT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "HUMAN OVERSIGHT"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Human Oversight**

Human oversight acts as a fundamental governance arrangement and mandatory mitigation measure, primarily concerning the deployment of high-risk AI systems. As established under Article 14, it is a core requirement that mandates AI systems be designed to ensure that natural persons can effectively monitor, understand, intervene in, and override system outputs. The overarching goal of these measures is to mitigate risks to health, safety, and fundamental rights, and to prevent"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_14,
        euai:DEPLOYER,
        euai:FUNDAMENTAL_RIGHTS_IMPACT_ASSESSMENT,
        euai:RECITAL_73 .

euai:MEMBER_STATES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "MEMBER STATES"@en ;
    skos:definition "**MEMBER STATES** play a pivotal role in the implementation and enforcement of the AI Regulation. As the national authorities of EU countries, they bear the primary responsibility for ensuring compliance with the Regulation within their respective jurisdictions. This encompasses the critical task of establishing and enforcing rules on penalties, while ensuring that the internal market remains functional; consequently, they are prohibited from imposing unjustified restrictions on AI systems that "@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_OFFICE,
        euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOX,
        euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOXES,
        euai:ARTICLE_95_CODES_OF_CONDUCT,
        euai:AWARENESS_RAISING_AND_TRAINING_ACTIVITIES,
        euai:CE_MARKING,
        euai:CODE_OF_CONDUCT,
        euai:COMPLIANCE_WITH_THE_REGULATION,
        euai:CONSULTATION_PROCEDURE,
        euai:EUROPEAN_ARTIFICIAL_INTELLIGENCE_BOARD,
        euai:FEE_PAYMENT_OBLIGATION,
        euai:FINANCIAL_AND_HUMAN_RESOURCES_ASSESSMENT,
        euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODELS,
        euai:HARMONISED_RULES,
        euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY,
        euai:NATIONAL_COMPETENT_AUTHORITY,
        euai:NE_BIS_IN_IDEM_PRINCIPLE,
        euai:NOTIFYING_AUTHORITY,
        euai:PENALTIES,
        euai:PENALTIES_FOR_GENERAL_NON_COMPLIANCE,
        euai:PENALTIES_FOR_MISLEADING_INFORMATION,
        euai:PENALTIES_FOR_PROHIBITED_PRACTICES,
        euai:PENALTIES_IMPLEMENTATION_OBLIGATION,
        euai:POOL_OF_EXPERTS,
        euai:REPORTING_OBLIGATION,
        euai:RESOURCE_PROVISION_OBLIGATION,
        euai:RESOURCE_REPORTING_OBLIGATION,
        euai:SCIENTIFIC_PANEL,
        euai:SME,
        euai:STANDARDISATION_DEVELOPMENT_PROCESS,
        euai:STANDARDISATION_DEVELOPMENT_PROCESSES,
        euai:TRANSLATION_COSTS,
        euai:UNION_AI_TESTING_SUPPORT_STRUCTURES,
        euai:VOLUNTARY_CODE_OF_CONDUCT ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ARTICLE_26_10_,
        euai:ARTICLE_5,
        euai:RESOURCE_PROVISION_REQUIREMENT .

euai:REAL_WORLD_TESTING_PLAN a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "REAL-WORLD TESTING PLAN"@en ;
    skos:definition """A Real-World Testing Plan is a formal, mandatory document required for the testing of high-risk AI systems in real-world conditions outside of controlled sandbox environments. As defined under the regulatory framework (specifically Article 60 and Article 3(53)), this plan serves as a comprehensive roadmap for providers and prospective providers who intend to conduct such evaluations.

The document must clearly outline the objectives, methodology, scope, and monitoring procedures for the proposed"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_60 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_5,
        euai:IMPLEMENTING_ACTS,
        euai:TACIT_APPROVAL .

euai:ADMINISTRATIVE_FINE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "ADMINISTRATIVE FINE"@en ;
    skos:definition "Monetary penalty imposed for infringements of the AI Act. The amount depends on specific criteria like nature/gravity of infringement, SME status, and operator size. Regulated by Article 99 and Article 100"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_100,
        euai:ARTICLE_99 .

euai:ARTICLE_3 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 3"@en ;
    skos:definition "ARTICLE 3 serves as the section of the Regulation dedicated to establishing and specifying the key terms and definitions necessary for the interpretation and application of the Regulation. By defining these essential concepts, ARTICLE 3 provides the foundational terminology required to ensure clarity and consistency throughout the document."@en .

euai:DELEGATED_ACT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:DelegatedAct ;
    rdfs:label "DELEGATED ACT"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Delegated Acts**

A Delegated Act is a legislative instrument adopted by the European Commission, primarily authorized under Article 290 of the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU) and Article 97 of the AI Act. These acts serve as a flexible mechanism that empowers the Commission to modify, supplement, or extend specific non-essential provisions of the AI Act to ensure the regulation remains effective and aligned with evolving technological progress.

Functionally, Delegated """@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_7_3_ ;
    euai:modifies euai:ANNEX_V,
        euai:ANNEX_VI,
        euai:ANNEX_VII,
        euai:ANNEX_XII,
        euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT_PROCEDURES,
        euai:EU_DECLARATION_OF_CONFORMITY,
        euai:TRANSPARENCY_INFORMATION ;
    euai:providesInstructionsTo euai:MEASUREMENT_AND_CALCULATION_METHODOLOGIES ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEXES,
        euai:ANNEX_I,
        euai:ANNEX_III,
        euai:ANNEX_IV,
        euai:ANNEX_XI,
        euai:ARTICLE_44,
        euai:ARTICLE_97,
        euai:COMMISSION,
        euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODELS_WITH_SYSTEMIC_RISK,
        euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:HIGH_RISK_CLASSIFICATION_RULE,
        euai:TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:DELEGATION_OF_POWER_PERIOD,
        euai:OBJECTION_PERIOD,
        euai:REQUIREMENTS_OF_CHAPTER_III_SECTION_2 .

euai:DelegatedAct a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "DelegatedAct"@en ;
    skos:definition "A Commission act that modifies or extends classification rules or obligations."@en .

euai:EDUCATION_AND_VOCATIONAL_TRAINING a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AnnexIIICategory ;
    rdfs:label "EDUCATION AND VOCATIONAL TRAINING"@en ;
    skos:definition "\"Education and Vocational Training\" is classified as a high-risk domain regarding the application of AI systems. This domain encompasses AI technologies utilized within educational and training environments, specifically focusing on critical functions such as facilitating access to educational institutions, evaluating learning outcomes, and monitoring student behavior. According to Recital 56, the designation of this domain as a high-risk use case highlights the necessity for stringent oversight"@en .

euai:HighRiskAISystem a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "High-Risk AI System"@en ;
    rdfs:subClassOf euai:AISystem ;
    skos:definition "An AI system listed in Annex III or embedded in a product covered by Union harmonisation legislation. (Article 6)"@en .

euai:PRESUMPTION_OF_CONFORMITY a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PRESUMPTION OF CONFORMITY"@en ;
    skos:definition """**PRESUMPTION OF CONFORMITY** is a legal status granted to AI systems and, in certain contexts, conformity assessment bodies, which significantly simplifies the process of demonstrating adherence to regulatory requirements. This status is primarily conferred upon AI systems that meet established benchmarks, such as European harmonised standards, common specifications, cybersecurity standards, or specific training data and certification criteria.

By achieving this status, providers are effective"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_40,
        euai:ARTICLE_42 .

euai:PRIOR_AUTHORISATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "PRIOR AUTHORISATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """**PRIOR AUTHORISATION**

Prior authorisation is a mandatory legal requirement for law enforcement agencies seeking to deploy real-time remote biometric identification systems. Under this framework, authorities must obtain express, specific, and binding approval from a judicial or independent administrative body before such systems can be utilized.

This process ensures oversight and accountability in the application of biometric technologies. However, the framework includes specific provisions f"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_5 .

euai:REAL_TIME_REMOTE_BIOMETRIC_IDENTIFICATION_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "REAL-TIME REMOTE BIOMETRIC IDENTIFICATION SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **Real-Time Remote Biometric Identification System** is a sophisticated AI technology defined as a remote biometric identification system where the capturing, comparison, and identification of biometric data occur instantaneously or near-instantaneously without significant delay. This process utilizes live or "near-live" material, such as real-time video footage, to identify natural persons. 

Under the AI Act, these systems are categorized as high-risk and are subject to stringent oversight"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_3_42_,
        euai:RECITAL_17,
        euai:RECITAL_33 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ADVERSE_LEGAL_EFFECT,
        euai:ANNEX__LIST_OF_CRIMINAL_OFFENCES_,
        euai:ARTICLE_10_OF_DIRECTIVE__EU_,
        euai:ARTICLE_10_OF_DIRECTIVE__EU__2016_680,
        euai:ARTICLE_16_TFEU,
        euai:ARTICLE_5,
        euai:CRIMINAL_OFFENCES,
        euai:CRITICAL_INFRASTRUCTURE,
        euai:HUMAN_OVERSIGHT,
        euai:LAW_ENFORCEMENT_OBJECTIVES,
        euai:PROHIBITED_AI_PRACTICE,
        euai:PUBLICLY_ACCESSIBLE_SPACE,
        euai:PUBLICLY_ACCESSIBLE_SPACES,
        euai:RECITAL_32,
        euai:REMOTE_BIOMETRIC_IDENTIFICATION_SYSTEM ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ADVERSE_LEGAL_EFFECT_PROHIBITION,
        euai:AUTHORISATION_REQUIREMENT,
        euai:CRIMINAL_OFFENCE_THRESHOLD,
        euai:PRIOR_AUTHORISATION,
        euai:PROHIBITION_OF_AI_PRACTICES ;
    euai:triggers euai:DATA_DELETION_OBLIGATION,
        euai:NOTIFICATION_OBLIGATION .

euai:TESTING_IN_REAL_WORLD_CONDITIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "TESTING IN REAL WORLD CONDITIONS"@en,
        "TESTING IN REAL-WORLD CONDITIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Testing in Real World Conditions** refers to a regulatory mechanism designed to facilitate the deployment and evaluation of artificial intelligence systems outside of controlled laboratory environments. This framework is primarily governed by Articles 57, 59, and 60 of the applicable AI regulations.

The concept encompasses two primary operational modes. First, it involves testing activities conducted within established AI regulatory sandboxes. In this context, developers may test innovative A"""@en,
        "Temporary testing of an AI system outside laboratory environments to gather data and verify conformity; does not qualify as placing on the market if conditions in Article 57 or 60 are met, as defined in Article 3(57)"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOX,
        euai:ARTICLE_57,
        euai:ARTICLE_60,
        euai:ARTICLE_61,
        euai:INFORMED_CONSENT,
        euai:REAL_WORLD_TESTING_PLAN,
        euai:TESTING_DURATION_LIMIT,
        euai:TESTING_PLAN ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:REGISTRATION_OF_TESTING .

euai:ARTICLE_113 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 113"@en ;
    skos:definition "Article concerning the entry into force and application dates of the Regulation."@en .

euai:CHAPTER_III__SECTION_2 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "CHAPTER III, SECTION 2"@en ;
    skos:definition """**CHAPTER III, SECTION 2**

CHAPTER III, SECTION 2 is a critical component of the EU AI Act, specifically designed to establish the regulatory framework for high-risk AI systems. This section delineates the essential technical and organizational requirements that providers must adhere to in order to ensure their systems are safe, transparent, and accountable. 

Compliance with the mandates set forth in this section is a necessary precursor for market access, as it dictates the standards to which"""@en .

euai:COMMON_SPECIFICATIONS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "COMMON SPECIFICATIONS"@en ;
    skos:definition "An exceptional fall-back solution established by the Commission via implementing acts to facilitate provider compliance when harmonised standards are absent, insufficient, or delayed"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_41,
        euai:CHAPTER_V__SECTIONS_2_AND_3,
        euai:COMMISSION,
        euai:SECTION_2_OF_CHAPTER_II,
        euai:STANDARDISATION_REQUEST ;
    euai:triggers euai:PRESUMPTION_OF_CONFORMITY .

euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL_WITH_SYSTEMIC_RISK a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:SystemicRisk ;
    rdfs:label "GENERAL-PURPOSE AI MODEL WITH SYSTEMIC RISK"@en ;
    skos:definition """A "General-Purpose AI Model with Systemic Risk" is a specific classification of general-purpose AI (GPAI) models that possess high-impact capabilities sufficient to pose concrete, identifiable risks at the Union level. These models are subject to additional, stricter regulatory obligations under the European Union’s AI Act to ensure safety and transparency.

A model is designated as having systemic risk based on specific criteria defined in the AI Act. The primary technical benchmark for this cl"""@en ;
    euai:belongsToCategory euai:SYSTEMIC_RISK ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_XIII,
        euai:ARTICLE_51,
        euai:ARTICLE_55,
        euai:ARTICLE_92,
        euai:COMMISSION,
        euai:EUROPEAN_COMMISSION,
        euai:MODEL_EVALUATION ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:ARTICLE_93_MITIGATION_MEASURES,
        euai:POST_MARKET_MONITORING,
        euai:RISK_MANAGEMENT_POLICIES .

euai:HARMONISED_STANDARDS a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "HARMONISED STANDARDS"@en ;
    skos:definition "Technical specifications adopted by European standardisation organisations that, when followed, allow providers to presume compliance with the requirements of this Regulation"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_40,
        euai:ARTICLE_40_AND_41 ;
    euai:presumesConformity euai:ARTICLE_31,
        euai:CHAPTER_V__SECTIONS_2_AND_3,
        euai:SECTION_2_OF_CHAPTER_II ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_2,
        euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:OFFICIAL_JOURNAL_OF_THE_EUROPEAN_UNION,
        euai:PRESUMPTION_OF_CONFORMITY,
        euai:REGULATION__EU__NO_1025_2012 .

euai:SME a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Actor ;
    rdfs:label "SME"@en ;
    skos:definition "Small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs), including start-ups, are central to the regulatory framework surrounding artificial intelligence. Recognizing their limited legal and administrative capacities, the AI Act mandates that the specific needs of these entities be considered by the AI Office and Member States, as outlined in Articles 95 and 96. To prevent excessive burdens and high compliance costs, the regulation provides various support mechanisms and relief measures designed to ensure SME"@en ;
    euai:cooperatesWith euai:HARMONISED_STANDARD ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ADMINISTRATIVE_FINE,
        euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOXES,
        euai:HARMONISED_STANDARDS,
        euai:MODEL_MODIFICATION,
        euai:PROVIDER_OF_GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODELS,
        euai:SIMPLIFIED_TECHNICAL_DOCUMENTATION_FORM ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:FEES_FOR_CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT .

euai:CODE_OF_CONDUCT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:CodeOfPractice ;
    rdfs:label "CODE OF CONDUCT"@en ;
    skos:definition """The "Code of Conduct" serves as a voluntary instrument designed to enhance the ethical development and deployment of artificial intelligence. It primarily targets providers of AI systems that are not classified as high-risk, encouraging these entities to voluntarily adopt the mandatory requirements established for high-risk AI systems. By doing so, the Code of Conduct promotes consistency in safety and ethical standards across the broader AI landscape.

As outlined in Article 95 of the relevant """@en ;
    euai:appliesTo euai:NON_HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:PROVIDER_OF_GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_95 ;
    euai:isBasedOn euai:MANDATORY_REQUIREMENTS,
        euai:UNION_ETHICS_GUIDELINES_FOR_TRUSTWORTHY_AI ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_LITERACY,
        euai:AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:ENVIRONMENTAL_SUSTAINABILITY_REQUIREMENT,
        euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:INCLUSIVE_AND_DIVERSE_DESIGN,
        euai:NEGATIVE_IMPACT_ASSESSMENT,
        euai:STAKEHOLDERS,
        euai:UNION_ETHICAL_GUIDELINES_FOR_TRUSTWORTHY_AI,
        euai:VOLUNTARY_CODES_OF_CONDUCT_EVALUATION .

euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT_PROCEDURE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CONFORMITY ASSESSMENT PROCEDURE"@en ;
    skos:definition """The "Conformity Assessment Procedure" serves as a critical mechanism for ensuring that AI systems adhere to the necessary legal and safety requirements established by the Regulation. It is a mandatory process that must be completed before an AI system can be placed on the market, functioning as a vital step in demonstrating that a system meets all applicable compliance standards.

At its core, the Conformity Assessment Procedure is the method used to verify that a high-risk AI system aligns with"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_43 ;
    euai:triggers euai:HIGH_RISK_AI_SYSTEM .

euai:ESSENTIAL_PRIVATE_AND_PUBLIC_SERVICES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AnnexIIICategory ;
    rdfs:label "ESSENTIAL PRIVATE AND PUBLIC SERVICES"@en ;
    skos:definition "High-risk domain covering public assistance eligibility, creditworthiness, insurance risk, and emergency response."@en .

euai:EUROPEAN_ARTIFICIAL_INTELLIGENCE_BOARD a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "EUROPEAN ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE BOARD"@en ;
    skos:definition """The European Artificial Intelligence Board (often referred to simply as "the Board") is a central governing and advisory body established under the AI Act. Composed of representatives from Member States, with participation from the AI Office and the European Data Protection Supervisor (EDPS), the Board serves a critical function in the uniform application and enforcement of AI regulations across the European Union.

The Board’s primary mandate is to facilitate consistency, coordination, and coop"""@en ;
    euai:conductsEvaluationOf euai:EU_DATABASE,
        euai:SERIOUS_INCIDENT ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_112,
        euai:ARTICLE_57,
        euai:ARTICLE_59,
        euai:ARTICLE_60,
        euai:ARTICLE_65,
        euai:ARTICLE_66,
        euai:ARTICLE_67,
        euai:ARTICLE_71,
        euai:ARTICLE_73,
        euai:ARTICLE_74_11_ ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ADVISORY_FORUM,
        euai:AI_LITERACY,
        euai:AI_OFFICE,
        euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOX,
        euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOXES,
        euai:ANNEX_I,
        euai:ANNEX_III,
        euai:ARTICLE_5,
        euai:ARTICLE_7,
        euai:CODE_OF_PRACTICE,
        euai:COMMISSION,
        euai:COMMON_SPECIFICATIONS,
        euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT,
        euai:DELEGATED_ACT,
        euai:EUROPEAN_COMMISSION,
        euai:EXIT_REPORT,
        euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL,
        euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODELS,
        euai:HARMONISED_STANDARDS,
        euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITIES,
        euai:MARKET_SURVEILLANCE_AUTHORITY,
        euai:MEMBER_STATES,
        euai:NATIONAL_COMPETENT_AUTHORITY,
        euai:NOTIFYING_AUTHORITIES,
        euai:STANDING_SUBGROUP_FOR_MARKET_SURVEILLANCE,
        euai:STANDING_SUB_GROUPS,
        euai:TESTING_IN_REAL_WORLD_CONDITIONS .

euai:QUALITY_MANAGEMENT_SYSTEM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "QUALITY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM"@en ;
    skos:definition "A Quality Management System (QMS) is a mandatory organizational requirement that providers of high-risk AI systems must establish to ensure compliance with the relevant AI regulations. As detailed in Article 17, this system functions as a framework for documented policies and procedures, encompassing critical areas such as strategy, design control, verification, data management, risk management, post-market monitoring, incident reporting, and accountability. The QMS serves as a comprehensive sys"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_63 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_17,
        euai:DATA_MANAGEMENT,
        euai:DATA_MANAGEMENT_SYSTEM,
        euai:DESIGN_CONTROL,
        euai:DEVELOPMENT_AND_QUALITY_CONTROL,
        euai:EXAMINATION_AND_VALIDATION_PROCEDURES,
        euai:POST_MARKET_MONITORING_SYSTEM,
        euai:RISK_MANAGEMENT_SYSTEM,
        euai:SERIOUS_INCIDENT_REPORTING,
        euai:STRATEGY_FOR_REGULATORY_COMPLIANCE,
        euai:TECHNICAL_SPECIFICATIONS .

euai:REQUIREMENTS_IN_CHAPTER_III_SECTION_2 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "REQUIREMENTS IN CHAPTER III SECTION 2"@en ;
    skos:definition "Technical and organizational requirements set out in the AI Act (Regulation 2024/1689) that must be considered when other regulations adopt delegated or implementing acts concerning AI safety components."@en .

euai:ADVISORY_FORUM a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "ADVISORY FORUM"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **Advisory Forum** is a dedicated advisory body established to provide technical expertise and strategic guidance to both the European AI Board and the European Commission.

Composed of a diverse group of stakeholders, the Advisory Forum includes representatives from industry, small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs), academia, and civil society. It also incorporates participation from key organizations such as the European Union Agency for Fundamental Rights (FRA), the European Union Agenc"""@en ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:ANNUAL_REPORT_PREPARATION ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_67,
        euai:BOARD,
        euai:EUROPEAN_ARTIFICIAL_INTELLIGENCE_BOARD,
        euai:EUROPEAN_COMMISSION .

euai:EU_DATABASE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "EU DATABASE"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **EU DATABASE** is a central repository established and managed by the European Commission, serving as a critical tool for the oversight and regulation of artificial intelligence systems. As referenced in Article 71 of the relevant regulations, this database functions as an essential resource for market surveillance authorities, enabling them to effectively monitor AI systems and perform necessary checks as mandated by Article 81(8).

Structurally, the **EU DATABASE** is designed to house in"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_71 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DIRECTIVE__EU__2019_882,
        euai:EUROPEAN_COMMISSION .

euai:FUNDAMENTAL_RIGHTS_IMPACT_ASSESSMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Requirement ;
    rdfs:label "FUNDAMENTAL RIGHTS IMPACT ASSESSMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition """A Fundamental Rights Impact Assessment is a mandatory evaluation required for the deployment of specific artificial intelligence (AI) systems. The assessment serves as a critical procedural safeguard, ensuring that deployers analyze the potential impacts on fundamental rights before putting such systems into operation.

For high-risk AI systems as defined under the relevant framework, particularly those outlined in Annex III (points 5(b) and (c)), the assessment must be conducted by specific dep"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:RECITAL_96 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_27,
        euai:ARTICLE_27_OF_DIRECTIVE__EU__2016_680,
        euai:ARTICLE_35_OF_REGULATION__EU__2016_679,
        euai:DATA_PROTECTION_IMPACT_ASSESSMENT,
        euai:DEPLOYER .

euai:PROHIBITED_AI_PRACTICE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "PROHIBITED AI PRACTICE"@en ;
    skos:definition """**PROHIBITED AI PRACTICE** refers to any artificial intelligence system or practice that is strictly forbidden from being placed on the market, put into service, or utilized. These prohibitions, primarily outlined in Article 5 of the relevant Regulation, are established because such systems pose unacceptable risks to fundamental rights and safety.

A core category of these prohibited AI systems includes those that employ manipulative, exploitative, or social control techniques. Such practices ar"""@en ;
    euai:belongsToCategory euai:UNACCEPTABLE_RISK ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_5,
        euai:ARTICLE_5_PROHIBITIONS,
        euai:RECITALS_29_30 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:NATURAL_PERSONS,
        euai:RECITAL_28,
        euai:RECITAL_29 ;
    euai:subjectTo euai:PROHIBITION,
        euai:SAFEGUARD_PROCEDURE .

euai:REPORTING_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "REPORTING OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The Reporting Obligations outlined within the regulatory framework impose significant transparency and accountability duties on Member States, providers, market surveillance authorities, and the European Commission. These obligations ensure rigorous oversight and compliance throughout the implementation of the regulations.

Regarding resource management, Member States are required to report to the European Commission on the status and adequacy of their national competent authorities' resources b"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_5 ;
    euai:hasDeadline euai:ARTICLE_3_49__B_ ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ARTICLE_3_49__C_,
        euai:COMMISSION,
        euai:COMPETITION_AUTHORITIES,
        euai:SERIOUS_INCIDENT .

euai:SYSTEMIC_RISK a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:SystemicRisk ;
    rdfs:label "SYSTEMIC RISK"@en ;
    skos:definition "**Systemic Risk** is a critical classification applied to general-purpose AI (GPAI) models under the European Union’s regulatory framework. It identifies models that, due to their significant scale, high-impact capabilities, or reach, pose identifiable and concrete risks at the Union level. These risks carry the potential for major consequences, including widespread accidents, threats to public health and safety, disruption of democratic processes and civic discourse, interference with electoral"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:FREE_AND_OPEN_SOURCE_AI_COMPONENTS,
        euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL_WITH_SYSTEMIC_RISK,
        euai:HIGH_IMPACT_CAPABILITIES,
        euai:SYSTEMIC_RISK_THRESHOLD,
        euai:TRANSPARENCY_RELATED_REQUIREMENTS,
        euai:VERY_LARGE_ONLINE_PLATFORM ;
    euai:triggers euai:OPEN_SOURCE_EXCEPTION,
        euai:QUALIFIED_ALERT .

euai:UNION_HARMONISATION_LEGISLATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "UNION HARMONISATION LEGISLATION"@en ;
    skos:definition "**Union Harmonisation Legislation** refers to an established framework of European Union legislative acts designed to govern product safety across a wide range of sectors. This collection of existing rules—which includes specific regulations and directives such as Regulation (EC) No 300/2008, Regulation (EU) No 167/2013, and Directive 2014/90/EU—covers a diverse array of products, including machinery, toys, and medical devices. Much of this legislation is rooted in the \"New Legislative Framework"@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ANNEX_I,
        euai:RECITAL_49 .

euai:HARMONISED_RULES a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "HARMONISED RULES"@en ;
    skos:definition """"Harmonised Rules" refer to a unified body of regulations designed to govern artificial intelligence (AI) systems. These rules establish a comprehensive framework of duties and requirements imposed upon operators to ensure that AI systems are trustworthy, consistent, and safe when placed on the market, put into service, or utilized.

By mandating these uniform obligations, the Harmonised Rules aim to facilitate the proper functioning of the internal market while simultaneously safeguarding cruci"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:AI_SYSTEM,
        euai:ARTICLE_114,
        euai:ARTICLE_114_TFEU,
        euai:ARTICLE_16_TFEU,
        euai:EUROPEAN_DATA_PROTECTION_BOARD .

euai:AI_OFFICE a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Authority ;
    rdfs:label "AI OFFICE"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **AI Office** is an EU-level body established by the Commission to serve as a central authority for the implementation, supervision, and enforcement of the EU AI Act. Functioning as the Commission’s primary enforcement arm—and effectively synonymous with the Commission’s administrative role in this context—the AI Office is dedicated to developing Union-level expertise in artificial intelligence and ensuring consistent application of AI law.

The core mission of the AI Office centers on the s"""@en ;
    euai:conductsEvaluationOf euai:EVALUATION_OF_GPAI_MODEL,
        euai:GPAI_MODEL_PROVIDER ;
    euai:cooperatesWith euai:CIVIL_SOCIETY,
        euai:INDEPENDENT_EXPERT,
        euai:NATIONAL_COMPETENT_AUTHORITY,
        euai:SCIENTIFIC_COMMUNITY ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_3_47_,
        euai:ARTICLE_62,
        euai:ARTICLE_64 ;
    euai:enforces euai:PROVIDER_OF_GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL,
        euai:RISK_MITIGATION_MEASURES ;
    euai:hasObligation euai:AWARENESS_COMMUNICATION_CAMPAIGNS,
        euai:BEST_PRACTICE_EVALUATION_IN_PROCUREMENT,
        euai:DEVELOPMENT_OF_INFORMATION_PLATFORM,
        euai:PROVISION_OF_STANDARDISED_TEMPLATES ;
    euai:providesInstructionsTo euai:FUNDAMENTAL_RIGHTS_IMPACT_ASSESSMENT ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ACADEMIA,
        euai:AI_REGULATORY_SANDBOX,
        euai:ANNEX_III,
        euai:ARTICLE_5,
        euai:ARTICLE_50,
        euai:ARTICLE_93,
        euai:ARTICLE_94,
