euai:TRANSPARENCY_OBLIGATION a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "TRANSPARENCY OBLIGATION"@en ;
    skos:definition """The **Transparency Obligation** constitutes a regulatory framework designed to ensure that artificial intelligence (AI) systems operate with openness, accountability, and clarity. This mandate, primarily defined by the requirements set forth in Article 50, ensures that providers, deployers, and operators of AI systems fulfill specific duties to maintain public trust and protect fundamental rights.

At its core, the Transparency Obligation requires that AI systems be sufficiently documented, expl"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:ACCESSIBILITY_REQUIREMENTS,
        euai:AISYSTEM .

euai:ARTICLE_2 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Article ;
    rdfs:label "ARTICLE 2"@en ;
    skos:definition """**Article 2** serves as a foundational provision within the EU AI Act, primarily dedicated to defining the regulation’s scope and establishing its jurisdictional boundaries. By delineating who is subject to the Act, Article 2 ensures clarity regarding the obligations of various stakeholders within the AI ecosystem.

At its core, Article 2 specifies the scope of the Regulation by identifying the key entities it governs, including providers, deployers, importers, and distributors of AI systems. It"""@en ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:DEPLOYER,
        euai:DISTRIBUTOR,
        euai:IMPORTER,
        euai:PROVIDER .

euai:CONFORMITY_ASSESSMENT a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:Obligation ;
    rdfs:label "CONFORMITY ASSESSMENT"@en ;
    skos:definition """Conformity Assessment is a critical mandatory procedure within the framework of the EU AI Act designed to verify and demonstrate that high-risk AI systems meet all prescribed regulatory requirements. This procedural requirement must be satisfied before a high-risk AI system is placed on the market or put into service, and it is also required following any substantial modification to the system.

The core purpose of Conformity Assessment is to ensure that the obligations set out in the AI Act—spe"""@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_43,
        euai:CHAPTER_III__SECTION_2 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:REGULATION_ON_HORIZONTAL_CYBERSECURITY_REQUIREMENTS_FOR_PRODUCTS_WITH_DIGITAL_ELEMENTS .

euai:GENERAL_PURPOSE_AI_MODEL a owl:NamedIndividual,
        euai:AISystem ;
    rdfs:label "GENERAL-PURPOSE AI MODEL"@en ;
    skos:definition "A General-Purpose AI (GPAI) model is defined as an AI model that displays significant generality and is capable of competently performing a wide range of distinct tasks, regardless of the manner in which it is placed on the market. These models are typically trained with large amounts of data using self-supervision at scale and can be integrated into a variety of downstream systems or applications. Notably, GPAI models serve as the foundational architecture upon which many other AI systems are b"@en ;
    euai:definedInArticle euai:ARTICLE_3,
        euai:RECITALS_106_110,
        euai:RECITAL_97 ;
    euai:isExemptFromHighRisk euai:RESEARCH_AND_PROTOTYPING_EXCLUSION ;
    euai:regulatedBy euai:CHAPTER_V__SECTIONS_2_AND_3 ;
    euai:relatedTo euai:CAPABILITY_BENCHMARK,
        euai:COMMON_SPECIFICATIONS,
        euai:COMPLIANCE_OBLIGATION,
        euai:COMPLIANCE_WITH_THE_REGULATION,
